{"title_page": "Battle of Tinian", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|partof = the [[Mariana and Palau Islands campaign]] of the [[Pacific War|Pacific Theater]] ([[World War II]])\n|conflict = Battle of Tinian\n|campaign = Marianas and Palaus\n|colour_scheme = background:#ffccaa\n| image = Marines wading ashore on Tinian.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n|caption = U.S. Marines wading ashore on Tinian.\n|date = 24 July&nbsp;\u2013 1 August 1944\n|place = [[Tinian]], [[Mariana Islands]]\n|result = American victory\n|combatant1 = {{flag|United States|1912}}\n|combatant2 = {{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|commander1 = {{flagicon|US|1912}} [[Harry Schmidt (USMC)|Harry Schmidt]]<br>{{flagicon|US|1912}} [[Richmond K. Turner]]<br>{{flagicon|US|1912}} [[Thomas E. Watson (USMC)|Thomas E. Watson]]<br>{{flagicon|US|1912}} [[Clifton B. Cates]]\n|commander2 = {{flagicon|Empire of Japan|army}} [[Kiyochi Ogata]]{{KIA}}<br/> {{flagicon|Empire of Japan|naval}} [[Kakuji Kakuta]]{{KIA}}<br/>{{flagicon|Empire of Japan|naval}} [[Goichi Oya]]{{KIA}}\n|units1={{flagicon|United States|marines}} [[V Amphibious Corps]]\n*[[2nd Marine Division (United States)|2nd Marine Division]]\n*[[4th Marine Division (United States)|4th Marine Division]]\n*[[147th Infantry Regiment (United States)|147th Infantry Regiment]]\n*[[Underwater Demolition Team|UDT 5, UDT 6, UDT 7]]\n\n''Additional Support units''\n|units2={{flagicon|Empire of Japan|army}} [[Thirty-First Army (Japan)|31st Army]]\n*29th Infantry Division\n**50th Inf. Regiment\n\n''Additional Support units''\n|strength1 = 41,364 Marines<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|34}}\n|strength2 = 8,039<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|89}}\n|casualties1 = 326 killed<br/>1,593 wounded<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|88}}\n|casualties2 = 5,542 killed<br/>252 captured<br/>Remainder (2,265) missing<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|88}}\n|casualties3 = Up to 4,000 Japanese civilians killed (including many suicides)<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|89}}\n|campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Marianas and Palaus}}\n}}\n[[File:Marines mopping up Tinian Island.jpg|thumb|Marines mopping up Tinian Island]]\n[[File:Japanese tank knocked out of action - Tinian.jpg|right|thumb|Marines check out a Japanese tank knocked out of action.]]\n[[File:Badly battered Japanese plane.jpg|thumb|A wrecked Japanese plane in a hangar on Tinian Island, 30 July 1944]]\n\nThe '''Battle of Tinian''' was a battle of the [[Pacific War|Pacific campaign]] of [[World War II]], fought on the island of [[Tinian]] in the [[Mariana Islands]] from 24 July until 1 August 1944. The 8,000-man Japanese garrison was eliminated, and the island joined [[Saipan]] and [[Guam]] as a base for the [[Twentieth Air Force]].<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|72}}\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Map of the Battle of Tinian (1944).svg|thumb|right|Map of the battle]]\n\nA two-prong attack through the Central Pacific and the Philippines was adopted at the 1943 [[Cairo Conference]].<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|8}} Operation Granite II, was a [[U.S. Navy]] devised strategy of [[Leapfrogging (strategy)|island hopping]], calling for the seizure of Saipan, Tinian and Guam.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|8}} The Gilbert and [[Marshall Islands]] had been seized by the summer of 1944, while some Japanese garrisons were left to starve.<ref name=Rottman>{{cite book |last1= Rottman |first1= Gordon L. |first2= Howard |last2= Gerrard |lastauthoramp= yes |title= Saipan & Tinian 1944: Piercing the Japanese Empire |location= Oxford |publisher= Osprey Publishing |year= 2004 |isbn= 1841768049}}</ref>{{rp|7}} Following the conclusion of the [[Battle of Saipan]] on 9 July, the US began preparations for attacking nearby Tinian.\n\nTinian was part of Japan's [[South Pacific Mandate]]. By June 1944, it had a population of 15,700 Japanese civilians, including 2,700 ethnic Koreans and 22 ethnic [[Chamorro people|Chamorro]].\n\nThe Japanese defending the island, the 50th Infantry Regiment, which was originally part of 29th Division, were commanded by [[Colonel]] [[Kiyochi Ogata]]<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|31}}. On May 12, 1943, there were also 2,349 Marines of the 3rd Special Forces Unit (\u7b2c 3 \u7279\u5225 \u6839 \u5730 \u968a, Dai-3 Tokubetsu Konkyochitai) and 950 marines of the 56th Naval Guards, who had been transferred there from Truk. These soldiers were under the command of [[Captain (United States O-6)|Kaigun-Taisa]] [[Goichi Oya]]. The naval forces took over the defense of the airfields, as they belonged to the facilities of naval aviation. The Japanese naval Troops also took over all the heavy artillery guns around the airfields and the 39 heavy anti-aircraft guns, which were set up directly around the slopes. In addition, there were construction crews, flight technicians and staff, so that a total of about 4,110 soldiers of various units defended the airfields. Vice-Admiral [[Kakuji Kakuta]], commander of [[1st Air Fleet (Imperial Japanese Navy)|First Air Fleet]], was headquartered in Manila, but on Tinian on an inspection tour when the invasion started. Kakuta exercised no command authority over the army troops on the island, and also the naval troops were not subject to his direct command.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|31}}<ref>{{cite web |last= Klemen |first= L. |url= http://www.dutcheastindies.webs.com/kakuta.html |title= Rear-Admiral Kakaji Kakuta |date= 1999\u20132000 |work= Forgotten Campaign: The Dutch East Indies Campaign 1941\u20131942 |access-date= 1 June 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120325051012/http://www.dutcheastindies.webs.com/kakuta.html |archive-date= 25 March 2012 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe US naval bombardment commenced on 16 July, with three battleships, five cruisers and sixteen destroyers.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|75}}  The battleship {{USS|Colorado|BB-45|2}} and the destroyer {{USS|Norman Scott|DD-690|2}} were both hit by 150mm Japanese [[shore batteries]]. ''Colorado'' was hit 22 times, killing 43 men and wounding 198. ''Norman Scott'' was hit six times, killing the captain, Seymore Owens, and 18 of his seamen, plus wounding 47.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|76}}\n\n==Battle==\nThe [[U.S. 4th Marine Division|4th Marine Division]] landed on 24 July 1944, supported by [[naval bombardment]] and marine artillery firing across the strait from Saipan.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|72}} With the help of [[Seabee]] ingenuity the Marines were able to land along the Northwest coast with its two small beaches and low coral.\n.<ref>https://seabeemuseum.wordpress.com/tag/doodlebug/</ref>  The rest of the island had coral cliffs up to 15 feet in height at the waters edge negating any assault plans.  Commodore Paul J. Halloran (CEC) CB theater commander provided drawings of a conceptual landing ramp for the 18th and  121st CBs to fabricate.<ref name= \"Doodlebug\"/>   They mounted steel beams salvaged from Saipan's abandoned [[sugar mill]] on [[Landing Vehicle Tracked|LVT]]-2s to create a portable assault ramps. If they worked they would allow the Marines to outflank Tinian's prepared defenses.  The General Schmidt was skeptical and ordered that the ramps be put through a 100-vehicle use test.   The Seabee creation was named a Doodlebug.<ref name= \"Doodlebug\"/>   It worked exactly as the Marines had hoped.<ref name= \"Doodlebug\">The Doodlebug, Naval History and Heritage Command, U.S. Navy Seabee Museum webpage, Port Hueneme, Ca, [https://www.history.navy.mil/content/history/museums/seabee/explore/online-reading-room/seabee-faqs/the-doodlebugs.html]</ref> A successful feint for the major settlement of Tinian Town diverted defenders from the actual landing site on the north of the island.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|76}} They withstood a series of night counterattacks supported by tanks, and the [[U.S. 2nd Marine Division|2nd Marine Division]] landed the next day.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|80}}\n[[File: Saipan flamethrower.jpg|thumb|\nOne of the \"Satan\" [[M3 Stuart]]s brought over from Saipan.]]\n\nAnother piece of Seabee handiwork was brought across from Saipan.  The 24 \"Satan\" mechanized flamethrowers that General Smith USMC had requested from the \n[[Seabees in World War II|Army's CWS Flame Tank Group]] in Hawaii. The terrain on Tinian was much more conducive to their use than Saipan. <ref>The Fires of Hell,Tank Encyclopedia online, Mark Nash, 2018,tank.encylopedia@gmail </ref>  Saipan and Tinian served as a training grounds for the tank crews and proving grounds for the Corps.\n\n\nThe weather worsened on 28 July, damaging the pontoon causeways, and interrupting the unloading of supplies.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|81}} By 29 July, the Americans had captured half the island, and on 30 July, the 4th Marine Division occupied Tinian Town and Airfield No. 4.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|81}}\n\nJapanese remnants made a final stand in the caves and ravines of a limestone ridge on the south portion of the island, making probes and counterattacks into the Marine line.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|85}} Resistance continued through 3 August, with some civilians murdered by the Japanese.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|87}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nBy 10 August 1944, 13,000 Japanese civilians were interned, but up to 4,000 were dead through suicide, murdered by Japanese troops, or killed in combat.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|89}}\nThe garrison on [[Aguijan]] Island off the southwest cape of Tinian, commanded by Lieutenant Kinichi Yamada, held out until the end of the war, surrendering on 4 September 1945. The last [[Japanese holdout|holdout]] on Tinian, Murata Susumu, was captured in 1953.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.wanpela.com/holdouts/registry.html |work= No Surrender Japanese Holdouts |title= Registry}}</ref>\n\nAfter the battle, Tinian became an important base for further [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] operations in the Pacific campaign. Camps were built for 50,000 troops. Fifteen thousand Seabees turned the island into the busiest airfield of the war, with six {{convert|2400|m|ft|order=flip|adj=on}} runways for attacks by [[United States Army Air Forces]] [[B-29 Superfortress]] [[bombers]] on enemy targets in the [[Philippines]], the [[Ryukyu Islands]], and mainland [[Japan]], including the [[Bombing of Tokyo (10 March 1945)|March 9/10 1945 ''Operation Meetinghouse'' firebombing of Tokyo]] and the [[atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|atomic bombings]] of [[Hiroshima]] and [[Nagasaki]].<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|89}} [[North Field (Tinian)|North Field]] was built over Airfields No. 1 and 3, and became operational in February 1945, while [[West Field (Tinian)|West Field]] was built over Airfield No. 2, and became operational in March 1945.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|89}}\n\nFour 1,000-bed hospitals (110,111,112,113) were planned and located in preparation for the [[invasion of Japan]]. None were actually built, as the [[Surrender of Japan|Japanese surrendered]] after the atomic bombs were dropped, which thus ended the need for the hospitals.\n\n==See also==\n* [[North Field (Tinian)]]\n* [[West Field (Tinian)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last= Harwood |first= Richard |title= A Close Encounter: The Marine Landing on Tinian |editor-first= Benis M. |editor-last= Frank |publisher= [[United States Marine Corps]] |location= Washington, D.C. |year= 1994 |id= 19000312700 |series= World War II Commemorative Series |url= http://www.marines.mil/News/Publications/ELECTRONICLIBRARY/ElectronicLibraryDisplay/tabid/13082/Article/125276/a-close-encounter-the-marine-landing-on-tinian-pt-1.aspx |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081211035023/http://www.marines.mil/news/publications/Pages/A%20CLOSE%20ENCOUNTER%20%20MARINE%20LANDING%20TINIAN.aspx |archivedate= 11 December 2008 | url-status= dead}}\n*{{cite book |url= http://www.history.army.mil/brochures/westpac/westpac.htm |series= U.S. Army Campaigns of World War II |title= Western Pacific |publisher= [[United States Army Center of Military History]] |id= CMH Pub 72-29}}\n*{{cite web |url= http://ww2db.com/battle_spec.php?battle_id=10 |work= World War II Database |title= Mariana Islands Campaign and the Great Turkey Shoot}}\n*{{cite book |first= Carl W. |last= Hoffman |url= http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USMC/USMC-M-Tinian/index.html |series= USMC Historical Monograph |title= The Seizure of Tinian |via= HyperWar Foundation}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Battle of Tinian}}\n*{{YouTube|id=FiQUCxbHgnI|title=Battle for the Mariana Islands}}\n\n{{coord|15|00|N|145|38|E|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tinian}}\n[[Category:Pacific Ocean theatre of World War II|Tinian]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War II involving the United States|Tinian]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War II involving Japan|Tinian]]\n[[Category:History of the Northern Mariana Islands]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps in World War II]]\n[[Category:Amphibious operations of World War II]]\n[[Category:July 1944 events]]\n[[Category:August 1944 events]]\n[[Category:Amphibious operations involving the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|partof = the [[Mariana and Palau Islands campaign]] of the [[Pacific War|Pacific Theater]] ([[World War II]])\n|conflict = Battle of Tinian\n|campaign = Marianas and Palaus\n|colour_scheme = background:#ffccaa\n| image = Marines wading ashore on Tinian.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n|caption = U.S. Marines wading ashore on Tinian.\n|date = 24 July&nbsp;\u2013 1 August 1944\n|place = [[Tinian]], [[Mariana Islands]]\n|result = American victory\n|combatant1 = {{flag|United States|1912}}\n|combatant2 = {{flagcountry|Empire of Japan}}\n|commander1 = {{flagicon|US|1912}} [[Harry Schmidt (USMC)|Harry Schmidt]]<br>{{flagicon|US|1912}} [[Richmond K. Turner]]<br>{{flagicon|US|1912}} [[Thomas E. Watson (USMC)|Thomas E. Watson]]<br>{{flagicon|US|1912}} [[Clifton B. Cates]]\n|commander2 = {{flagicon|Empire of Japan|army}} [[Kiyochi Ogata]]{{KIA}}<br/> {{flagicon|Empire of Japan|naval}} [[Kakuji Kakuta]]{{KIA}}<br/>{{flagicon|Empire of Japan|naval}} [[Goichi Oya]]{{KIA}}\n|units1={{flagicon|United States|marines}} [[V Amphibious Corps]]\n*[[2nd Marine Division (United States)|2nd Marine Division]]\n*[[4th Marine Division (United States)|4th Marine Division]]\n*[[147th Infantry Regiment (United States)|147th Infantry Regiment]]\n*[[Underwater Demolition Team|UDT 5, UDT 6, UDT 7]]\n\n''Additional Support units''\n|units2={{flagicon|Empire of Japan|army}} [[Thirty-First Army (Japan)|31st Army]]\n*29th Infantry Division\n**50th Inf. Regiment\n\n''Additional Support units''\n|strength1 = 41,364 Marines<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|34}}\n|strength2 = 8,039<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|89}}\n|casualties1 = 326 killed<br/>1,593 wounded<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|88}}\n|casualties2 = 5,542 killed<br/>252 captured<br/>Remainder (2,265) missing<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|88}}\n|casualties3 = Up to 4,000 Japanese civilians killed (including many suicides)<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|89}}\n|campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Marianas and Palaus}}\n}}\n[[File:Marines mopping up Tinian Island.jpg|thumb|Marines mopping up Tinian Island]]\n[[File:Japanese tank knocked out of action - Tinian.jpg|right|thumb|Marines check out a Japanese tank knocked out of action.]]\n[[File:Badly battered Japanese plane.jpg|thumb|A wrecked Japanese plane in a hangar on Tinian Island, 30 July 1944]]\n\nThe '''Battle of Tinian''' was a battle of the [[Pacific War|Pacific campaign]] of [[World War II]], fought on the island of [[Tinian]] in the [[Mariana Islands]] from 24 July until 1 August 1944. The 8,000-man Japanese garrison was eliminated, and the island joined [[Saipan]] and [[Guam]] as a base for the [[Twentieth Air Force]].<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|72}}\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Map of the Battle of Tinian (1944).svg|thumb|right|Map of the battle]]\n\nA two-prong attack through the Central Pacific and the Philippines was adopted at the 1943 [[Cairo Conference]].<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|8}} Operation Granite II, was a [[U.S. Navy]] devised strategy of [[Leapfrogging (strategy)|island hopping]], calling for the seizure of Saipan, Tinian and Guam.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|8}} The Gilbert and [[Marshall Islands]] had been seized by the summer of 1944, while some Japanese garrisons were left to starve.<ref name=Rottman>{{cite book |last1= Rottman |first1= Gordon L. |first2= Howard |last2= Gerrard |lastauthoramp= yes |title= Saipan & Tinian 1944: Piercing the Japanese Empire |location= Oxford |publisher= Osprey Publishing |year= 2004 |isbn= 1841768049}}</ref>{{rp|7}} Following the conclusion of the [[Battle of Saipan]] on 9 July, the US began preparations for attacking nearby Tinian.\n\nTinian was part of Japan's [[South Pacific Mandate]]. By June 1944, it had a population of 15,700 Japanese civilians, including 2,700 ethnic Koreans and 22 ethnic [[Chamorro people|Chamorro]].\n\nThe Japanese defending the island, the 50th Infantry Regiment, which was originally part of 29th Division, were commanded by [[Colonel]] [[Kiyochi Ogata]]<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|31}}. On May 12, 1943, there were also 2,349 Marines of the 3rd Special Forces Unit (\u7b2c 3 \u7279\u5225 \u6839 \u5730 \u968a, Dai-3 Tokubetsu Konkyochitai) and 950 marines of the 56th Naval Guards, who had been transferred there from Truk. These soldiers were under the command of [[Captain (United States O-6)|Kaigun-Taisa]] [[Goichi Oya]]. The naval forces took over the defense of the airfields, as they belonged to the facilities of naval aviation. The Japanese naval Troops also took over all the heavy artillery guns around the airfields and the 39 heavy anti-aircraft guns, which were set up directly around the slopes. In addition, there were construction crews, flight technicians and staff, so that a total of about 4,110 soldiers of various units defended the airfields. Vice-Admiral [[Kakuji Kakuta]], commander of [[1st Air Fleet (Imperial Japanese Navy)|First Air Fleet]], was headquartered in Manila, but on Tinian on an inspection tour when the invasion started. Kakuta exercised no command authority over the army troops on the island, and also the naval troops were not subject to his direct command.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|31}}<ref>{{cite web |last= Klemen |first= L. |url= http://www.dutcheastindies.webs.com/kakuta.html |title= Rear-Admiral Kakaji Kakuta |date= 1999\u20132000 |work= Forgotten Campaign: The Dutch East Indies Campaign 1941\u20131942 |access-date= 1 June 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120325051012/http://www.dutcheastindies.webs.com/kakuta.html |archive-date= 25 March 2012 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe US naval bombardment commenced on 16 July, with three battleships, five cruisers and sixteen destroyers.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|75}}  The battleship {{USS|Colorado|BB-45|2}} and the destroyer {{USS|Norman Scott|DD-690|2}} were both hit by 150mm Japanese [[shore batteries]]. ''Colorado'' was hit 22 times, killing 43 men and wounding 198. ''Norman Scott'' was hit six times, killing the captain, Seymore Owens, and 18 of his seamen, plus wounding 47.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|76}}\n\n==Battle==\nThe [[U.S. 4th Marine Division|4th Marine Division]] landed on 24 July 1944, supported by [[naval bombardment]] and marine artillery firing across the strait from Saipan.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|72}} With the help of [[Seabee]] ingenuity the Marines were able to land along the Northwest coast with its two small beaches and low coral.\n.<ref>https://seabeemuseum.wordpress.com/tag/doodlebug/</ref>  The rest of the island had coral cliffs up to 15 feet in height at the waters edge negating any assault plans.  Commodore Paul J. Halloran (CEC) CB theater commander provided drawings of a conceptual landing ramp for the 18th and  121st CBs to fabricate.<ref name= \"Doodlebug\"/>   They mounted steel beams salvaged from Saipan's abandoned [[sugar mill]] on [[Landing Vehicle Tracked|LVT]]-2s to create a portable assault ramps. If they worked they would allow the Marines to outflank Tinian's prepared defenses.  The General Smith was skeptical and ordered that the ramps be put through a 100-vehicle use test.   The Seabee creation was named a Doodlebug.<ref name= \"Doodlebug\"/>   It worked exactly as the Marines had hoped.<ref name= \"Doodlebug\">The Doodlebug, Naval History and Heritage Command, U.S. Navy Seabee Museum webpage, Port Hueneme, Ca, [https://www.history.navy.mil/content/history/museums/seabee/explore/online-reading-room/seabee-faqs/the-doodlebugs.html]</ref> A successful feint for the major settlement of Tinian Town diverted defenders from the actual landing site on the north of the island.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|76}} They withstood a series of night counterattacks supported by tanks, and the [[U.S. 2nd Marine Division|2nd Marine Division]] landed the next day.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|80}}\n[[File: Saipan flamethrower.jpg|thumb|\nOne of the \"Satan\" [[M3 Stuart]]s brought over from Saipan.]]\n\nAnother piece of Seabee handiwork was brought across from Saipan.  The 24 \"Satan\" mechanized flamethrowers that General Smith USMC had requested from the \n[[Seabees in World War II|Army's CWS Flame Tank Group]] in Hawaii. The terrain on Tinian was much more conducive to their use than Saipan. <ref>The Fires of Hell,Tank Encyclopedia online, Mark Nash, 2018,tank.encylopedia@gmail </ref>  Saipan and Tinian served as a training grounds for the tank crews and proving grounds for the Corps.\n\n\nThe weather worsened on 28 July, damaging the pontoon causeways, and interrupting the unloading of supplies.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|81}} By 29 July, the Americans had captured half the island, and on 30 July, the 4th Marine Division occupied Tinian Town and Airfield No. 4.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|81}}\n\nJapanese remnants made a final stand in the caves and ravines of a limestone ridge on the south portion of the island, making probes and counterattacks into the Marine line.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|85}} Resistance continued through 3 August, with some civilians murdered by the Japanese.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|87}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nBy 10 August 1944, 13,000 Japanese civilians were interned, but up to 4,000 were dead through suicide, murdered by Japanese troops, or killed in combat.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|89}}\nThe garrison on [[Aguijan]] Island off the southwest cape of Tinian, commanded by Lieutenant Kinichi Yamada, held out until the end of the war, surrendering on 4 September 1945. The last [[Japanese holdout|holdout]] on Tinian, Murata Susumu, was captured in 1953.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.wanpela.com/holdouts/registry.html |work= No Surrender Japanese Holdouts |title= Registry}}</ref>\n\nAfter the battle, Tinian became an important base for further [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] operations in the Pacific campaign. Camps were built for 50,000 troops. Fifteen thousand Seabees turned the island into the busiest airfield of the war, with six {{convert|2400|m|ft|order=flip|adj=on}} runways for attacks by [[United States Army Air Forces]] [[B-29 Superfortress]] [[bombers]] on enemy targets in the [[Philippines]], the [[Ryukyu Islands]], and mainland [[Japan]], including the [[Bombing of Tokyo (10 March 1945)|March 9/10 1945 ''Operation Meetinghouse'' firebombing of Tokyo]] and the [[atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|atomic bombings]] of [[Hiroshima]] and [[Nagasaki]].<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|89}} [[North Field (Tinian)|North Field]] was built over Airfields No. 1 and 3, and became operational in February 1945, while [[West Field (Tinian)|West Field]] was built over Airfield No. 2, and became operational in March 1945.<ref name=Rottman/>{{rp|89}}\n\nFour 1,000-bed hospitals (110,111,112,113) were planned and located in preparation for the [[invasion of Japan]]. None were actually built, as the [[Surrender of Japan|Japanese surrendered]] after the atomic bombs were dropped, which thus ended the need for the hospitals.\n\n==See also==\n* [[North Field (Tinian)]]\n* [[West Field (Tinian)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last= Harwood |first= Richard |title= A Close Encounter: The Marine Landing on Tinian |editor-first= Benis M. |editor-last= Frank |publisher= [[United States Marine Corps]] |location= Washington, D.C. |year= 1994 |id= 19000312700 |series= World War II Commemorative Series |url= http://www.marines.mil/News/Publications/ELECTRONICLIBRARY/ElectronicLibraryDisplay/tabid/13082/Article/125276/a-close-encounter-the-marine-landing-on-tinian-pt-1.aspx |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081211035023/http://www.marines.mil/news/publications/Pages/A%20CLOSE%20ENCOUNTER%20%20MARINE%20LANDING%20TINIAN.aspx |archivedate= 11 December 2008 | url-status= dead}}\n*{{cite book |url= http://www.history.army.mil/brochures/westpac/westpac.htm |series= U.S. Army Campaigns of World War II |title= Western Pacific |publisher= [[United States Army Center of Military History]] |id= CMH Pub 72-29}}\n*{{cite web |url= http://ww2db.com/battle_spec.php?battle_id=10 |work= World War II Database |title= Mariana Islands Campaign and the Great Turkey Shoot}}\n*{{cite book |first= Carl W. |last= Hoffman |url= http://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/USMC/USMC-M-Tinian/index.html |series= USMC Historical Monograph |title= The Seizure of Tinian |via= HyperWar Foundation}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Battle of Tinian}}\n*{{YouTube|id=FiQUCxbHgnI|title=Battle for the Mariana Islands}}\n\n{{coord|15|00|N|145|38|E|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tinian}}\n[[Category:Pacific Ocean theatre of World War II|Tinian]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War II involving the United States|Tinian]]\n[[Category:Battles of World War II involving Japan|Tinian]]\n[[Category:History of the Northern Mariana Islands]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps in World War II]]\n[[Category:Amphibious operations of World War II]]\n[[Category:July 1944 events]]\n[[Category:August 1944 events]]\n[[Category:Amphibious operations involving the United States]]\n", "name