 - Dec 8, 2007 || ''[[White Christmas (musical)|Irving Berlin's White Christmas]]'' || Martha Watson || [[Edinburgh Playhouse]], [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]]\n|-\n| Dec 13, 2007 - Jan 12, 2008 || ''[[White Christmas (musical)|Irving Berlin's White Christmas]]'' || Martha Watson || [[Wales Millennium Centre]], [[Cardiff]], [[Wales]]\n|-\n| Nov 29, 2008 - Jan 4, 2009 || ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' || [[Wicked Witch of the West]] || [[The Lowry]], [[Manchester]], England\n|-\n| Feb 2, 2009 - Apr 11, 2009 || ''[[Pack of Lies]]'' || Helen Kroger || UK National Tour\n|-\n| Nov 3, 2009 - Jan 10, 2010 || ''[[White Christmas (musical)|Irving Berlin's White Christmas]]'' || Martha Watson || US National Tour\n|-\n| Nov 16, 2011 - Dec 24, 2011 || ''[[White Christmas (musical)|White Christmas]]'' || Martha Watson || [[Paper Mill Playhouse]], [[Millburn, New Jersey]]\n|-\n| Apr 28, 2015 || ''[[Follies]]'' || Hattie Walker || [[Royal Albert Hall]], London, England\n|-\n| Nov 12, 2016 - Jan 1, 2017 || ''[[White Christmas (musical)|Irving Berlin's White Christmas]]'' || Martha Watson || US National Tour\n|-\n| Nov 24, 2017 - Dec 31, 2017 || ''[[Holiday Inn (musical)|Holiday Inn]]'' || Louise Badger || [[5th Avenue Theatre]], [[Seattle|Seattle, Washington]]\n|-\n| Nov 9, 2019 - Dec 29, 2019 || ''[[White Christmas (musical)Irving Berlin's White Christmas]]'' || Martha Watson || US National Tour\n|-\n|}\n\n==Published works==\n* {{Cite book |last=Luft |first=Lorna |year= 1998 |title= Me and My Shadows: A Family Memoir |publisher= Simon & Schuster |isbn=978-0671019006}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Luft |first=Lorna |year= 2018 |title= A Star Is Born: Judy Garland and the Film That Got Away |publisher= Running Press |isbn=978-0762464807}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Lorna Luft}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051026183701/http://www.lornaluft.com/ Official website]\n* [https://www.myspace.com/lornaluft Lorna Luft] at MySpace\n* {{IMDb name|5167}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|16249}}\n* [http://www.broadwayworld.com/viewcolumn.cfm?colid=29791 July 2008 interview with Lorna Luft] on BroadwayWorld.com\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Luft, Lorna}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Santa Monica, California]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:People with cancer]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStage productions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lorna_Luft"}
{"title_page": "Homosexuality and Methodism", "text_new": "{{Christianity and sexual orientation}}\n{{Methodism}}\n\n'''Methodist viewpoints concerning homosexuality''' are diverse because there is no one [[Christian denomination|denomination]] which represents all Methodists. The [[World Methodist Council]], which represents most Methodist denominations, has no official statements regarding sexuality. [[Methodist Church of Great Britain|British Methodism]] holds a variety of views, and permits ministers to bless same-gender marriages.<ref name=\"Church Times\">{{cite web|last1=Drake|first1=Gavin|title=Methodists may bless but not marry same-sex couples|url=http://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2014/11-july/news/uk/methodists-may-bless-but-not-marry-same-sex-couples|website=www.churchtimes.co.uk|publisher=Church Times|accessdate=November 30, 2015}}</ref> American Methodism concentrates on the position that the [[homosexuality|same-sex]] relations are incompatible with \"Christian teaching\", but extends ministry to persons of a homosexual orientation, holding that all individuals are of sacred worth.<ref name=\"UMC - Sexuality\">{{cite web|url=http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?mid=1728|title=Human Sexuality|publisher=The United Methodist Church|accessdate=2008-05-16}}</ref><ref name=\"FMC - Christian Conduct\">{{cite web|url=http://www.freemethodistchurch.org/Sections/About%20Us/Beliefs/Christian%20Life/Christian%20Conduct/Christian%20Conduct%203.htm|title=The Christian Life - Christian Conduct|publisher=Free Methodist Church|accessdate=2008-05-16|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513181703/http://www.freemethodistchurch.org/Sections/About%20Us/Beliefs/Christian%20Life/Christian%20Conduct/Christian%20Conduct%203.htm|archivedate=2008-05-13}}</ref><ref name=\"UMC - British Methodists reject blessing of same-sex relationships\">{{cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/site/c.gjJTJbMUIuE/b.1827285/k.B985/British_Methodists_reject_blessing_of_samesex_relationships.htm|title=British Methodists reject blessing of same-sex relationships|publisher=The United Methodist Church|accessdate=2007-05-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914134747/http://www.umc.org/site/c.gjJTJbMUIuE/b.1827285/k.B985/British_Methodists_reject_blessing_of_samesex_relationships.htm|archive-date=2016-09-14|url-status=dead}}</ref> The following denominations are members of the World Methodist Council.\n\n==African Methodist Episcopal Church==\nThe [[African Methodist Episcopal Church]] does not approve of the ordination of openly gay persons to the ranks of the [[clergy]] in the Church.<ref name=\"HRC - Stances of Faiths on LGBT Issues: African Methodist Episcopal Church\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hrc.org/issues/4957.htm|title=Stances of Faiths on LGBT Issues: African Methodist Episcopal Church|publisher=The Human Rights Campaign|accessdate=2009-11-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091121220941/http://www.hrc.org/issues/4957.htm|archive-date=2009-11-21|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, there is no official prohibition at this time against ordination. In a historic decision, which marked the first vote on the issue of marriage rights for same-sex couples by a predominantly African-American denomination, the African Methodist Episcopal Church unanimously voted to forbid ministers from [[Blessing of same-sex unions in Christian churches|blessing same-sex unions]] in July 2004.<ref name=\"HRC - Stances of Faiths on LGBT Issues: African Methodist Episcopal Church\"/><ref name=\"Washington Post - Gay Blacks Feeling Strained Church Ties\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A17057-2004Nov1.html|title=Gay Blacks Feeling Strained Church Ties|publisher=The Human Rights Campaign|accessdate=2009-11-25 | first=Darryl | last=Fears | date=2004-11-02}}</ref> The church leaders stated that homosexual activity \"clearly contradicts [their] understanding of Scripture.\"<ref name=\"HRC - Stances of Faiths on LGBT Issues: African Methodist Episcopal Church\"/> Although the AME prohibits its ministers from officiating at same-sex weddings, the AME has \"chosen to offer no official policy statements on homosexuality.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Trauma, Stress, and Resilience Among Sexual Minority Women: Rising Like the Phoenix|last=Balsam|first=Kimberly|publisher=Routledge|year=2012|isbn=|location=New York|pages=115|quote=|via=}}</ref>  As it has no official policy on ordination, some openly gay clergy have been ordained in the AME.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hahn|first1=Heather|title=Gay pastor's removal brings sadness, defiance|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/gay-pastors-removal-brings-sadness-defiance|website=www.umc.org|publisher=United Methodist Church|accessdate=November 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Allegheny Wesleyan Methodist Connection==\nThe [[Allegheny Wesleyan Methodist Connection]], in its ''Discipline'', teaches in \u00b644:<ref name=\"AWMC2014\"/>\n{{quotation|Further, by observing the teaching of Scripture regarding sexual conduct. We believe that God has commanded that no intimate sexual activity be engaged in outside of marriage between a man and a woman. We believe that any form of homosexuality, lesbianism, bi-sexuality, bestiality, incest, fornication, adultery, and any attempt to alter one\u2019s gender by surgery or appearance are sinful perversions of God\u2019s gift of sex. The party guilty of such conduct has by his or her act forfeited membership in the church.<br>\nGen. 2:24; 19:5, 13; 26:8\u201310; Lev. 18:1\u201330; Rom. 1:26\u201329; 1 Cor. 5:1; 6:9; 1 Thes. 4:1\u20138; Heb. 13:4.<ref name=\"AWMC2014\">{{cite book|title=The Discipline of the Allegheny Wesleyan Methodist Connection (Original Allegheny Conference)|year=2014|publisher=[[Allegheny Wesleyan Methodist Connection]]|location=[[Salem, Ohio|Salem]]|language=English|page=21, 125}}</ref>}}\n\u00b6340 outlines the consequences for clergymen engaged in homosexual activity:<ref name=\"AWMC2014\"/>\n{{quotation|When an elder or a minister shall have been convicted of the crime of fornication, adultery, or homosexual activity, he or she shall be expelled from the Connection and shall never be restored to membership in the Connection; and the Connection shall not receive from any church anyone who has been convicted of these crimes after entering the ministry. But this shall not prohibit membership in an Allegheny Wesleyan Methodist church when the guilty person repents.<ref name=\"AWMC2014\"/>}}\n\n== Argentine Evangelical Methodist Church ==\nThe church, also called the [[Evangelical Methodist Church in Argentina]], allows each congregation to make its own position. The church has stated that they have \"given, on a national level, freedom so that each congregation accompany...these couples. We permit freedom of action in order to bless them\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elciudadanoweb.com/hay-libertad-para-acompanar-a-las-parejas-homosexuales/|title=Hay libertad para acompa\u00f1ar a las parejas homosexuales |website=Diario El Ciudadano y la Gente|access-date=2016-05-26}}</ref>\n\n== Bible Methodist Connection of Churches ==\nThe [[Bible Methodist Connection of Churches]], in its ''Discipline'', states in \u00b642 that:\n{{quotation|We believe that God has given to us the gift of sexuality which may be exercised only within the boundaries of covenanted, monogamous, heterosexual marriage. Sexual relationships outside of marriage and sexual relationships between persons of the same sex are immoral and sinful. Thus, we condemn homosexuality, lesbianism, pederasty, bisexuality, bestiality, incest, pedophilia, fornication, adultery, pornography, and other forms of licentiousness as sinful perversions of the divine gift of sexuality. We believe that God disapproves of and forbids any attempt to alter one\u2019s gender by surgery or appearance.<ref name=\"BMC2014\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.biblemethodist.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/2014-Bible-Methodist-Discipline.pdf|title=Discipline of the Bible Methodist Connection of Churches|year=2014|publisher=General Conference of the Bible Methodist Connection of Churches}}</ref>}}\nIn \u00b644, it further states that:\n{{quotation|No practicing homosexual/lesbian shall be ordained as a minister or missionary or shall be used as a teacher, office holder or other employee in any of our ministries. They shall not be eligible to be members, lay leaders, or ministerial leaders in our churches. If any of the aforementioned persons or office holders practice this lifestyle, they forfeit their right to any office or membership in our churches. Practicing this lifestyle shall constitute automatic removal from membership or office.<ref name=\"BMC2014\"/>}}\n\u00b645 of the ''Discipline of the Bible Methodist Connection of Churches'' specifically prohibits its clergymen from officiating at [[Blessing of same-sex unions in Christian churches|same-sex marriages]].<ref name=\"BMC2014\"/>\n\n== Church of the Nazarene ==\nThe [[Church of the Nazarene]], a Methodist/Holiness denomination, teaches that marriage is only defined for heterosexual couples.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nazarene.org/files/docs/Perspectives_Homosexuality.pdf|title=A Pastoral Perspective of Homosexuality|date=September 20, 2011|website=nazarene.org|publisher=Church of the Nazarene|access-date=May 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304200945/http://nazarene.org/files/docs/Perspectives_Homosexuality.pdf|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> As such, the denomination does not allow same-gender marriages.\n\n== Church of North India ==\nThe denomination, [[Uniting church|uniting]] different Protestants including Methodists, takes a traditional stand on human sexuality maintaining that marriage is defined heterosexually. The church opposes the criminalization of homosexuality, but also opposed the consecration of the first homosexual bishop in the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]], the Rt. Rev. [[Gene Robinson]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://continuingindaba.org/2013/09/18/homosexuality-an-indian-issue-in-church-and-state/|title=Homosexuality: An Indian Issue in Church and State|date=2013-09-18|website=Continuing Indaba|access-date=2016-05-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611094253/https://continuingindaba.org/2013/09/18/homosexuality-an-indian-issue-in-church-and-state/|archive-date=2016-06-11|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2009, the church both opposed the supreme court's decision to criminalize homosexuality, and also opposed same-sex marriage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/indian-supreme-court-re-criminalizes-homosexual-activity/|title=Indian Supreme Court Re-Criminalizes Homosexual Activity|website=National Catholic Register|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref>\n\n== Church of South India ==\nThe Church of South India (CSI) is a united church representing Anglicans, Methodists, and Presbyterians. The CSI \"is a relatively liberal Protestant church which has, since 1984, allowed women to become pastors. 'CSI has been liberal on these issues. It has taken up issues of gender, dalits and landlessness. It has to address the issue of sexual minorities too\"'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/kerala-rising-cases-of-sexual-abuse-within-the-church/1/151572.html|title=Rising cases of sexual abuse within the church in Kerala force clergy to rethink on homosexuality|website=indiatoday.intoday.in|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref> In 2009, the Rev. Christopher Rajkumar, speaking for the CSI, supported civil rights for gay people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1090805/jsp/frontpage/story_11322140.jsp|title=The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) {{!}} Frontpage {{!}} Protestants support gay rights|website=www.telegraphindia.com|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref> In 2015, St. Mark's Cathedral in Bangalore hosted an event challenging homophobia where the Rev. Vincent Rajkumar affirmed his support for LGBT rights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thewire.in/2015/12/09/a-theological-challenge-to-christian-homophobia-16685/|title=A Theological Challenge to Christian Homophobia|last=Sitlhou|first=Makepeace|date=2015-12-09|website=The Wire|access-date=2016-05-21|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151211203604/http://thewire.in/2015/12/09/a-theological-challenge-to-christian-homophobia-16685/|archivedate=2015-12-11}}</ref>  The BBC has listed the CSI as being among the churches open to blessing same-gender couples.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-35278124|title=Church split over homosexuality would be a failure - Welby - BBC News|website=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref>\n\n==Evangelical Methodist Church==\nThe [[Evangelical Methodist Church]] maintains that the biblical record condemns homosexuality as evidenced in [[Leviticus]] {{Bibleref2-nb|Leviticus|18:22}}, [[Epistle to the Romans|Romans]] {{Bibleref2-nb|Romans|1:26-27}}, and [[1 Corinthians]] {{Bibleref2-nb|1 Corinthians|6:9-19}}.<ref name=\"EMC-Homosexuality\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emchurch.org/main/?s=homosexuality#74|title=Handbook of the EMC|publisher=[[Evangelical Methodist Church]]|accessdate=2009-12-03}}</ref> It teaches that homosexual practices are \"[[sin]] leading to spiritual death and [[Hell in Christian beliefs|eternal punishment]].<ref name=\"EMC-Homosexuality\"/> Nevertheless, homosexuality is no greater a sin than [[adultery]], [[murder]], [[stealing]], among others.<ref name=\"EMC-Homosexuality\"/> As a result, practicing homosexuals are barred from becoming members of the [[Evangelical Methodist Church]]. Moreover, practicing homosexuals are prohibited from becoming candidates for [[Elder (Methodism)|ordained]] ministry.<ref name=\"EMC-Homosexuality\"/> The Church upholds that all individuals are entitled to certain rights and protection of the [[Civil law (legal system)|civil law]]; nevertheless, it opposes all civil legislation that supports homosexuality as a normal life style.<ref name=\"EMC-Homosexuality\"/> All homosexuals who seek faith in [[Jesus Christ]] as Saviour and Lord, and cease to practice homosexual acts are welcomed into the fellowship of the Evangelical Methodist Church.<ref name=\"EMC-Homosexuality\"/>\n\n==Evangelical Wesleyan Church==\nThe [[Evangelical Wesleyan Church]], in \u00b692.1 and \u00b692.2 of its ''Discipline'', teaches that:<ref name=\"EWC2015\">{{cite book|title=The Discipline of the Evangelical Wesleyan Church |year=2015|publisher=[[Evangelical Wesleyan Church]]|language=English|pages=64-65}}</ref>\n{{quotation|God has commanded that no intimate sexual activity be engaged in outside of a marriage between one naturally-born man and one naturally-born woman. It stands opposed to the immoral lifestyles of the day, including but not limited to homosexuality, lesbianism, transsexualism, bisexuality, bestiality, incest, fornication, adultery, pornography, polygamy, bigamy, and living together without legally being married, realizing that these are sinful perversions of God's gracious gifts to mankind. Further, it believes that God disapproves of and forbids any attempt to alter one's gender by surgery or appearance. (Gen. 2:24; Gen. 19:5, 13; Gen. 26:8-9; Lev. 18:1-30; Rom. 1:26-29; I Cor. 5:1, 6-9, I Thess. 4:1-8; Heb. 13:4.) It does not condemn the individual but rejects the practices which are condemned by the Bible as unacceptable conduct. The church believes it is a free right to publicly express this Scriptural position (Romans 1:21-27, Leviticus 18:22). Any current member who becomes engaged in such behaviors shall be considered as having voluntarily withdrawn from membership. The Evangelical Wesleyan Church, Inc., does not recognize the marriage or civil unions between persons of the same sex. All its ministers are expressly forbidden to perform a marriage ceremony between persons of the same gender. A marriage ceremony between persons of the same sex may not be performed in any Evangelical Wesleyan Church or church-related facility.<ref name=\"EWC2015\"/>}}\n\n==Free Methodist Church==\nAs stated in the ''[[Book of Discipline (disambiguation)|Book of Discipline]]'' (A/342) of the [[Free Methodist Church]], it believes and teaches that {{quote|Homosexual behavior, as all sexual deviation, is a [[perversion]] of God's [[Genesis creation myth|created order]] (Genesis 1-3). The [[Christian views of marriage|sanctity of marriage]] and the family is to be preserved against all manner of [[immoral]] conduct (Exodus 22:16-17; Deuteronomy 22:23-28; Leviticus 20:10-16), thus the Free Methodist Church does not recognize the legitimacy or participation in the practice of [[same-sex marriage]].\n\nHomosexual behavior is contrary to the will of God as clearly stated in [[Bible|Scripture]] (Leviticus 18:22; 20:13; Romans 1:26-27; 1 Corinthians 6:9-10; 1 Timothy 1:8-10).\n\nPersons with homosexual inclinations are accountable to God for their behavior (Romans 14:12).\n\nThe [[Forgiveness#Christianity|forgiving]] and [[Salvation|delivering]] [[Divine grace|grace]] of God in [[Christ]] is all-sufficient for the homosexual (1 John 1:9; Hebrews 7:25; Luke 4:18; 1 Corinthians 6:9-11).\nThe Church has a personal and corporate responsibility to be God's instrument of healing, restoring love to the homosexual seeking recovery of [[Christianity|Christian]] conduct and life-style (2 Corinthians 2:7-8).\n\nThe church opposes legislation which makes homosexual conduct or life-style legitimate.<ref name=\"FMC - Christian Conduct\"/>}}\n\n== Italian Methodist Church ==\nThe [[Union of Methodist and Waldensian Churches]], of which the [[Italian Methodist Church]] is a part of, voted in 2010 to bless same-sex relationships.<ref name=\"Italy\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcusa.org/news/2010/9/7/italian-protestants-approve-same-sex-blessings/|title=Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) - News & Announcements - Italian Protestants approve same-sex blessings|last=(U.S.A.)|first=Presbyterian Church|date=2010-09-07|website=www.pcusa.org|language=en|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref> LGBT-affirming church leaders said \"the references to homosexuality in the Bible needed to be understood taking into account issue of culture and interpretation, to avoid the danger of Biblical fundamentalism.\"<ref name=\"Italy\" />\n\n==Methodist Church of Great Britain==\nAt the annual Methodist Conference in 1993 in Derby, following long debate at all levels of the Church's life on the basis of a detailed report, the [[Methodist Church of Great Britain|British Methodist Church]] considered the issues of [[human sexuality]].<ref name=\"The Methodist Church of Great Britain- Human Sexuality\">{{cite web|url=http://www.methodist.org.uk/index.cfm?fuseaction=opentogod.content&cmid=1547 |title=Human Sexuality |publisher=The Methodist Church of Great Britain |accessdate=2008-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071023044509/http://www.methodist.org.uk/index.cfm?fuseaction=opentogod.content&cmid=1547 |archivedate=2007-10-23 }}</ref> The Derby Conference in 1993 passed a series of Resolutions which still stand. These resolutions are as follows:\n{{quote|\n1. The Conference, affirming the joy of human sexuality as God's gift and the place of every human being within the grace of God, recognises the responsibility that flows from this for us all. It therefore welcomes the serious, prayerful and sometimes costly consideration given to this issue by The Methodist Church.<br>\n2. All practices of sexuality, which are promiscuous, exploitative or demeaning in any way are unacceptable forms of behaviour and contradict God's purpose for us all.<br>\n3. A person shall not be debarred from church on the grounds of sexual orientation in itself.<br>\n4. The Conference reaffirms the traditional teaching of the Church on human sexuality; namely [[chastity]] for all outside marriage and [[fidelity]] within it. The Conference directs that this affirmation is made clear to all candidates for ministry, office and membership, and having established this, affirm that the existing procedures of our church are adequate to deal with all such cases.<br>\n5. The Conference resolves that its decision in this debate shall not be used to form the basis of a disciplinary charge against any person in relation to conduct alleged to have taken place before such decisions were made.<br>\n6. Conference recognises, affirms and celebrates the participation and ministry of lesbians and gay men in the church. Conference calls on the Methodist people to begin a pilgrimage of faith to combat repression and discrimination, to work for justice and human rights and to give dignity and worth to people whatever their sexuality.<ref name=\"The Methodist Church of Great Britain- Human Sexuality\"/>}}\n\nIn 2005, the church voted \"to offer the prospect of blessing services for same-sex couples\", but in 2006 the church voted to step back but did offer \"informal, private prayers to couples\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://outcomeonline.org.uk/?p=187|title=Methodist Church votes on same sex blessings|website=outcomeonline.org.uk|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> In 2013, the denomination initiated a consultation on blessing same-sex marriages,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/10484097/Methodist-Church-begins-mass-consultation-on-gay-marriage.html|title=Methodist Church begins mass consultation on gay marriage|website=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> and, in 2014, after same-sex marriage became legal, the Methodist Church decided in favor of allowing ministers to celebrate same-sex couples entering into civil marriages.<ref name=\"Church Times\"/> Also in 2014, \"the Conference resolved that its previous ruling that there was no reason per se to prevent anyone within the Church, ordained or lay, from entering into or remaining within a civil partnership, should also extend to those entering into legally contracted same-sex marriages\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.methodist.org.uk/news-and-events/news-releases/methodist-conference-receives-report-on-same-sex-marriage|title=Methodist Conference receives report on same-sex marriage|website=www.methodist.org.uk|access-date=2016-08-09}}</ref>\n\nThe denomination officially stated that Methodists may enter into same-sex marriages and that \"prayers of thanksgiving or celebration may be said, and there may be informal services of thanksgiving or celebration\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.methodist.org.uk/who-we-are/views-of-the-church/human-sexuality/talking-of-marriage-and-relationships/frequently-asked-questions-marriage-and-relationships|title=Frequently Asked Questions - Marriage and Relationships|website=www.methodist.org.uk|access-date=2016-07-09}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 July 2019, the [[United Kingdom|UK]] Methodist Conference voted by 247 votes to 48 to allow [[Same-sex marriage|same-sex marriages]] in UK [[Methodism|Methodist Churches.]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2019/5-july/news/uk/methodists-move-towards-conducting-same-sex-marriages|title=Methodists move towards conducting same-sex marriages|website=www.churchtimes.co.uk|access-date=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\n== Methodist Church of New Zealand ==\nThe [[Methodist Church of New Zealand]], since 2004, has approved of ordaining openly gay and lesbian ministers, and the denomination allows each local congregation to determine its own policy on the issue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=3591533|title=Methodists say yes to ordaining homosexuals|date=2004-09-15|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777|access-date=2016-04-13}}</ref> In 2013, when same-sex marriage was legalized in New Zealand, congregations that opted to do so were able to perform same-sex marriages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baybuzz.co.nz/archives/6830/4/|title=Gay Marriage Coming to the Bay|website=www.baybuzz.co.nz|access-date=2016-08-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122053751/http://www.baybuzz.co.nz/archives/6830/4/|archive-date=2015-01-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Methodist Church of Peru ==\nThe [[Methodist Church of Peru]], an autonomous affiliate of the United Methodist Church, has agreed to discuss the issue of homosexuality and the blessing of same-gender unions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iglesiametodista.org.pe/index.php/noticias/noticias-nacionales/74-acuerdos-de-la-jnc|title=Iglesia Metodista del Per\u00fa - Acuerdos de la JNC|last=Oshige|first=Fernando|website=www.iglesiametodista.org.pe|access-date=2016-05-27}}</ref> Generally, the denomination is considered to be a progressive church in Peru.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://revistaargumentos.iep.org.pe/articulos/iglesias-y-diversidad-sexual-en-el-peru-contemporaneo/|title=Iglesias y diversidad sexual en el Per\u00fa contempor\u00e1neo - Revista Argumentos|website=Revista Argumentos|language=es-ES|access-date=2016-05-27}}</ref>\n\n== Methodist Church of Southern Africa ==\nThe [[Methodist Church of Southern Africa]] spoke out against laws criminalizing homosexuality, and, in particular, condemned the anti-homosexuality laws proposed in Uganda.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.methodist.org.za/news/02262014-1831|title=Methodists Condemn Uganda Anti- Homosexuality Law {{!}} The Methodist Church of Southern Africa|website=www.methodist.org.za|access-date=2016-05-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508123213/http://www.methodist.org.za/news/02262014-1831|archive-date=2016-05-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> Currently, the denomination is discussing how to approach the issue of same-gender relationships.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.methodist.org.za/blog/conference-address-2013-01172014-1304|title=Conference Address 2013  {{!}} The Methodist Church of Southern Africa|website=www.methodist.org.za|access-date=2016-05-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160501153521/http://www.methodist.org.za/blog/conference-address-2013-01172014-1304|archive-date=2016-05-01|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Currently, \u201cConference recognises that any decision and subsequent action on the issue of civil unions between same sex partners must await the outcome of the ongoing process of engagement as specified by Conference 2005 and, in the interim, expects Methodist Ministers to continue to offer pastoral care to homosexual individuals.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2013-05-23-the-curious-case-of-the-pastor-punished-for-honesty/|title=The curious case of the pastor punished for honesty {{!}} Daily Maverick|website=www.dailymaverick.co.za|language=en|access-date=2017-05-10}}</ref> Several courts have concluded that the church's policies are currently accepting of same-sex relationships as long as they are not 'marriages'.\n\nIn 2013, the Western Cape High Court found that \"the Methodist Church did not have a rule prohibiting its ministers from marrying someone of the same sex\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Church-didnt-have-same-sex-marriage-rule-20130521|title=No same-sex marriage rule in church|access-date=2016-07-23}}</ref> Additionally, in 2015, another court determined that the denomination \"even accepts same-sex relationships (as long as such relationships are not solemnised by marriage), which means it is not at the core of the Church\u2019s beliefs\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2015-11-24-the-methodist-church-is-confused-and-irrational/#.V5Ml3LQ-CT8|title=The Methodist Church is confused and irrational {{!}} Daily Maverick|website=www.dailymaverick.co.za|access-date=2016-07-23}}</ref> At the Constitutional Court, the church stated that the church \"tolerates homosexual relationships but requires its ministers not to enter into same-sex marriages.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.saflii.org/za/cases/ZACC/2015/35.html|title=De Lange v Presiding Bishop of the Methodist Church of Southern Africa for the time being and Another (CCT223/14) [2015] ZACC 35; 2016 (1) BCLR 1 (CC); 2016 (2) SA 1 (CC) (24 November 2015)|website=www.saflii.org|access-date=2017-05-10}}</ref> The Church allowed [gay ministers] to be in a homosexual relationship whilst being a minister, and allowed [a gay minister] to stay in the Church\u2019s manse with [a] partner, but drew the line at recognising her same-sex marriage.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.methodist.org.za/sites/default/files/fileuploads/Judgment%20-%20CCT%20223-14%20-%20De%20Lange%20v%20Presiding%20Bishop%20of%20the%20Methodist%20Chu...%20%282%29.pdf|title=Constitutional Court of South Africa|last=|first=|date=|website=methodist.org.za|access-date=May 10, 2017}}{{dead link|date=November 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n== Methodist Church of Uruguay ==\nThe church, part of the [[Evangelical Church of Uruguay in Uruguay|Evangelical Church of Uruguay]], \"has a ministry with persons of diverse sexual orientations\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oikoumene.org/en/member-churches/methodist-church-of-uruguay|title=Methodist Church of Uruguay \u2014 World Council of Churches|website=www.oikoumene.org|language=en|access-date=2016-05-26}}</ref> The denomination \"resolved that pastors that wish to minister to homosexuals could do so freely\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.laotravozdigital.com/discriminacion-sexual-avances-y-retrocesos-de-las-iglesias-protestantes-historicas/|title=DISCRIMINACI\u00d3N SEXUAL: AVANCES Y RETROCESOS DE LAS IGLESIAS PROTESTANTES HIST\u00d3RICAS - La Otra Voz Digital|website=La Otra Voz Digital|access-date=2016-05-26}}</ref> Since then, some congregations have provided blessing services for same-gender couples.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.republica.com.uy/bendecidos-por-el-clerigo/519053/|title=Bendecidos por el cl\u00e9rigo Front\u00e1n|date=2015-05-31|website=Diario La Rep\u00fablica|language=es-ES|access-date=2016-05-27}}</ref>\n\n==Primitive Methodist Church==\nThe [[Primitive Methodist Church]] teaches that the practice of homosexuality is positively forbidden by Scripture, specifically in [[Epistle to the Romans|Romans]] 1:26-27 and [[Book of Leviticus|Leviticus]] 18:22; 20:13.<ref name=\"PMC - Chapter Eight of The Discipline\"/> With regards to [[Christian views of marriage|marriage]], the Primitive Methodist Church believes it to involve the total commitment of one man and one woman.<ref name=\"PMC - Chapter Eight of The Discipline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.primitivemethodistchurch.org/chapter8.html|title=CHAPTER EIGHT OF THE DISCIPLINE|publisher=[[Primitive Methodist Church]]|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== United Church of Canada ==\nThe United Church of Canada, a member of the [[World Methodist Council]], is a united church which resulted from the merger of multiple denominations including Methodists. The denomination is supportive of LGBT inclusion. The church ordains openly gay and lesbian clergy, and, in 2012, elected its first openly gay moderator to lead the whole denomination.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vancouversun.com/life/Vancouver+reverend+elected+United+Church+Canada+first+openly+moderator/7102657/story.html|title=Vancouver reverend elected United Church of Canada's first openly gay moderator|last=Butler|first=,Don|website=www.vancouversun.com|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref> Since 2003, the UCC has supported same-gender marriage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/united-church-endorses-gay-marriage-1.357106|title=United Church endorses gay marriage|website=www.cbc.ca|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref>\n\n==United Methodist Church==\n{{see also|Paul Abels}}\n{{Recentism|section|date=August 2018}}\n[[File:Twin Cities Pride- Gay Methodist minister interview.webm|thumb|\"Through the labyrinth of booths at the Twin Cities Pride Festival, Faith Forward MN wove its way on Sunday to a row of faith-based organizations. There, we found a stream of interesting stories and perspectives of progressive faith. Here, you'll meet an ordained Methodist minister barred by the United Methodist Church from leading a congregation of his own.\"]]\nAs stated in the ''[[Book of Discipline of The United Methodist Church]]'', the [[United Methodist Church]] holds that \"homosexual persons no less than heterosexual persons are individuals of sacred worth.\"<ref name=\"UMC - Sexuality\"/> In other words, all individuals are of worth to God. In 1972, the proposed statement ended there; however, this phrase struggled to pass<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.gcah.org/bitstream/handle/10516/9938/Methodist-History-2017-04-Sledge.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y|title=THE SADDEST DAY:\nGENE LEGGETT AND THE ORIGINS OF\nTHE INCOMPATIBLE CLAUSE|last=Sledge|first=Robert W.|date=April 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. Don Hand, a delegate from Southwest Texas suggested that the period be turned into a comma and add the phrase: \"practice of homosexuality [to be] incompatible with [[Christianity|Christian]] teaching,\" For this reason, the \"United Methodist Church does not condone the practice of homosexuality\"<ref name=\"UMC - Sexuality\" /> or allow \"[[Coming out|self-avowed practicing homosexual]]s\" to be \"certified as candidates, ordained as ministers, or appointed to serve in The United Methodist Church.\"<ref name=\"UMC - Homosexuality\">{{cite web|url=http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?mid=1324 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121209051506/http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?mid=1324 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-12-09 |title=What is the denomination\u2019s position on homosexuality? |publisher=The United Methodist Church |accessdate=2008-05-16 }}</ref>  \n\nBased on its teaching, the United Methodist Church officially prohibits the [[Blessing of same-sex unions in Christian churches|blessing of weddings]] of same-sex couples by its clergy and in its [[Church (building)|churches]].<ref name=\"UMC - Homosexuality\"/> As officiating at a same-sex wedding or [[coming out]] as an openly LGBT Minister is potentially a chargeable offense, numerous Ministers have been put on trial and [[defrocked]],<ref name=\"UMC - Chargeable Offenses\">{{cite web|url=http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?ptid=3&mid=5711 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130416065428/http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?ptid=3&mid=5711 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-04-16 |title=\u00b6 2702. Chargeable Offenses and the Statute of Limitations |publisher=The United Methodist Church |accessdate=2008-05-16 }}</ref>. The first United Methodist clergy to be defrocked due to being homosexual was [[Gene Leggett]], in 1971, prior to the addition of the Incompatibility Clause which was in 1972. In 1987 Methodist minister Rose Mary Denman, was also defrocked for being openly gay.<ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/03/national/03trial.html?ex=1259730000&en=2bf3ceb5ddafc10e&ei=5090&partner=rssuserland|title=United Methodists Move to Defrock Lesbian|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=2008-05-16 | first=Neela | last=Banerjee | date=2004-12-03}}</ref> Similarly, in 2005, clergy credentials were removed from [[Irene Elizabeth Stroud]] after she was convicted in a church trial of violating Church law by engaging in a lesbian relationship; this conviction was later upheld by the Church Judicial Council, the highest court in the denomination.<ref name=\"Religious Tolerance - Homosexuality UMC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.religioustolerance.org/hom_umc10.htm |title=United Methodist Church (UMC): The trial of Irene Elizabeth Stroud |publisher=Religious Tolerance|accessdate=2008-05-16}}</ref> Other clergy, however, avoided church trials altogether. The Rev. Val Roseqnuist officiated a same-sex marriage in 2016 and reached a 'just resolution', and a church trial was avoided.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/living/religion/article100229657.html|title=Charlotte pastor who married same-sex couple will keep job, avoid church trial|access-date=2016-09-07}}</ref> Also in 2016, a complaint filed against an openly gay minister was dismissed, and the minister was able to continue working.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rmnetwork.org/newrmn/after-complaint-dismissed-rev-blaedel-calls-united-methodists-to-action/|title=After complaint dismissed, Rev. Blaedel calls United Methodists to action|date=2016-08-31|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-07}}</ref>\n\nThe United Methodist Church in addition  supports \"laws in civil society that define marriage as the union of one man and one woman.\"<ref name=\"UMC - Marriage\">{{cite web|url=http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?mid=1722 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130416001724/http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?mid=1722 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-04-16 |title=Marriage |publisher=The United Methodist Church |accessdate=2008-05-16 }}</ref> On April 30, 2008, at the [[General conference (United Methodist Church)|General Conference]], delegates adopted even more conservative language, stating that Christians are called to \"responsible stewardship of this sacred gift\" of sexuality and that \"sexual relations are affirmed only within the covenant of monogamous, heterosexual marriage.\"<ref name=\"UMC - Calendar Item 1186\">{{cite web|url=http://calms.umc.org/2008/Text.aspx?mode=Minority&Number=1186 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728142124/http://calms.umc.org/2008/Text.aspx?mode=Minority&Number=1186 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-07-28 |title=Calendar Item 1186 |publisher=The United Methodist Church |accessdate=2008-05-16 }}</ref> Still, in 2015, the Connectional Table, a general agency of the UMC, proposed a localized option that would permit ministers to officiate same-sex weddings and conferences to ordain openly gay clergy; the Connectional Table, however, cannot legislate church law (a right reserved to the General Conference) and their suggestion was rejected by three-fourths of the delegates at the 2016 General Conference.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Connectional Table votes to submit legislation proposal related to homosexuality|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/connectional-table-votes-to-submit-legislation-related-to-homosexuality|website=www.umc.org|publisher=United Methodist Church|accessdate=November 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UMC Connectional Table Solidifies Commitments to Exclusive Western Liberalism|last=Lomperis|first=John|date=20 December 2017|publisher=Juicy Ecumenism|language=English|accessdate=18 June 2018|url=https://juicyecumenism.com/2017/12/20/umc-connectional-table-solidifies-commitments-exclusive-western-liberalism/}}</ref> \n\nAs a result of decisions made in April 2008 and August 2009,<ref name=\"UMC - Lutheran-United Methodist dialogue timeline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content3.aspx?c=lwL4KnN1LtH&b=5259669&ct=7305103 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090823133108/http://www.umc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content3.aspx?c=lwL4KnN1LtH&b=5259669&ct=7305103 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-08-23 |title=Lutheran-United Methodist dialogue timeline |publisher=The United Methodist Church |accessdate=2009-11-25 }}</ref> the United Methodist Church entered into [[full communion]] with the [[Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]].<ref name=\"Christian Post- ELCA Delegates OK Full Communion with UMC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.christianpost.com/article/20090821/elca-delegates-ok-full-communion-with-umc/index.html|title=ELCA Delegates OK Full Communion with UMC|publisher=[[The Christian Post]]|accessdate=2009-11-25}}</ref> The latter denomination allows individuals in committed homosexual relationships to serve as [[Minister (Christianity)|ministers]],<ref name=\"CARM- The ELCA, homosexuality, and apostasy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.carm.org/elca-and-homosexuality|title=The ELCA, homosexuality, and apostasy|publisher=[[Christian Apologetics and Research Ministry]]|accessdate=2009-11-25}}</ref> while the United Methodist Church requires gay clergy to remain [[Clerical celibacy|celibate]].<ref name=\"UMC - Ecumenical pact does not open door to gay clergy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content.aspx?c=lwL4KnN1LtH&b=5398307&ct=7321637 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130416015835/http://www.umc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content.aspx?c=lwL4KnN1LtH&b=5398307&ct=7321637 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-04-16 |title=Ecumenical pact does not open door to gay clergy |publisher=The United Methodist Church |accessdate=2009-11-25 }}</ref> Despite the fact that full communion allows for the interchangeability of all ordained ministers between the two denominations,<ref name=\"BCNN1 - United Methodist Church says No to Lutheran Homosexual Clergy\">{{cite web|url=http://blackchristiannews.com/news/2009/08/united-methodist-church-says-no-to-lutheran-homosexual-clergy.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304215545/http://blackchristiannews.com/news/2009/08/united-methodist-church-says-no-to-lutheran-homosexual-clergy.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-03-04 |title=United Methodist Church says No to Lutheran Homosexual Clergy |publisher=Black Christian News |accessdate=2009-11-25 }}</ref> Lutheran clergy who are involved in homosexual activity are prohibited to serve in the United Methodist Church in order to uphold the integrity of United Methodist ministerial standards.<ref name=\"UMC - Ecumenical pact does not open door to gay clergy\"/> Nevertheless, the UMC has a more ambiguous policy regarding the ordination of transgender pastors and, in 2008,  the Judicial Council ruled that each regional conference can determine their own policy; as a result, some conferences have ordained transgender pastors.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bartolone|first1=Pauline|title=Methodists Vote to Keep Transgender Pastors|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/bryantpark/2007/10/methodists_vote_to_keep_transg.html|website=www.npr.org|publisher=NPR|accessdate=November 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSeveral [[grassroots]] organizations not officially recognized by the United Methodist Church have also formed around positions on issues relating to homosexuality.  The [[Confessing Movement|Confessing Movement within the United Methodist Church]] seeks to continue to protect the United Methodist Church's current stance on homosexuality, if not make it more rigid. Moreover, another movement, ''Transforming Congregations'', is a Methodist [[ex-gay]] ministry whose purpose is to \"equip the local church to model and minister sanctified sexuality through biblical instruction, personal and public witness, and compassionate outreach.<ref name=\"Transforming Congregations\">{{cite web|url=http://www.transformingcong.org/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19991114235730/http://www.transformingcong.org/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=1999-11-14 |title=Our Purpose |publisher=Transforming Congregations |accessdate=2008-05-16 }}</ref> Meanwhile, the [[Reconciling Ministries Network]] seeks to change the United Methodist Church's current teaching on homosexuality in order to make the church more inclusive of [[LGBT]] people.<ref name=\"RMN-Our Mission\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rmnetwork.org/mission.asp |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090219214254/http://rmnetwork.org/mission.asp |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-02-19 |title=Our Mission |publisher=Reconciling Ministries Network |accessdate=2008-05-16 }}</ref> At the 2008 General Conference of the United Methodist Church, it was decided that the Church would retain its views on homosexuality.<ref name=\"ENI-Homosexuality\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eni.ch/featured/article.php?id=1867 |title=Methodists yes to full communion with Lutherans; no on gay change |publisher=Ecumenical News International |accessdate=2008-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109084955/http://www.eni.ch/featured/article.php?id=1867 |archivedate=2009-01-09 }}</ref> At the General Conference in 2016, the delegates deferred the issue of human sexuality to the Council of Bishops in what has been described as a \"'historic action'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thinkprogress.org/lgbt/2016/05/18/3779705/united-methodist-church-has-a-new-method/|title=United Methodist Church Takes \u2018Historic Action\u2019 Toward LGBT Equality|website=ThinkProgress|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, after General Conference, several [[Annual Conferences of the United Methodist Church|Annual Conferences]] voted in favor of non-discrimination clauses that effectively allowed LGBTQ clergy and which indicated that those conferences would refuse to participate in any church trials in which people were being tried for being an active homosexual. The Baltimore-Washington, California-Nevada, California-Pacific, Desert Southwest, New England, New York, Northern Illinois, and Oregon-Idaho Annual Conferences voted in favor of full inclusion for LGBTQ members and clergy.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gadoua|first1=Renee K.|title=United Methodist conferences petition denomination on behalf of LGBT rights|url=http://www.religionnews.com/2015/06/17/united-methodist-conferences-petition-denomination-behalf-lgbt-rights/|website=www.religionnews.com|publisher=Religion News Service|accessdate=November 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/two-conferences-vote-for-full-inclusion-of-lgbtq|title=Two conferences vote for full inclusion  of LGBTQ - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|access-date=2016-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyac.com/newsdetail/new-england-south-georgia-differ-on-gay-clergy-5073383|title=New England, South Georgia differ on gay clergy|website=www.nyac.com|access-date=2016-06-20}}</ref> Additionally, the Virginia Annual Conference voted to petition the UMC to allow LGBTQ clergy and same-gender marriages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/united-methodist-bodys-support-for-pro-gay-petition-saying-homosexuality-is-part-of-gods-creation-wont-influence-churchs-ban-say-theological-conservatives-140797/|title=United Methodist Body's Pro-Gay Petition Saying Homosexuality Is Part of 'God's Creation' Won't Influence Church's Ban, Say Theological Conservatives|website=Christian Post|access-date=2016-06-20}}</ref> The Rocky Mountain Annual Conference voted to not consider sexual orientation when electing a bishop.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rmcumc.org/petitionsruleselections|title=Rocky Mountain Conference: Rules, Petitions & Elections|last=River|first=Brick|website=www.rmcumc.org|access-date=2016-06-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624184439/http://www.rmcumc.org/petitionsruleselections|archive-date=2016-06-24|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2015, the Great Plains and Greater New Jersey Conferences voted to petition the UMC to allow same-gender marriages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kansas.com/living/religion/article24139798.html|title=Kansas, Nebraska United Methodists support change to homosexual doctrines|website=kansas|access-date=2016-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mississippi-umc.org/newsdetail/news-poll-racism-voted-top-2015-story-3216914|title=The Mississippi Annual Conference of the United Methodist Church|website=www.mississippi-umc.org|access-date=2016-06-20}}</ref> In 2014, the Social and Ethics Ministry of the Central Conference in Germany supported an initiative to propose steps toward the full inclusion of LGBT people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.emk.at/blog/debatte-%C3%BCber-homosexualit%C3%A4t-geht-weiter|title=Debatte \u00fcber Homosexualit\u00e4t geht weiter {{!}} Evangelisch-methodistische Kirche in \u00d6sterreich|website=www.emk.at|access-date=2016-06-20}}</ref> In 2012, the Minnesota Conference had voted to oppose bans on same-gender marriage, and the Illinois Great Rivers and West Michigan Conferences voted that it \"expressed sadness\" at the actions of 2012 General Conference, and the Arkansas Annual Conference voted to encourage respect for multiple perspectives on human sexuality.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/conferences-reject-churchs-stance-on-gays|title=Conferences reject church\u2019s stance on gays - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|access-date=2016-06-20}}</ref> The Detroit, Upper New York, and Wisconsin Conferences also supported resolutions supporting allowing same-gender marriages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://umc-gbcs.org/faith-in-action/annual-conferences-report|title=Annual conferences report  {{!}} gbcs|website=umc-gbcs.org|access-date=2016-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703133602/http://umc-gbcs.org/faith-in-action/annual-conferences-report|archive-date=2016-07-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> Bishop Christian Alsted of the Nordic and Baltic Episcopal Area shared that some of the conferences within his region support same-sex marriage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/sexuality-panel-displays-churchs-global-variation|title=Sexuality panel displays church\u2019s global variation - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|access-date=2016-07-01}}</ref> Within the jurisdictions, the Western Jurisdiction and the North Central Jurisdiction have nominated three openly gay candidates for bishop.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://religionnews.com/2016/06/28/methodists-nominate-3-openly-gay-candidates-for-bishop/|title=Methodists nominate 3 openly gay candidates for bishop|last=Emily|first=More by|website=Religion News Service|access-date=2016-06-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/faith_and_values/2016/07/01/ohioan-among-3-openly-gay-united-methodist-ministers-in-u-s--up-for-bishop.html|title=Ohioan among 3 openly gay United Methodist ministers in U.S. up for bishop|access-date=2016-08-07}}</ref> The Northeastern Jurisdiction passed a resolution supporting same-sex marriage and the ordination of openly gay and lesbian clergy, with the New York body ordaining the first openly gay and lesbian clergy in the denomination.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/resolution-recommends-letting-regional-bodies-adapt-discipline|title=Resolution recommends letting regional bodies adapt Discipline - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|access-date=2016-08-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921100403/http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/resolution-recommends-letting-regional-bodies-adapt-discipline|archive-date=2016-09-21|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyac.com/newsdetail/33-ordained-commissioned-by-new-york-conference-5012427|title=33 Ordained, Commissioned in \"Historic\" Service|website=www.nyac.com|access-date=2016-06-13}}</ref> In 2016, the Baltimore-Washington Conference appointed an openly partnered lesbian to the provisional diaconate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.episcopalcafe.com/us-united-methodists-vs-african-asian-united-methodists/|title=US United Methodists vs African & Asian United Methodists|website=Episcopal Cafe|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref> In April 2016, Bishop Melvin Talbert performed a same-sex marriage as a public sign of his support for change and full inclusion of LGBT persons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/bishop-again-officiates-at-same-gender-nuptials|title=Bishop again officiates at same-gender nuptials - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|access-date=2016-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160521065619/http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/bishop-again-officiates-at-same-gender-nuptials|archive-date=2016-05-21|url-status=dead}}</ref> The church also provides spousal benefits for non-ordained employees in same-sex marriages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/04/29/methodist-same-sex-marriage-benefits_n_5235596.html|title=Methodist Church Approves Same-Sex Marriage Benefits|last=Service|first=Lauren Markoe Religion News|date=2014-04-29|website=The Huffington Post|access-date=2016-06-21}}</ref> Some congregations have individually voted to perform same-sex marriages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/rural-texas-church-votes-for-same-sex-weddings|title=Rural Texas church votes for same-sex weddings - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|access-date=2016-08-29}}</ref> Also in 2016, the Western Jurisdiction of the denomination elected an openly partnered lesbian as bishop.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/western-jurisdiction-elects-openly-gay-united-methodist-bishop|title=Western Jurisdiction elects openly gay United Methodist bishop - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|access-date=2016-07-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160718232123/http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/western-jurisdiction-elects-openly-gay-united-methodist-bishop|archive-date=2016-07-18|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHowever, two United Methodist bishops \"voided two resolutions in the Northeastern United States that called for defying church restrictions\".<ref name=\"Hahn2016\">{{cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/bishops-overrule-nonconformity-resolutions|title=Bishops overrule nonconformity resolutions|last=Hahn|first=Heather|date=15 September 2016|publisher=The United Methodist Church|language=English|accessdate=15 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916213650/http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/bishops-overrule-nonconformity-resolutions|archive-date=16 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Similarly, the United Methodist Bishops of the Central Conferences of Africa unanimously called for \"unreserved commitment to the Holy Bible as the primary authority for faith and practice in the Church\" and proclaimed that \"sexual relations are affirmed only within the covenant bond of a faithful monogamous, heterosexual marriage, and not within same-sex unions or polygamy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/african-bishops-speak-out-on-terrorism-sexuality|title=African bishops speak out on terrorism, sexuality|last=Hahn|first=Heather|date=4 November 2015|publisher=The United Methodist Church|language=English|accessdate=15 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916131634/http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/african-bishops-speak-out-on-terrorism-sexuality|archive-date=16 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://goodnewsmag.org/2015/11/united-methodist-bishops-from-africa-speak-out/|title=United Methodist Bishops from Africa issue statement|date=4 November 2015|publisher=Good News Magazine|language=English|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://juicyecumenism.com/2015/11/04/bishops-of-the-central-conferences-of-africa-release-statement-encouraging-church-unity-and-a-return-to-doctrine/|title=United Methodist Bishops in Africa Reaffirm Biblical Teaching on Marriage|date=4 November 2015|publisher=[[Institute on Religion and Democracy]]|language=English|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref> United Methodist Bishop Gaspar Jo\u00e3o Domingos stated that \"the United Methodist Church denies the abuse of the principle of tolerance that sets aside the authority of Jesus Christ and the teaching on sexuality.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://juicyecumenism.com/2016/02/08/angolan-bishop-urges-umc-to-stand-firm-on-homosexuality/|title=Angolan Bishop Urges UMC to Stand Firm on Homosexuality|date=8 February 2016|publisher=[[Institute on Religion and Democracy]]|language=English|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref> At the same time, the Alabama-West Florida Conference\" passed resolutions upholding the denomination's rules on homosexuality\" and the Eastern Pennsylvania Conference \"approved a resolution that urges the conference to demand clergy accountability to the Discipline's 'rules of our common covenant,' and to call upon clergy to challenge those rules only 'through legitimate channels of holy conferencing, rather than breaking that covenant.'\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gadoua|first1=Renee K.|title=United Methodist conferences petition denomination on behalf of LGBT rights|url=http://www.religionnews.com/2015/06/17/united-methodist-conferences-petition-denomination-behalf-lgbt-rights/|website=www.religionnews.com|publisher=Religion News|accessdate=November 30, 2015}}</ref> The Southeastern Jurisdiction also voted to maintain the current language in the Book of Discipline.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/southeastern-bishops-decry-nonconformity-plans|title=Southeastern bishops decry 'nonconformity' plans - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|access-date=2016-07-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716055150/http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/southeastern-bishops-decry-nonconformity-plans|archive-date=2016-07-16|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn July 15, 2016, the Western Jurisdictional Conference elected [[Karen Oliveto]] to become the first openly lesbian Bishop in the United Methodist Church. She was consecrated as Bishop on July 16. She recently served as Pastor at Glide Memorial Church, is an ordained elder, teaches students at the Pacific School of Religion, and is on the Advisory Board of the Forum for Theological Education. Bishop Oliveto is married to Robin Ridenour, a Deaconess in the California-Nevada Conference.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/western-jurisdiction-elects-openly-gay-united-methodist-bishop |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-07-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160718232123/http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/western-jurisdiction-elects-openly-gay-united-methodist-bishop |archive-date=2016-07-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/married-lesbian-consecrated-united-methodist-bishop</ref><ref>http://www.rmnetwork.org/newrmn/bishopkarenoliveto/</ref> However, on 25 April 2017, \"In a 6-to-3 vote, the United Methodist Church\u2019s highest court ruled that a married lesbian bishop, and those who consecrated her, had violated church law on marriage and homosexuality\";<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/04/28/us/Methodist-Decision-Oliveto.html?_r=0|title=Methodist Court Declares Gay Bishop\u2019s Consecration Illegal|date=28 April 2017|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|language=English|accessdate=2 May 2017}}</ref> the United Methodist Church held that she \"is in violation of a church law barring the ordination of 'self-avowed practicing homosexuals,' but it did not remove her as bishop, instead sending the issue back to the jurisdiction that chose her.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2017/04/28/gay-bishop-karen-oliveto-methodist-church/|title=Karen Oliveto, first openly gay bishop, in violation of Methodist church law, court says|last1=Brown|first1=Jennifer|first2=Danika|last2=Worthington|date=28 April 2017|publisher=[[The Denver Post]]|language=English|accessdate=2 May 2017}}</ref> Therefore, the Judicial Council ruled that \"Bishop Oliveto 'remains in good standing,' until an administrative or judicial process is completed.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/president-of-the-council-of-bishops-statement-regarding-judicial-council-de|title=President of the Council of Bishops: Statement regarding Judicial Council decision 1341 - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|language=en|access-date=2017-05-09}}</ref> However, the Judicial Council also ruled that \"she was in good standing\" and that \"it had no jurisdiction to review Bishop Oliveto's nomination, election, and assignment.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/blogs-commentaries/post/commentary-attorney-on-confusion-over-olivetos-status|title=Commentary: Attorney on confusion over Oliveto\u2019s status - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|language=en|access-date=2017-05-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508225934/http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/blogs-commentaries/post/commentary-attorney-on-confusion-over-olivetos-status|archive-date=2017-05-08|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn May 7, 2018 the Council of Bishops in the United Methodist Church proposed allowing individual pastors and regional church bodies to decide whether to ordain LGBT clergy and perform same-sex weddings, though this proposal can only be approved by the General Conference.<ref>[https://www.advocate.com/religion/2018/5/05/methodist-bishops-back-choice-lgbt-clergy-same-sex-marriage Advocate: Methodist Bishops Back Choice on LGBT Clergy, Same-Sex Marriage]</ref> At this meeting, the Council of Bishops will also consider 2 other alternative plans for the future concerning this issue. The second plan called the Connectional Conference Plan would create three connectional conferences based on theology related to the issue of human sexuality, the current five conferences would be abolished and each of the five conferences would have clearly defined values of accountability, contextualization, and justice. These three denominations would serve almost as three sub-denominations within overall United Methodism.  The third plan, called the Traditional Plan, would reinforce the existing language in the Book of Discipline prohibiting homosexuality, gay marriage ceremonies on church campuses, and allow for stricter enforcement of violations of existing church law.<ref>[https://www.umnews.org/en/news/ask-the-umc-can-you-explain-way-forward-plans-cob-recommendation Ask The UMC:Can you explain Way Forward plans, COB reccomendation?]</ref>  On February 26, 2019, during a special session of the General Conference, delegates from around the world voted to pass the Traditional Plan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/02/26/698188343/united-methodist-church-votes-to-keep-bans-on-same-sex-weddings-lgbtq-clergy|title=United Methodist Church Votes To Keep Bans On Same-Sex Weddings, LGBTQ Clergy|last=Chappell|first=Bill|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, the [[Central conferences (United Methodist Church)|German Central Conference]] announced that it would not be implementing the Traditional Plan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.umnews.org:443/en/news/german-church-wont-impose-traditional-plan-bans|title=German church won\u2019t impose Traditional Plan bans|website=United Methodist News Service|language=en|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref> Although the [[Annual conferences of the United Methodist Church|US jurisdictions and annual conferences]] are unable to alter the Book of Discipline as the Central Conferences are, the Western Jurisdiction declared their disagreement with the Traditional Plan and vowed to remain LGBTQ inclusive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://westernjurisdictionumc.org/western-jurisdiction-umc-bishops-video-statement-script/|title=Western Jurisdiction UMC Bishops video statement script|last=UMC|first=Western Jurisdiction|date=2019-03-01|website=Western Jurisdiction of The UMC|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, a 16-person committee of bishops and other official submitted to the General Conference a scism proposal for the creation of a new separated \"traditional Methodist\" denomination, a text that still needs to be approved by the conference in May. By default, any parish will be set as a member of the United Methodist Church (UMC) and would have to conduct votes in order to enter in the newborn communion of the more conservative Methodists.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n== Uniting Church in Australia ==\nThe denomination has permitted presbyteries to ordain openly gay and lesbian ministers if they opt to do so<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/7.30/content/2003/s906981.htm|title=7.30 Report|website=www.abc.net.au|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref> and churches may bless same-sex couples entering into civil partnerships.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/wa/a/28769619/uniting-church-may-overhaul-rules-of-marriage/|title=Church may overhaul its rules of marriage|website=au.news.yahoo.com|access-date=2016-05-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401170740/https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/wa/a/28769619/uniting-church-may-overhaul-rules-of-marriage/|archive-date=2016-04-01|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 13 July 2018, the Uniting Church in Australia voted by national Assembly to approve the creation of official marriage rites for same-sex couples.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sandeman |first=John |date=13 July 2018 |title=Uniting Church to hold same sex marriages |url=https://www.eternitynews.com.au/australia/uniting-church-to-hold-same-sex-marriage/ |work=Eternity |location=Australia |access-date=13 July 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Methodism|Evangelical Christianity|LGBT}}\n*[[Paul Abels]]\n*[[Gene Leggett]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.garyhopkins.net/pilgrimageoffaith/ Pilgrimage of Faith Research:] Research about homosexuality and the Methodist Church of Great Britain\n*[https://rmnetwork.org/ Reconciling Ministries Network] The largest organization working for equality for LGBT United Methodists \n\n{{Methodism footer}}\n{{Religion and LGBT people}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Homosexuality And Methodism}}\n[[Category:LGBT topics and Protestantism|Methodism]]\n[[Category:Methodism]]\n", "text_old": "{{Christianity and sexual orientation}}\n{{Methodism}}\n\n'''Methodist viewpoints concerning homosexuality''' are diverse because there is no one [[Christian denomination|denomination]] which represents all Methodists. The [[World Methodist Council]], which represents most Methodist denominations, has no official statements regarding sexuality. [[Methodist Church of Great Britain|British Methodism]] holds a variety of views, and permits ministers to bless same-gender marriages.<ref name=\"Church Times\">{{cite web|last1=Drake|first1=Gavin|title=Methodists may bless but not marry same-sex couples|url=http://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2014/11-july/news/uk/methodists-may-bless-but-not-marry-same-sex-couples|website=www.churchtimes.co.uk|publisher=Church Times|accessdate=November 30, 2015}}</ref> American Methodism concentrates on the position that the [[homosexuality|same-sex]] relations are incompatible with \"Christian teaching\", but extends ministry to persons of a homosexual orientation, holding that all individuals are of sacred worth.<ref name=\"UMC - Sexuality\">{{cite web|url=http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?mid=1728|title=Human Sexuality|publisher=The United Methodist Church|accessdate=2008-05-16}}</ref><ref name=\"FMC - Christian Conduct\">{{cite web|url=http://www.freemethodistchurch.org/Sections/About%20Us/Beliefs/Christian%20Life/Christian%20Conduct/Christian%20Conduct%203.htm|title=The Christian Life - Christian Conduct|publisher=Free Methodist Church|accessdate=2008-05-16|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513181703/http://www.freemethodistchurch.org/Sections/About%20Us/Beliefs/Christian%20Life/Christian%20Conduct/Christian%20Conduct%203.htm|archivedate=2008-05-13}}</ref><ref name=\"UMC - British Methodists reject blessing of same-sex relationships\">{{cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/site/c.gjJTJbMUIuE/b.1827285/k.B985/British_Methodists_reject_blessing_of_samesex_relationships.htm|title=British Methodists reject blessing of same-sex relationships|publisher=The United Methodist Church|accessdate=2007-05-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914134747/http://www.umc.org/site/c.gjJTJbMUIuE/b.1827285/k.B985/British_Methodists_reject_blessing_of_samesex_relationships.htm|archive-date=2016-09-14|url-status=dead}}</ref> The following denominations are members of the World Methodist Council.\n\n==African Methodist Episcopal Church==\nThe [[African Methodist Episcopal Church]] does not approve of the ordination of openly gay persons to the ranks of the [[clergy]] in the Church.<ref name=\"HRC - Stances of Faiths on LGBT Issues: African Methodist Episcopal Church\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hrc.org/issues/4957.htm|title=Stances of Faiths on LGBT Issues: African Methodist Episcopal Church|publisher=The Human Rights Campaign|accessdate=2009-11-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091121220941/http://www.hrc.org/issues/4957.htm|archive-date=2009-11-21|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, there is no official prohibition at this time against ordination. In a historic decision, which marked the first vote on the issue of marriage rights for same-sex couples by a predominantly African-American denomination, the African Methodist Episcopal Church unanimously voted to forbid ministers from [[Blessing of same-sex unions in Christian churches|blessing same-sex unions]] in July 2004.<ref name=\"HRC - Stances of Faiths on LGBT Issues: African Methodist Episcopal Church\"/><ref name=\"Washington Post - Gay Blacks Feeling Strained Church Ties\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A17057-2004Nov1.html|title=Gay Blacks Feeling Strained Church Ties|publisher=The Human Rights Campaign|accessdate=2009-11-25 | first=Darryl | last=Fears | date=2004-11-02}}</ref> The church leaders stated that homosexual activity \"clearly contradicts [their] understanding of Scripture.\"<ref name=\"HRC - Stances of Faiths on LGBT Issues: African Methodist Episcopal Church\"/> Although the AME prohibits its ministers from officiating at same-sex weddings, the AME has \"chosen to offer no official policy statements on homosexuality.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Trauma, Stress, and Resilience Among Sexual Minority Women: Rising Like the Phoenix|last=Balsam|first=Kimberly|publisher=Routledge|year=2012|isbn=|location=New York|pages=115|quote=|via=}}</ref>  As it has no official policy on ordination, some openly gay clergy have been ordained in the AME.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hahn|first1=Heather|title=Gay pastor's removal brings sadness, defiance|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/gay-pastors-removal-brings-sadness-defiance|website=www.umc.org|publisher=United Methodist Church|accessdate=November 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Allegheny Wesleyan Methodist Connection==\nThe [[Allegheny Wesleyan Methodist Connection]], in its ''Discipline'', teaches in \u00b644:<ref name=\"AWMC2014\"/>\n{{quotation|Further, by observing the teaching of Scripture regarding sexual conduct. We believe that God has commanded that no intimate sexual activity be engaged in outside of marriage between a man and a woman. We believe that any form of homosexuality, lesbianism, bi-sexuality, bestiality, incest, fornication, adultery, and any attempt to alter one\u2019s gender by surgery or appearance are sinful perversions of God\u2019s gift of sex. The party guilty of such conduct has by his or her act forfeited membership in the church.<br>\nGen. 2:24; 19:5, 13; 26:8\u201310; Lev. 18:1\u201330; Rom. 1:26\u201329; 1 Cor. 5:1; 6:9; 1 Thes. 4:1\u20138; Heb. 13:4.<ref name=\"AWMC2014\">{{cite book|title=The Discipline of the Allegheny Wesleyan Methodist Connection (Original Allegheny Conference)|year=2014|publisher=[[Allegheny Wesleyan Methodist Connection]]|location=[[Salem, Ohio|Salem]]|language=English|page=21, 125}}</ref>}}\n\u00b6340 outlines the consequences for clergymen engaged in homosexual activity:<ref name=\"AWMC2014\"/>\n{{quotation|When an elder or a minister shall have been convicted of the crime of fornication, adultery, or homosexual activity, he or she shall be expelled from the Connection and shall never be restored to membership in the Connection; and the Connection shall not receive from any church anyone who has been convicted of these crimes after entering the ministry. But this shall not prohibit membership in an Allegheny Wesleyan Methodist church when the guilty person repents.<ref name=\"AWMC2014\"/>}}\n\n== Argentine Evangelical Methodist Church ==\nThe church, also called the [[Evangelical Methodist Church in Argentina]], allows each congregation to make its own position. The church has stated that they have \"given, on a national level, freedom so that each congregation accompany...these couples. We permit freedom of action in order to bless them\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.elciudadanoweb.com/hay-libertad-para-acompanar-a-las-parejas-homosexuales/|title=Hay libertad para acompa\u00f1ar a las parejas homosexuales |website=Diario El Ciudadano y la Gente|access-date=2016-05-26}}</ref>\n\n== Bible Methodist Connection of Churches ==\nThe [[Bible Methodist Connection of Churches]], in its ''Discipline'', states in \u00b642 that:\n{{quotation|We believe that God has given to us the gift of sexuality which may be exercised only within the boundaries of covenanted, monogamous, heterosexual marriage. Sexual relationships outside of marriage and sexual relationships between persons of the same sex are immoral and sinful. Thus, we condemn homosexuality, lesbianism, pederasty, bisexuality, bestiality, incest, pedophilia, fornication, adultery, pornography, and other forms of licentiousness as sinful perversions of the divine gift of sexuality. We believe that God disapproves of and forbids any attempt to alter one\u2019s gender by surgery or appearance.<ref name=\"BMC2014\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.biblemethodist.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/2014-Bible-Methodist-Discipline.pdf|title=Discipline of the Bible Methodist Connection of Churches|year=2014|publisher=General Conference of the Bible Methodist Connection of Churches}}</ref>}}\nIn \u00b644, it further states that:\n{{quotation|No practicing homosexual/lesbian shall be ordained as a minister or missionary or shall be used as a teacher, office holder or other employee in any of our ministries. They shall not be eligible to be members, lay leaders, or ministerial leaders in our churches. If any of the aforementioned persons or office holders practice this lifestyle, they forfeit their right to any office or membership in our churches. Practicing this lifestyle shall constitute automatic removal from membership or office.<ref name=\"BMC2014\"/>}}\n\u00b645 of the ''Discipline of the Bible Methodist Connection of Churches'' specifically prohibits its clergymen from officiating at [[Blessing of same-sex unions in Christian churches|same-sex marriages]].<ref name=\"BMC2014\"/>\n\n== Church of the Nazarene ==\nThe [[Church of the Nazarene]], a Methodist/Holiness denomination, teaches that marriage is only defined for heterosexual couples.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nazarene.org/files/docs/Perspectives_Homosexuality.pdf|title=A Pastoral Perspective of Homosexuality|date=September 20, 2011|website=nazarene.org|publisher=Church of the Nazarene|access-date=May 20, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304200945/http://nazarene.org/files/docs/Perspectives_Homosexuality.pdf|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> As such, the denomination does not allow same-gender marriages.\n\n== Church of North India ==\nThe denomination, [[Uniting church|uniting]] different Protestants including Methodists, takes a traditional stand on human sexuality maintaining that marriage is defined heterosexually. The church opposes the criminalization of homosexuality, but also opposed the consecration of the first homosexual bishop in the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal Church]], the Rt. Rev. [[Gene Robinson]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://continuingindaba.org/2013/09/18/homosexuality-an-indian-issue-in-church-and-state/|title=Homosexuality: An Indian Issue in Church and State|date=2013-09-18|website=Continuing Indaba|access-date=2016-05-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611094253/https://continuingindaba.org/2013/09/18/homosexuality-an-indian-issue-in-church-and-state/|archive-date=2016-06-11|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2009, the church both opposed the supreme court's decision to criminalize homosexuality, and also opposed same-sex marriage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/indian-supreme-court-re-criminalizes-homosexual-activity/|title=Indian Supreme Court Re-Criminalizes Homosexual Activity|website=National Catholic Register|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref>\n\n== Church of South India ==\nThe Church of South India (CSI) is a united church representing Anglicans, Methodists, and Presbyterians. The CSI \"is a relatively liberal Protestant church which has, since 1984, allowed women to become pastors. 'CSI has been liberal on these issues. It has taken up issues of gender, dalits and landlessness. It has to address the issue of sexual minorities too\"'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/kerala-rising-cases-of-sexual-abuse-within-the-church/1/151572.html|title=Rising cases of sexual abuse within the church in Kerala force clergy to rethink on homosexuality|website=indiatoday.intoday.in|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref> In 2009, the Rev. Christopher Rajkumar, speaking for the CSI, supported civil rights for gay people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1090805/jsp/frontpage/story_11322140.jsp|title=The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) {{!}} Frontpage {{!}} Protestants support gay rights|website=www.telegraphindia.com|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref> In 2015, St. Mark's Cathedral in Bangalore hosted an event challenging homophobia where the Rev. Vincent Rajkumar affirmed his support for LGBT rights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thewire.in/2015/12/09/a-theological-challenge-to-christian-homophobia-16685/|title=A Theological Challenge to Christian Homophobia|last=Sitlhou|first=Makepeace|date=2015-12-09|website=The Wire|access-date=2016-05-21|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151211203604/http://thewire.in/2015/12/09/a-theological-challenge-to-christian-homophobia-16685/|archivedate=2015-12-11}}</ref>  The BBC has listed the CSI as being among the churches open to blessing same-gender couples.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-35278124|title=Church split over homosexuality would be a failure - Welby - BBC News|website=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref>\n\n==Evangelical Methodist Church==\nThe [[Evangelical Methodist Church]] maintains that the biblical record condemns homosexuality as evidenced in [[Leviticus]] {{Bibleref2-nb|Leviticus|18:22}}, [[Epistle to the Romans|Romans]] {{Bibleref2-nb|Romans|1:26-27}}, and [[1 Corinthians]] {{Bibleref2-nb|1 Corinthians|6:9-19}}.<ref name=\"EMC-Homosexuality\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emchurch.org/main/?s=homosexuality#74|title=Handbook of the EMC|publisher=[[Evangelical Methodist Church]]|accessdate=2009-12-03}}</ref> It teaches that homosexual practices are \"[[sin]] leading to spiritual death and [[Hell in Christian beliefs|eternal punishment]].<ref name=\"EMC-Homosexuality\"/> Nevertheless, homosexuality is no greater a sin than [[adultery]], [[murder]], [[stealing]], among others.<ref name=\"EMC-Homosexuality\"/> As a result, practicing homosexuals are barred from becoming members of the [[Evangelical Methodist Church]]. Moreover, practicing homosexuals are prohibited from becoming candidates for [[Elder (Methodism)|ordained]] ministry.<ref name=\"EMC-Homosexuality\"/> The Church upholds that all individuals are entitled to certain rights and protection of the [[Civil law (legal system)|civil law]]; nevertheless, it opposes all civil legislation that supports homosexuality as a normal life style.<ref name=\"EMC-Homosexuality\"/> All homosexuals who seek faith in [[Jesus Christ]] as Saviour and Lord, and cease to practice homosexual acts are welcomed into the fellowship of the Evangelical Methodist Church.<ref name=\"EMC-Homosexuality\"/>\n\n==Evangelical Wesleyan Church==\nThe [[Evangelical Wesleyan Church]], in \u00b692.1 and \u00b692.2 of its ''Discipline'', teaches that:<ref name=\"EWC2015\">{{cite book|title=The Discipline of the Evangelical Wesleyan Church |year=2015|publisher=[[Evangelical Wesleyan Church]]|language=English|pages=64-65}}</ref>\n{{quotation|God has commanded that no intimate sexual activity be engaged in outside of a marriage between one naturally-born man and one naturally-born woman. It stands opposed to the immoral lifestyles of the day, including but not limited to homosexuality, lesbianism, transsexualism, bisexuality, bestiality, incest, fornication, adultery, pornography, polygamy, bigamy, and living together without legally being married, realizing that these are sinful perversions of God's gracious gifts to mankind. Further, it believes that God disapproves of and forbids any attempt to alter one's gender by surgery or appearance. (Gen. 2:24; Gen. 19:5, 13; Gen. 26:8-9; Lev. 18:1-30; Rom. 1:26-29; I Cor. 5:1, 6-9, I Thess. 4:1-8; Heb. 13:4.) It does not condemn the individual but rejects the practices which are condemned by the Bible as unacceptable conduct. The church believes it is a free right to publicly express this Scriptural position (Romans 1:21-27, Leviticus 18:22). Any current member who becomes engaged in such behaviors shall be considered as having voluntarily withdrawn from membership. The Evangelical Wesleyan Church, Inc., does not recognize the marriage or civil unions between persons of the same sex. All its ministers are expressly forbidden to perform a marriage ceremony between persons of the same gender. A marriage ceremony between persons of the same sex may not be performed in any Evangelical Wesleyan Church or church-related facility.<ref name=\"EWC2015\"/>}}\n\n==Free Methodist Church==\nAs stated in the ''[[Book of Discipline (disambiguation)|Book of Discipline]]'' (A/342) of the [[Free Methodist Church]], it believes and teaches that {{quote|Homosexual behavior, as all sexual deviation, is a [[perversion]] of God's [[Genesis creation myth|created order]] (Genesis 1-3). The [[Christian views of marriage|sanctity of marriage]] and the family is to be preserved against all manner of [[immoral]] conduct (Exodus 22:16-17; Deuteronomy 22:23-28; Leviticus 20:10-16), thus the Free Methodist Church does not recognize the legitimacy or participation in the practice of [[same-sex marriage]].\n\nHomosexual behavior is contrary to the will of God as clearly stated in [[Bible|Scripture]] (Leviticus 18:22; 20:13; Romans 1:26-27; 1 Corinthians 6:9-10; 1 Timothy 1:8-10).\n\nPersons with homosexual inclinations are accountable to God for their behavior (Romans 14:12).\n\nThe [[Forgiveness#Christianity|forgiving]] and [[Salvation|delivering]] [[Divine grace|grace]] of God in [[Christ]] is all-sufficient for the homosexual (1 John 1:9; Hebrews 7:25; Luke 4:18; 1 Corinthians 6:9-11).\nThe Church has a personal and corporate responsibility to be God's instrument of healing, restoring love to the homosexual seeking recovery of [[Christianity|Christian]] conduct and life-style (2 Corinthians 2:7-8).\n\nThe church opposes legislation which makes homosexual conduct or life-style legitimate.<ref name=\"FMC - Christian Conduct\"/>}}\n\n== Italian Methodist Church ==\nThe [[Union of Methodist and Waldensian Churches]], of which the [[Italian Methodist Church]] is a part of, voted in 2010 to bless same-sex relationships.<ref name=\"Italy\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcusa.org/news/2010/9/7/italian-protestants-approve-same-sex-blessings/|title=Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) - News & Announcements - Italian Protestants approve same-sex blessings|last=(U.S.A.)|first=Presbyterian Church|date=2010-09-07|website=www.pcusa.org|language=en|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref> LGBT-affirming church leaders said \"the references to homosexuality in the Bible needed to be understood taking into account issue of culture and interpretation, to avoid the danger of Biblical fundamentalism.\"<ref name=\"Italy\" />\n\n==Methodist Church of Great Britain==\nAt the annual Methodist Conference in 1993 in Derby, following long debate at all levels of the Church's life on the basis of a detailed report, the [[Methodist Church of Great Britain|British Methodist Church]] considered the issues of [[human sexuality]].<ref name=\"The Methodist Church of Great Britain- Human Sexuality\">{{cite web|url=http://www.methodist.org.uk/index.cfm?fuseaction=opentogod.content&cmid=1547 |title=Human Sexuality |publisher=The Methodist Church of Great Britain |accessdate=2008-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071023044509/http://www.methodist.org.uk/index.cfm?fuseaction=opentogod.content&cmid=1547 |archivedate=2007-10-23 }}</ref> The Derby Conference in 1993 passed a series of Resolutions which still stand. These resolutions are as follows:\n{{quote|\n1. The Conference, affirming the joy of human sexuality as God's gift and the place of every human being within the grace of God, recognises the responsibility that flows from this for us all. It therefore welcomes the serious, prayerful and sometimes costly consideration given to this issue by The Methodist Church.<br>\n2. All practices of sexuality, which are promiscuous, exploitative or demeaning in any way are unacceptable forms of behaviour and contradict God's purpose for us all.<br>\n3. A person shall not be debarred from church on the grounds of sexual orientation in itself.<br>\n4. The Conference reaffirms the traditional teaching of the Church on human sexuality; namely [[chastity]] for all outside marriage and [[fidelity]] within it. The Conference directs that this affirmation is made clear to all candidates for ministry, office and membership, and having established this, affirm that the existing procedures of our church are adequate to deal with all such cases.<br>\n5. The Conference resolves that its decision in this debate shall not be used to form the basis of a disciplinary charge against any person in relation to conduct alleged to have taken place before such decisions were made.<br>\n6. Conference recognises, affirms and celebrates the participation and ministry of lesbians and gay men in the church. Conference calls on the Methodist people to begin a pilgrimage of faith to combat repression and discrimination, to work for justice and human rights and to give dignity and worth to people whatever their sexuality.<ref name=\"The Methodist Church of Great Britain- Human Sexuality\"/>}}\n\nIn 2005, the church voted \"to offer the prospect of blessing services for same-sex couples\", but in 2006 the church voted to step back but did offer \"informal, private prayers to couples\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://outcomeonline.org.uk/?p=187|title=Methodist Church votes on same sex blessings|website=outcomeonline.org.uk|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> In 2013, the denomination initiated a consultation on blessing same-sex marriages,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/religion/10484097/Methodist-Church-begins-mass-consultation-on-gay-marriage.html|title=Methodist Church begins mass consultation on gay marriage|website=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref> and, in 2014, after same-sex marriage became legal, the Methodist Church decided in favor of allowing ministers to celebrate same-sex couples entering into civil marriages.<ref name=\"Church Times\"/> Also in 2014, \"the Conference resolved that its previous ruling that there was no reason per se to prevent anyone within the Church, ordained or lay, from entering into or remaining within a civil partnership, should also extend to those entering into legally contracted same-sex marriages\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.methodist.org.uk/news-and-events/news-releases/methodist-conference-receives-report-on-same-sex-marriage|title=Methodist Conference receives report on same-sex marriage|website=www.methodist.org.uk|access-date=2016-08-09}}</ref>\n\nThe denomination officially stated that Methodists may enter into same-sex marriages and that \"prayers of thanksgiving or celebration may be said, and there may be informal services of thanksgiving or celebration\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.methodist.org.uk/who-we-are/views-of-the-church/human-sexuality/talking-of-marriage-and-relationships/frequently-asked-questions-marriage-and-relationships|title=Frequently Asked Questions - Marriage and Relationships|website=www.methodist.org.uk|access-date=2016-07-09}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 July 2019, the [[United Kingdom|UK]] Methodist Conference voted by 247 votes to 48 to allow [[Same-sex marriage|same-sex marriages]] in UK [[Methodism|Methodist Churches.]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2019/5-july/news/uk/methodists-move-towards-conducting-same-sex-marriages|title=Methodists move towards conducting same-sex marriages|website=www.churchtimes.co.uk|access-date=2019-07-05}}</ref>\n\n== Methodist Church of New Zealand ==\nThe [[Methodist Church of New Zealand]], since 2004, has approved of ordaining openly gay and lesbian ministers, and the denomination allows each local congregation to determine its own policy on the issue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=3591533|title=Methodists say yes to ordaining homosexuals|date=2004-09-15|newspaper=New Zealand Herald|language=en-NZ|issn=1170-0777|access-date=2016-04-13}}</ref> In 2013, when same-sex marriage was legalized in New Zealand, congregations that opted to do so were able to perform same-sex marriages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baybuzz.co.nz/archives/6830/4/|title=Gay Marriage Coming to the Bay|website=www.baybuzz.co.nz|access-date=2016-08-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122053751/http://www.baybuzz.co.nz/archives/6830/4/|archive-date=2015-01-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Methodist Church of Peru ==\nThe [[Methodist Church of Peru]], an autonomous affiliate of the United Methodist Church, has agreed to discuss the issue of homosexuality and the blessing of same-gender unions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iglesiametodista.org.pe/index.php/noticias/noticias-nacionales/74-acuerdos-de-la-jnc|title=Iglesia Metodista del Per\u00fa - Acuerdos de la JNC|last=Oshige|first=Fernando|website=www.iglesiametodista.org.pe|access-date=2016-05-27}}</ref> Generally, the denomination is considered to be a progressive church in Peru.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://revistaargumentos.iep.org.pe/articulos/iglesias-y-diversidad-sexual-en-el-peru-contemporaneo/|title=Iglesias y diversidad sexual en el Per\u00fa contempor\u00e1neo - Revista Argumentos|website=Revista Argumentos|language=es-ES|access-date=2016-05-27}}</ref>\n\n== Methodist Church of Southern Africa ==\nThe [[Methodist Church of Southern Africa]] spoke out against laws criminalizing homosexuality, and, in particular, condemned the anti-homosexuality laws proposed in Uganda.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.methodist.org.za/news/02262014-1831|title=Methodists Condemn Uganda Anti- Homosexuality Law {{!}} The Methodist Church of Southern Africa|website=www.methodist.org.za|access-date=2016-05-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508123213/http://www.methodist.org.za/news/02262014-1831|archive-date=2016-05-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> Currently, the denomination is discussing how to approach the issue of same-gender relationships.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.methodist.org.za/blog/conference-address-2013-01172014-1304|title=Conference Address 2013  {{!}} The Methodist Church of Southern Africa|website=www.methodist.org.za|access-date=2016-05-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160501153521/http://www.methodist.org.za/blog/conference-address-2013-01172014-1304|archive-date=2016-05-01|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Currently, \u201cConference recognises that any decision and subsequent action on the issue of civil unions between same sex partners must await the outcome of the ongoing process of engagement as specified by Conference 2005 and, in the interim, expects Methodist Ministers to continue to offer pastoral care to homosexual individuals.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2013-05-23-the-curious-case-of-the-pastor-punished-for-honesty/|title=The curious case of the pastor punished for honesty {{!}} Daily Maverick|website=www.dailymaverick.co.za|language=en|access-date=2017-05-10}}</ref> Several courts have concluded that the church's policies are currently accepting of same-sex relationships as long as they are not 'marriages'.\n\nIn 2013, the Western Cape High Court found that \"the Methodist Church did not have a rule prohibiting its ministers from marrying someone of the same sex\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Church-didnt-have-same-sex-marriage-rule-20130521|title=No same-sex marriage rule in church|access-date=2016-07-23}}</ref> Additionally, in 2015, another court determined that the denomination \"even accepts same-sex relationships (as long as such relationships are not solemnised by marriage), which means it is not at the core of the Church\u2019s beliefs\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymaverick.co.za/opinionista/2015-11-24-the-methodist-church-is-confused-and-irrational/#.V5Ml3LQ-CT8|title=The Methodist Church is confused and irrational {{!}} Daily Maverick|website=www.dailymaverick.co.za|access-date=2016-07-23}}</ref> At the Constitutional Court, the church stated that the church \"tolerates homosexual relationships but requires its ministers not to enter into same-sex marriages.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.saflii.org/za/cases/ZACC/2015/35.html|title=De Lange v Presiding Bishop of the Methodist Church of Southern Africa for the time being and Another (CCT223/14) [2015] ZACC 35; 2016 (1) BCLR 1 (CC); 2016 (2) SA 1 (CC) (24 November 2015)|website=www.saflii.org|access-date=2017-05-10}}</ref> The Church allowed [gay ministers] to be in a homosexual relationship whilst being a minister, and allowed [a gay minister] to stay in the Church\u2019s manse with [a] partner, but drew the line at recognising her same-sex marriage.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.methodist.org.za/sites/default/files/fileuploads/Judgment%20-%20CCT%20223-14%20-%20De%20Lange%20v%20Presiding%20Bishop%20of%20the%20Methodist%20Chu...%20%282%29.pdf|title=Constitutional Court of South Africa|last=|first=|date=|website=methodist.org.za|access-date=May 10, 2017}}{{dead link|date=November 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n== Methodist Church of Uruguay ==\nThe church, part of the [[Evangelical Church of Uruguay in Uruguay|Evangelical Church of Uruguay]], \"has a ministry with persons of diverse sexual orientations\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oikoumene.org/en/member-churches/methodist-church-of-uruguay|title=Methodist Church of Uruguay \u2014 World Council of Churches|website=www.oikoumene.org|language=en|access-date=2016-05-26}}</ref> The denomination \"resolved that pastors that wish to minister to homosexuals could do so freely\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.laotravozdigital.com/discriminacion-sexual-avances-y-retrocesos-de-las-iglesias-protestantes-historicas/|title=DISCRIMINACI\u00d3N SEXUAL: AVANCES Y RETROCESOS DE LAS IGLESIAS PROTESTANTES HIST\u00d3RICAS - La Otra Voz Digital|website=La Otra Voz Digital|access-date=2016-05-26}}</ref> Since then, some congregations have provided blessing services for same-gender couples.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.republica.com.uy/bendecidos-por-el-clerigo/519053/|title=Bendecidos por el cl\u00e9rigo Front\u00e1n|date=2015-05-31|website=Diario La Rep\u00fablica|language=es-ES|access-date=2016-05-27}}</ref>\n\n==Primitive Methodist Church==\nThe [[Primitive Methodist Church]] teaches that the practice of homosexuality is positively forbidden by Scripture, specifically in [[Epistle to the Romans|Romans]] 1:26-27 and [[Book of Leviticus|Leviticus]] 18:22; 20:13.<ref name=\"PMC - Chapter Eight of The Discipline\"/> With regards to [[Christian views of marriage|marriage]], the Primitive Methodist Church believes it to involve the total commitment of one man and one woman.<ref name=\"PMC - Chapter Eight of The Discipline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.primitivemethodistchurch.org/chapter8.html|title=CHAPTER EIGHT OF THE DISCIPLINE|publisher=[[Primitive Methodist Church]]|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== United Church of Canada ==\nThe United Church of Canada, a member of the [[World Methodist Council]], is a united church which resulted from the merger of multiple denominations including Methodists. The denomination is supportive of LGBT inclusion. The church ordains openly gay and lesbian clergy, and, in 2012, elected its first openly gay moderator to lead the whole denomination.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vancouversun.com/life/Vancouver+reverend+elected+United+Church+Canada+first+openly+moderator/7102657/story.html|title=Vancouver reverend elected United Church of Canada's first openly gay moderator|last=Butler|first=,Don|website=www.vancouversun.com|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref> Since 2003, the UCC has supported same-gender marriage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/united-church-endorses-gay-marriage-1.357106|title=United Church endorses gay marriage|website=www.cbc.ca|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref>\n\n==United Methodist Church==\n{{see also|Paul Abels}}\n{{Recentism|section|date=August 2018}}\n[[File:Twin Cities Pride- Gay Methodist minister interview.webm|thumb|\"Through the labyrinth of booths at the Twin Cities Pride Festival, Faith Forward MN wove its way on Sunday to a row of faith-based organizations. There, we found a stream of interesting stories and perspectives of progressive faith. Here, you'll meet an ordained Methodist minister barred by the United Methodist Church from leading a congregation of his own.\"]]\nAs stated in the ''[[Book of Discipline of The United Methodist Church]]'', the [[United Methodist Church]] holds that \"homosexual persons no less than heterosexual persons are individuals of sacred worth.\"<ref name=\"UMC - Sexuality\"/> In other words, all individuals are of worth to God. Nevertheless, in keeping with historic Church teaching,<ref name=\"Reuters- Historic Teaching on Homosexuality\">{{cite web|url=http://africa.reuters.com/top/news/usnBAN423885.html|title=Episcopal Church faces divisions over gay issues|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=2008-05-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080703161547/http://africa.reuters.com/top/news/usnBAN423885.html|archive-date=2008-07-03|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Defender- Historic Teaching on Homosexuality\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedefender.org/teaching.html|title=Homosexuality|publisher=The Defender|accessdate=2007-05-16}}</ref> it considers the \"practice of homosexuality [to be] incompatible with [[Christianity|Christian]] teaching,\" For this reason, the \"United Methodist Church does not condone the practice of homosexuality\"<ref name=\"UMC - Sexuality\" /> or allow \"[[Coming out|self-avowed practicing homosexual]]s\" to be \"certified as candidates, ordained as ministers, or appointed to serve in The United Methodist Church.\"<ref name=\"UMC - Homosexuality\">{{cite web|url=http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?mid=1324 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121209051506/http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?mid=1324 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-12-09 |title=What is the denomination\u2019s position on homosexuality? |publisher=The United Methodist Church |accessdate=2008-05-16 }}</ref> \n\nBased on its teaching, the United Methodist Church officially prohibits the [[Blessing of same-sex unions in Christian churches|blessing of weddings]] of same-sex couples by its clergy and in its [[Church (building)|churches]].<ref name=\"UMC - Homosexuality\"/> As officiating at a same-sex wedding or [[coming out]] as an openly LGBT Minister is potentially a chargeable offense, numerous Ministers have been put on trial and [[defrocked]],<ref name=\"UMC - Chargeable Offenses\">{{cite web|url=http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?ptid=3&mid=5711 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130416065428/http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?ptid=3&mid=5711 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-04-16 |title=\u00b6 2702. Chargeable Offenses and the Statute of Limitations |publisher=The United Methodist Church |accessdate=2008-05-16 }}</ref> as was the case in 1987, when Methodist minister Rose Mary Denman, was defrocked for being openly gay.<ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/12/03/national/03trial.html?ex=1259730000&en=2bf3ceb5ddafc10e&ei=5090&partner=rssuserland|title=United Methodists Move to Defrock Lesbian|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=2008-05-16 | first=Neela | last=Banerjee | date=2004-12-03}}</ref> Similarly, in 2005, clergy credentials were removed from [[Irene Elizabeth Stroud]] after she was convicted in a church trial of violating Church law by engaging in a lesbian relationship; this conviction was later upheld by the Church Judicial Council, the highest court in the denomination.<ref name=\"Religious Tolerance - Homosexuality UMC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.religioustolerance.org/hom_umc10.htm |title=United Methodist Church (UMC): The trial of Irene Elizabeth Stroud |publisher=Religious Tolerance|accessdate=2008-05-16}}</ref> Other clergy, however, avoided church trials altogether. The Rev. Val Roseqnuist officiated a same-sex marriage in 2016 and reached a 'just resolution', and a church trial was avoided.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/living/religion/article100229657.html|title=Charlotte pastor who married same-sex couple will keep job, avoid church trial|access-date=2016-09-07}}</ref> Also in 2016, a complaint filed against an openly gay minister was dismissed, and the minister was able to continue working.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rmnetwork.org/newrmn/after-complaint-dismissed-rev-blaedel-calls-united-methodists-to-action/|title=After complaint dismissed, Rev. Blaedel calls United Methodists to action|date=2016-08-31|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-07}}</ref>\n\nThe United Methodist Church in addition  supports \"laws in civil society that define marriage as the union of one man and one woman.\"<ref name=\"UMC - Marriage\">{{cite web|url=http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?mid=1722 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130416001724/http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?mid=1722 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-04-16 |title=Marriage |publisher=The United Methodist Church |accessdate=2008-05-16 }}</ref> On April 30, 2008, at the [[General conference (United Methodist Church)|General Conference]], delegates adopted even more conservative language, stating that Christians are called to \"responsible stewardship of this sacred gift\" of sexuality and that \"sexual relations are affirmed only within the covenant of monogamous, heterosexual marriage.\"<ref name=\"UMC - Calendar Item 1186\">{{cite web|url=http://calms.umc.org/2008/Text.aspx?mode=Minority&Number=1186 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728142124/http://calms.umc.org/2008/Text.aspx?mode=Minority&Number=1186 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-07-28 |title=Calendar Item 1186 |publisher=The United Methodist Church |accessdate=2008-05-16 }}</ref> Still, in 2015, the Connectional Table, a general agency of the UMC, proposed a localized option that would permit ministers to officiate same-sex weddings and conferences to ordain openly gay clergy; the Connectional Table, however, cannot legislate church law (a right reserved to the General Conference) and their suggestion was rejected by three-fourths of the delegates at the 2016 General Conference.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Connectional Table votes to submit legislation proposal related to homosexuality|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/connectional-table-votes-to-submit-legislation-related-to-homosexuality|website=www.umc.org|publisher=United Methodist Church|accessdate=November 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UMC Connectional Table Solidifies Commitments to Exclusive Western Liberalism|last=Lomperis|first=John|date=20 December 2017|publisher=Juicy Ecumenism|language=English|accessdate=18 June 2018|url=https://juicyecumenism.com/2017/12/20/umc-connectional-table-solidifies-commitments-exclusive-western-liberalism/}}</ref> \n\nAs a result of decisions made in April 2008 and August 2009,<ref name=\"UMC - Lutheran-United Methodist dialogue timeline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content3.aspx?c=lwL4KnN1LtH&b=5259669&ct=7305103 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090823133108/http://www.umc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content3.aspx?c=lwL4KnN1LtH&b=5259669&ct=7305103 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-08-23 |title=Lutheran-United Methodist dialogue timeline |publisher=The United Methodist Church |accessdate=2009-11-25 }}</ref> the United Methodist Church entered into [[full communion]] with the [[Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]].<ref name=\"Christian Post- ELCA Delegates OK Full Communion with UMC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.christianpost.com/article/20090821/elca-delegates-ok-full-communion-with-umc/index.html|title=ELCA Delegates OK Full Communion with UMC|publisher=[[The Christian Post]]|accessdate=2009-11-25}}</ref> The latter denomination allows individuals in committed homosexual relationships to serve as [[Minister (Christianity)|ministers]],<ref name=\"CARM- The ELCA, homosexuality, and apostasy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.carm.org/elca-and-homosexuality|title=The ELCA, homosexuality, and apostasy|publisher=[[Christian Apologetics and Research Ministry]]|accessdate=2009-11-25}}</ref> while the United Methodist Church requires gay clergy to remain [[Clerical celibacy|celibate]].<ref name=\"UMC - Ecumenical pact does not open door to gay clergy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content.aspx?c=lwL4KnN1LtH&b=5398307&ct=7321637 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130416015835/http://www.umc.org/site/apps/nlnet/content.aspx?c=lwL4KnN1LtH&b=5398307&ct=7321637 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-04-16 |title=Ecumenical pact does not open door to gay clergy |publisher=The United Methodist Church |accessdate=2009-11-25 }}</ref> Despite the fact that full communion allows for the interchangeability of all ordained ministers between the two denominations,<ref name=\"BCNN1 - United Methodist Church says No to Lutheran Homosexual Clergy\">{{cite web|url=http://blackchristiannews.com/news/2009/08/united-methodist-church-says-no-to-lutheran-homosexual-clergy.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304215545/http://blackchristiannews.com/news/2009/08/united-methodist-church-says-no-to-lutheran-homosexual-clergy.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-03-04 |title=United Methodist Church says No to Lutheran Homosexual Clergy |publisher=Black Christian News |accessdate=2009-11-25 }}</ref> Lutheran clergy who are involved in homosexual activity are prohibited to serve in the United Methodist Church in order to uphold the integrity of United Methodist ministerial standards.<ref name=\"UMC - Ecumenical pact does not open door to gay clergy\"/> Nevertheless, the UMC has a more ambiguous policy regarding the ordination of transgender pastors and, in 2008,  the Judicial Council ruled that each regional conference can determine their own policy; as a result, some conferences have ordained transgender pastors.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bartolone|first1=Pauline|title=Methodists Vote to Keep Transgender Pastors|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/bryantpark/2007/10/methodists_vote_to_keep_transg.html|website=www.npr.org|publisher=NPR|accessdate=November 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSeveral [[grassroots]] organizations not officially recognized by the United Methodist Church have also formed around positions on issues relating to homosexuality.  The [[Confessing Movement|Confessing Movement within the United Methodist Church]] seeks to continue to protect the United Methodist Church's current stance on homosexuality, if not make it more rigid. Moreover, another movement, ''Transforming Congregations'', is a Methodist [[ex-gay]] ministry whose purpose is to \"equip the local church to model and minister sanctified sexuality through biblical instruction, personal and public witness, and compassionate outreach.<ref name=\"Transforming Congregations\">{{cite web|url=http://www.transformingcong.org/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19991114235730/http://www.transformingcong.org/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=1999-11-14 |title=Our Purpose |publisher=Transforming Congregations |accessdate=2008-05-16 }}</ref> Meanwhile, the [[Reconciling Ministries Network]] seeks to change the United Methodist Church's current teaching on homosexuality in order to make the church more inclusive of [[LGBT]] people.<ref name=\"RMN-Our Mission\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rmnetwork.org/mission.asp |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090219214254/http://rmnetwork.org/mission.asp |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-02-19 |title=Our Mission |publisher=Reconciling Ministries Network |accessdate=2008-05-16 }}</ref> At the 2008 General Conference of the United Methodist Church, it was decided that the Church would retain its views on homosexuality.<ref name=\"ENI-Homosexuality\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eni.ch/featured/article.php?id=1867 |title=Methodists yes to full communion with Lutherans; no on gay change |publisher=Ecumenical News International |accessdate=2008-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109084955/http://www.eni.ch/featured/article.php?id=1867 |archivedate=2009-01-09 }}</ref> At the General Conference in 2016, the delegates deferred the issue of human sexuality to the Council of Bishops in what has been described as a \"'historic action'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thinkprogress.org/lgbt/2016/05/18/3779705/united-methodist-church-has-a-new-method/|title=United Methodist Church Takes \u2018Historic Action\u2019 Toward LGBT Equality|website=ThinkProgress|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, after General Conference, several [[Annual Conferences of the United Methodist Church|Annual Conferences]] voted in favor of non-discrimination clauses that effectively allowed LGBTQ clergy and which indicated that those conferences would refuse to participate in any church trials in which people were being tried for being an active homosexual. The Baltimore-Washington, California-Nevada, California-Pacific, Desert Southwest, New England, New York, Northern Illinois, and Oregon-Idaho Annual Conferences voted in favor of full inclusion for LGBTQ members and clergy.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gadoua|first1=Renee K.|title=United Methodist conferences petition denomination on behalf of LGBT rights|url=http://www.religionnews.com/2015/06/17/united-methodist-conferences-petition-denomination-behalf-lgbt-rights/|website=www.religionnews.com|publisher=Religion News Service|accessdate=November 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/two-conferences-vote-for-full-inclusion-of-lgbtq|title=Two conferences vote for full inclusion  of LGBTQ - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|access-date=2016-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyac.com/newsdetail/new-england-south-georgia-differ-on-gay-clergy-5073383|title=New England, South Georgia differ on gay clergy|website=www.nyac.com|access-date=2016-06-20}}</ref> Additionally, the Virginia Annual Conference voted to petition the UMC to allow LGBTQ clergy and same-gender marriages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/united-methodist-bodys-support-for-pro-gay-petition-saying-homosexuality-is-part-of-gods-creation-wont-influence-churchs-ban-say-theological-conservatives-140797/|title=United Methodist Body's Pro-Gay Petition Saying Homosexuality Is Part of 'God's Creation' Won't Influence Church's Ban, Say Theological Conservatives|website=Christian Post|access-date=2016-06-20}}</ref> The Rocky Mountain Annual Conference voted to not consider sexual orientation when electing a bishop.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rmcumc.org/petitionsruleselections|title=Rocky Mountain Conference: Rules, Petitions & Elections|last=River|first=Brick|website=www.rmcumc.org|access-date=2016-06-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624184439/http://www.rmcumc.org/petitionsruleselections|archive-date=2016-06-24|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2015, the Great Plains and Greater New Jersey Conferences voted to petition the UMC to allow same-gender marriages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kansas.com/living/religion/article24139798.html|title=Kansas, Nebraska United Methodists support change to homosexual doctrines|website=kansas|access-date=2016-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mississippi-umc.org/newsdetail/news-poll-racism-voted-top-2015-story-3216914|title=The Mississippi Annual Conference of the United Methodist Church|website=www.mississippi-umc.org|access-date=2016-06-20}}</ref> In 2014, the Social and Ethics Ministry of the Central Conference in Germany supported an initiative to propose steps toward the full inclusion of LGBT people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.emk.at/blog/debatte-%C3%BCber-homosexualit%C3%A4t-geht-weiter|title=Debatte \u00fcber Homosexualit\u00e4t geht weiter {{!}} Evangelisch-methodistische Kirche in \u00d6sterreich|website=www.emk.at|access-date=2016-06-20}}</ref> In 2012, the Minnesota Conference had voted to oppose bans on same-gender marriage, and the Illinois Great Rivers and West Michigan Conferences voted that it \"expressed sadness\" at the actions of 2012 General Conference, and the Arkansas Annual Conference voted to encourage respect for multiple perspectives on human sexuality.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/conferences-reject-churchs-stance-on-gays|title=Conferences reject church\u2019s stance on gays - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|access-date=2016-06-20}}</ref> The Detroit, Upper New York, and Wisconsin Conferences also supported resolutions supporting allowing same-gender marriages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://umc-gbcs.org/faith-in-action/annual-conferences-report|title=Annual conferences report  {{!}} gbcs|website=umc-gbcs.org|access-date=2016-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703133602/http://umc-gbcs.org/faith-in-action/annual-conferences-report|archive-date=2016-07-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> Bishop Christian Alsted of the Nordic and Baltic Episcopal Area shared that some of the conferences within his region support same-sex marriage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/sexuality-panel-displays-churchs-global-variation|title=Sexuality panel displays church\u2019s global variation - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|access-date=2016-07-01}}</ref> Within the jurisdictions, the Western Jurisdiction and the North Central Jurisdiction have nominated three openly gay candidates for bishop.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://religionnews.com/2016/06/28/methodists-nominate-3-openly-gay-candidates-for-bishop/|title=Methodists nominate 3 openly gay candidates for bishop|last=Emily|first=More by|website=Religion News Service|access-date=2016-06-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/faith_and_values/2016/07/01/ohioan-among-3-openly-gay-united-methodist-ministers-in-u-s--up-for-bishop.html|title=Ohioan among 3 openly gay United Methodist ministers in U.S. up for bishop|access-date=2016-08-07}}</ref> The Northeastern Jurisdiction passed a resolution supporting same-sex marriage and the ordination of openly gay and lesbian clergy, with the New York body ordaining the first openly gay and lesbian clergy in the denomination.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/resolution-recommends-letting-regional-bodies-adapt-discipline|title=Resolution recommends letting regional bodies adapt Discipline - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|access-date=2016-08-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921100403/http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/resolution-recommends-letting-regional-bodies-adapt-discipline|archive-date=2016-09-21|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyac.com/newsdetail/33-ordained-commissioned-by-new-york-conference-5012427|title=33 Ordained, Commissioned in \"Historic\" Service|website=www.nyac.com|access-date=2016-06-13}}</ref> In 2016, the Baltimore-Washington Conference appointed an openly partnered lesbian to the provisional diaconate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.episcopalcafe.com/us-united-methodists-vs-african-asian-united-methodists/|title=US United Methodists vs African & Asian United Methodists|website=Episcopal Cafe|language=en-US|access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref> In April 2016, Bishop Melvin Talbert performed a same-sex marriage as a public sign of his support for change and full inclusion of LGBT persons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/bishop-again-officiates-at-same-gender-nuptials|title=Bishop again officiates at same-gender nuptials - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|access-date=2016-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160521065619/http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/bishop-again-officiates-at-same-gender-nuptials|archive-date=2016-05-21|url-status=dead}}</ref> The church also provides spousal benefits for non-ordained employees in same-sex marriages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/04/29/methodist-same-sex-marriage-benefits_n_5235596.html|title=Methodist Church Approves Same-Sex Marriage Benefits|last=Service|first=Lauren Markoe Religion News|date=2014-04-29|website=The Huffington Post|access-date=2016-06-21}}</ref> Some congregations have individually voted to perform same-sex marriages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/rural-texas-church-votes-for-same-sex-weddings|title=Rural Texas church votes for same-sex weddings - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|access-date=2016-08-29}}</ref> Also in 2016, the Western Jurisdiction of the denomination elected an openly partnered lesbian as bishop.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/western-jurisdiction-elects-openly-gay-united-methodist-bishop|title=Western Jurisdiction elects openly gay United Methodist bishop - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|access-date=2016-07-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160718232123/http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/western-jurisdiction-elects-openly-gay-united-methodist-bishop|archive-date=2016-07-18|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHowever, two United Methodist bishops \"voided two resolutions in the Northeastern United States that called for defying church restrictions\".<ref name=\"Hahn2016\">{{cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/bishops-overrule-nonconformity-resolutions|title=Bishops overrule nonconformity resolutions|last=Hahn|first=Heather|date=15 September 2016|publisher=The United Methodist Church|language=English|accessdate=15 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916213650/http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/bishops-overrule-nonconformity-resolutions|archive-date=16 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Similarly, the United Methodist Bishops of the Central Conferences of Africa unanimously called for \"unreserved commitment to the Holy Bible as the primary authority for faith and practice in the Church\" and proclaimed that \"sexual relations are affirmed only within the covenant bond of a faithful monogamous, heterosexual marriage, and not within same-sex unions or polygamy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/african-bishops-speak-out-on-terrorism-sexuality|title=African bishops speak out on terrorism, sexuality|last=Hahn|first=Heather|date=4 November 2015|publisher=The United Methodist Church|language=English|accessdate=15 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916131634/http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/african-bishops-speak-out-on-terrorism-sexuality|archive-date=16 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://goodnewsmag.org/2015/11/united-methodist-bishops-from-africa-speak-out/|title=United Methodist Bishops from Africa issue statement|date=4 November 2015|publisher=Good News Magazine|language=English|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://juicyecumenism.com/2015/11/04/bishops-of-the-central-conferences-of-africa-release-statement-encouraging-church-unity-and-a-return-to-doctrine/|title=United Methodist Bishops in Africa Reaffirm Biblical Teaching on Marriage|date=4 November 2015|publisher=[[Institute on Religion and Democracy]]|language=English|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref> United Methodist Bishop Gaspar Jo\u00e3o Domingos stated that \"the United Methodist Church denies the abuse of the principle of tolerance that sets aside the authority of Jesus Christ and the teaching on sexuality.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://juicyecumenism.com/2016/02/08/angolan-bishop-urges-umc-to-stand-firm-on-homosexuality/|title=Angolan Bishop Urges UMC to Stand Firm on Homosexuality|date=8 February 2016|publisher=[[Institute on Religion and Democracy]]|language=English|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref> At the same time, the Alabama-West Florida Conference\" passed resolutions upholding the denomination's rules on homosexuality\" and the Eastern Pennsylvania Conference \"approved a resolution that urges the conference to demand clergy accountability to the Discipline's 'rules of our common covenant,' and to call upon clergy to challenge those rules only 'through legitimate channels of holy conferencing, rather than breaking that covenant.'\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gadoua|first1=Renee K.|title=United Methodist conferences petition denomination on behalf of LGBT rights|url=http://www.religionnews.com/2015/06/17/united-methodist-conferences-petition-denomination-behalf-lgbt-rights/|website=www.religionnews.com|publisher=Religion News|accessdate=November 30, 2015}}</ref> The Southeastern Jurisdiction also voted to maintain the current language in the Book of Discipline.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/southeastern-bishops-decry-nonconformity-plans|title=Southeastern bishops decry 'nonconformity' plans - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|access-date=2016-07-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716055150/http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/southeastern-bishops-decry-nonconformity-plans|archive-date=2016-07-16|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn July 15, 2016, the Western Jurisdictional Conference elected [[Karen Oliveto]] to become the first openly lesbian Bishop in the United Methodist Church. She was consecrated as Bishop on July 16. She recently served as Pastor at Glide Memorial Church, is an ordained elder, teaches students at the Pacific School of Religion, and is on the Advisory Board of the Forum for Theological Education. Bishop Oliveto is married to Robin Ridenour, a Deaconess in the California-Nevada Conference.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/western-jurisdiction-elects-openly-gay-united-methodist-bishop |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-07-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160718232123/http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/western-jurisdiction-elects-openly-gay-united-methodist-bishop |archive-date=2016-07-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/married-lesbian-consecrated-united-methodist-bishop</ref><ref>http://www.rmnetwork.org/newrmn/bishopkarenoliveto/</ref> However, on 25 April 2017, \"In a 6-to-3 vote, the United Methodist Church\u2019s highest court ruled that a married lesbian bishop, and those who consecrated her, had violated church law on marriage and homosexuality\";<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/04/28/us/Methodist-Decision-Oliveto.html?_r=0|title=Methodist Court Declares Gay Bishop\u2019s Consecration Illegal|date=28 April 2017|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|language=English|accessdate=2 May 2017}}</ref> the United Methodist Church held that she \"is in violation of a church law barring the ordination of 'self-avowed practicing homosexuals,' but it did not remove her as bishop, instead sending the issue back to the jurisdiction that chose her.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2017/04/28/gay-bishop-karen-oliveto-methodist-church/|title=Karen Oliveto, first openly gay bishop, in violation of Methodist church law, court says|last1=Brown|first1=Jennifer|first2=Danika|last2=Worthington|date=28 April 2017|publisher=[[The Denver Post]]|language=English|accessdate=2 May 2017}}</ref> Therefore, the Judicial Council ruled that \"Bishop Oliveto 'remains in good standing,' until an administrative or judicial process is completed.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/president-of-the-council-of-bishops-statement-regarding-judicial-council-de|title=President of the Council of Bishops: Statement regarding Judicial Council decision 1341 - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|language=en|access-date=2017-05-09}}</ref> However, the Judicial Council also ruled that \"she was in good standing\" and that \"it had no jurisdiction to review Bishop Oliveto's nomination, election, and assignment.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/blogs-commentaries/post/commentary-attorney-on-confusion-over-olivetos-status|title=Commentary: Attorney on confusion over Oliveto\u2019s status - The United Methodist Church|last=Communications|first=United Methodist|website=The United Methodist Church|language=en|access-date=2017-05-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508225934/http://www.umc.org/news-and-media/blogs-commentaries/post/commentary-attorney-on-confusion-over-olivetos-status|archive-date=2017-05-08|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn May 7, 2018 the Council of Bishops in the United Methodist Church proposed allowing individual pastors and regional church bodies to decide whether to ordain LGBT clergy and perform same-sex weddings, though this proposal can only be approved by the General Conference.<ref>[https://www.advocate.com/religion/2018/5/05/methodist-bishops-back-choice-lgbt-clergy-same-sex-marriage Advocate: Methodist Bishops Back Choice on LGBT Clergy, Same-Sex Marriage]</ref> At this meeting, the Council of Bishops will also consider 2 other alternative plans for the future concerning this issue. The second plan called the Connectional Conference Plan would create three connectional conferences based on theology related to the issue of human sexuality, the current five conferences would be abolished and each of the five conferences would have clearly defined values of accountability, contextualization, and justice. These three denominations would serve almost as three sub-denominations within overall United Methodism.  The third plan, called the Traditional Plan, would reinforce the existing language in the Book of Discipline prohibiting homosexuality, gay marriage ceremonies on church campuses, and allow for stricter enforcement of violations of existing church law.<ref>[https://www.umnews.org/en/news/ask-the-umc-can-you-explain-way-forward-plans-cob-recommendation Ask The UMC:Can you explain Way Forward plans, COB reccomendation?]</ref>  On February 26, 2019, during a special session of the General Conference, delegates from around the world voted to pass the Traditional Plan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/02/26/698188343/united-methodist-church-votes-to-keep-bans-on-same-sex-weddings-lgbtq-clergy|title=United Methodist Church Votes To Keep Bans On Same-Sex Weddings, LGBTQ Clergy|last=Chappell|first=Bill|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, the [[Central conferences (United Methodist Church)|German Central Conference]] announced that it would not be implementing the Traditional Plan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.umnews.org:443/en/news/german-church-wont-impose-traditional-plan-bans|title=German church won\u2019t impose Traditional Plan bans|website=United Methodist News Service|language=en|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref> Although the [[Annual conferences of the United Methodist Church|US jurisdictions and annual conferences]] are unable to alter the Book of Discipline as the Central Conferences are, the Western Jurisdiction declared their disagreement with the Traditional Plan and vowed to remain LGBTQ inclusive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://westernjurisdictionumc.org/western-jurisdiction-umc-bishops-video-statement-script/|title=Western Jurisdiction UMC Bishops video statement script|last=UMC|first=Western Jurisdiction|date=2019-03-01|website=Western Jurisdiction of The UMC|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, a 16-person committee of bishops and other official submitted to the General Conference a scism proposal for the creation of a new separated \"traditional Methodist\" denomination, a text that still needs to be approved by the conference in May. By default, any parish will be set as a member of the United Methodist Church (UMC) and would have to conduct votes in order to enter in the newborn communion of the more conservative Methodists.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n== Uniting Church in Australia ==\nThe denomination has permitted presbyteries to ordain openly gay and lesbian ministers if they opt to do so<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/7.30/content/2003/s906981.htm|title=7.30 Report|website=www.abc.net.au|access-date=2016-05-21}}</ref> and churches may bless same-sex couples entering into civil partnerships.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/wa/a/28769619/uniting-church-may-overhaul-rules-of-marriage/|title=Church may overhaul its rules of marriage|website=au.news.yahoo.com|access-date=2016-05-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401170740/https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/wa/a/28769619/uniting-church-may-overhaul-rules-of-marriage/|archive-date=2016-04-01|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 13 July 2018, the Uniting Church in Australia voted by national Assembly to approve the creation of official marriage rites for same-sex couples.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sandeman |first=John |date=13 July 2018 |title=Uniting Church to hold same sex marriages |url=https://www.eternitynews.com.au/australia/uniting-church-to-hold-same-sex-marriage/ |work=Eternity |location=Australia |access-date=13 July 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Methodism|Evangelical Christianity|LGBT}}\n*[[Paul Abels]]\n*[[Gene Leggett]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.garyhopkins.net/pilgrimageoffaith/ Pilgrimage of Faith Research:] Research about homosexuality and the Methodist Church of Great Britain\n*[https://rmnetwork.org/ Reconciling Ministries Network] The largest organization working for equality for LGBT United Methodists \n\n{{Methodism footer}}\n{{Religion and LGBT people}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Homosexuality And Methodism}}\n[[Category:LGBT topics and Protestantism|Methodism]]\n[[Category:Methodism]]\n", "name_user": "Queerumc", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUnited Methodist Church:more historical information and an additional source was added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homosexuality_and_Methodism"}
{"title_page": "Ezra Miller", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American actor}}\n{{For|the politician|Ezra Miller (politician)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Ezra Miller \n| image        = Ezra Miller by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption      = Miller at the 2016 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name   = Ezra Matthew Miller\n| birth_date   = <!--- September 30, 1992 is correct, check the referenced article, which mentions their 19th birthday in September 2011, http://ezra-miller.com/gallery/albums/userpics/10001/BG_NYLON_JAN12_05.jpg --->{{birth date and age|1992|9|30}}<!--- September 30, 1992 is correct, check the referenced article, which mentions their 19th birthday in September 2011, http://ezra-miller.com/gallery/albums/userpics/10001/BG_NYLON_JAN12_05.jpg --->\n| birth_place  = [[Wyckoff, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| occupation   = Actor\n| years_active = 2007\u2013present\n}}\n<!-- NOTE: Per issues regarding Miller's GENDER IDENTITY (sources referring to Miller as \"he\" while Miller identifies as neither male nor female...but has not made clear preferred gender pronouns, and the confusion \"singular they\" usage causes), we avoid masculine pronouns in the article and use singular they sparingly. Use of the Miller surname where possible is preferred. See the talk page discussion about this. -->\n'''Ezra Matthew Miller'''<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/11176/1156185-58.stm |title=Actor faces charges for marijuana in Peters |publisher=Post-gazette.com |date=2011-06-25 |accessdate=2011-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Tribune |first=Pittsburgh |url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/news/regional/s_743898.html |title='Wallflower' actor faces drug chages - Pittsburgh Tribune-Review|publisher=Pittsburghlive.com |date=2011-06-25 |accessdate=2011-10-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120906085801/http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/news/regional/s_743898.html |archivedate=2012-09-06 }}</ref> (born <!--- September 30, 1992 is correct, check the referenced article, which mentions their 19th birthday in September 2011, http://ezra-miller.com/gallery/albums/userpics/10001/BG_NYLON_JAN12_05.jpg --->September 30, 1992<!--- September 30, 1992 is correct, check the referenced article, which mentions their 19th birthday in September 2011, http://ezra-miller.com/gallery/albums/userpics/10001/BG_NYLON_JAN12_05.jpg --->)<ref name=onyls1>{{Cite news|last=Harvkey|first=Mike|title=Ezra Miller|publisher=Nylon Magazine|year=2012|url=http://ezra-miller.com/gallery/albums/userpics/10001/BG_NYLON_JAN12_05.jpg|accessdate=2012-01-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426044332/http://ezra-miller.com/gallery/albums/userpics/10001/BG_NYLON_JAN12_05.jpg|archivedate=2012-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/11283/1180683-60-0.stm |title=Authentic movie clothing requires lots of shopping |publisher=Post-gazette.com |date=2011-10-10 |accessdate=2011-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Osborn |first=Michael |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-15365179 |title=BBC News - Talk About Kevin: Portrait of a parent's worst nightmare |publisher=bbc.co.uk |date=2011-10-21 |accessdate=2011-11-09|work=BBC News }}</ref> is an American actor. Miller's feature film debut was in ''[[Afterschool]]'' (2008). Miller starred as Kevin in the drama ''[[We Need to Talk About Kevin (film)|We Need to Talk About Kevin]]'' (2011) and co-starred in the film adaptation of ''[[The Perks of Being a Wallflower (film)|The Perks of Being a Wallflower]]'' (2012). In 2015, Miller co-starred in the drama ''[[The Stanford Prison Experiment (film)|The Stanford Prison Experiment]]'' and the comedy ''[[Trainwreck (film)|Trainwreck]]''. Miller played Credence Barebone in the ''[[Wizarding World#Fantastic Beasts films|Fantastic Beasts]]'' films ''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]'' (2016) and ''[[Fantastic Beasts: The Crimes of Grindelwald]]'' (2018).\n\nMiller also portrays [[Flash (Barry Allen)|Barry Allen / The Flash]] in the [[DC Extended Universe]], beginning with a minor role in ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]'' (2016), a cameo in ''[[Suicide Squad (film)|Suicide Squad]]'' (2016) and later as one of the leads in ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]'' (2017). Miller also reprised the role of Barry Allen on television in [[The CW]]'s ''[[Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)|Crisis on Infinite Earths]]'' crossover in 2020.\n\n==Early life==\nMiller was born and raised in [[Wyckoff, New Jersey|Wyckoff]], [[New Jersey]].<ref>Beckerman, Jim; and Rohan, Virginia. [http://www.northjersey.com/arts_entertainment/138023858_Our_picks_for_Oscar_s_top_honors.html \"Our picks for Oscar's top honors\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224100211/http://www.northjersey.com/arts_entertainment/138023858_Our_picks_for_Oscar_s_top_honors.html |date=2013-12-24 }}, ''[[The Record (Bergen County)]]'', January 25, 2012. Accessed June 7, 2012. \"And what happened to Tilda Swinton, Leonardo DiCaprio and Wyckoff's Ezra Miller (a Best Supporting Actor possibility for \"We Need to Talk About Kevin\")?\"</ref><ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|last=Bosworth|first=Kate|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/ezra-miller/|title=Ezra Miller|work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|quote =|date=2011-04-06|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lamble |first=David |url=http://www.ebar.com/arts/art_article.php?sec=film&article=976 |title=The Bay Area Reporter Online &#124; We need to talk about Ezra Miller |publisher=Ebar.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-23}}</ref> Miller has two older sisters, Saiya and Caitlin.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> Miller's mother, Marta Miller (n\u00e9e Koch), is a modern dancer.<ref name=autogenerated3/> Miller's father, Robert S. Miller, was senior vice president and managing director of [[Hachette Books#Hyperion Books|Hyperion Books]], and later became a publisher at [[Workman Publishing Company|Workman Publishing]].<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.co.uk/cgi/news/release?id=50644 |title=Walt Disney Company To Reorganise Publishing Business: Disney Publishing, Worldwide And Hyperion |publisher=Prnewswire.co.uk |date=1999-04-12 |accessdate=2011-10-25}} and is now the President of Macmillan's newest imprint, Flatiron Books.</ref><ref name=nymg1>{{Cite news|last=Yuan|first=Jada|title=We Need to Talk About Ezra|pages=|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=2012-01-08|url=https://nymag.com/movies/features/ezra-miller-2012-1/|accessdate=2012-01-11}}</ref> Miller's father is [[Jewish]] and Miller's mother, who has German and Dutch ancestry, is from a Christian background.<ref>{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Moran|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/the-diary/meet-the-latest-jewish-superhero-1.448384|title=Meet The Flash, the latest Jewish superhero|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=November 20, 2017|accessdate=May 5, 2018}}</ref> Miller self-identifies as Jewish and \"spiritual\".<ref name=hrt1>{{Cite news|last=Saar|first=Yuval|title=Ezra's Way (Weekend)|pages=|publisher=[[Haaretz]]|date=2012-01-19|url=http://www.haaretz.co.il/magazine/1.1620442|accessdate=2012-06-01|quote=\"My father is Jewish, my mother is not, but I consider myself entirely Jewish even though according to Jewish law I am not. I encourage everyone to understand that the rules were written before anyone could do DNA tests... I know that I am a descendant of Abraham through my father.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interfaithfamily.com/arts_and_entertainment/popular_culture/Interfaith_Celebrities_An_Upcoming_Actor_An_Enduring_Celebrity_Interfaith_Marriage_and_Sheriff_Andys_Jewish_Roots.shtml|title=Interfaith Celebrities: An Upcoming Actor, An Enduring Celebrity \u2013 InterfaithFamily|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=reps1>{{Cite news|last=Lamble|first=David|title=Family estrangement|pages=|publisher=The Bay Area Reporter|date=2011-12-08|url=http://www.cpanel.ebar.com/arts/art_article.php?sec=film&article=946|accessdate=2012-01-11}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of six, Miller started to train as an [[opera]] singer, in order to overcome a speech impediment.<ref name = out>{{cite web|author=Shana Naomi Krochmal|url=http://www.out.com/entertainment/movies/2012/08/15/perks-wallflower-ezra-miller-logan-lerman-johnny-simmons?page=0,2|title=Lost & Found|publisher=[[Out Magazine]]|date=2012-08-15|accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref> Miller has sung with the [[Metropolitan Opera]],<ref>{{cite web|last=VanAirsdale|first=S.T.|url=http://www.movieline.com/2010/04/the-verge-ezra-miller.php?page=all|title=The Verge: Ezra Miller|work=[[Movieline]]|date=2010-04-26|accessdate=2011-05-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100503031028/http://www.movieline.com/2010/04/the-verge-ezra-miller.php?page=all|archive-date=2010-05-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> and performed in the American premiere of [[Philip Glass]]'s opera ''White Raven''.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\" /> Miller attended [[Rockland Country Day School]] and [[The Hudson School]], dropping out at age 16<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2014/10/ezra-miller-the-flash-movie-gay/|title=Ezra Miller: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|last=Barbuti|first=Angela|date=2014-10-15|work=Heavy.com|access-date=2018-01-31|language=en-US}}</ref> after the release of the film ''[[Afterschool]]''.<ref name=\"nymg1\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecinemasource.com/blog/interviews/ezra-miller-interview-for-beware-the-gonzo/ |title=Ezra Miller Interview for Beware the Gonzo |publisher=The Cinema Source |date=2011-09-08 |accessdate=2011-10-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928071241/http://www.thecinemasource.com/blog/interviews/ezra-miller-interview-for-beware-the-gonzo/ |archivedate=2011-09-28 }}</ref><ref name=\"dsblse\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/09/18/ezra-miller-on-perks-of-being-a-wallflower-being-bisexual-more.html|title=Ezra Miller on 'Perks of Being a Wallflower,' Being Bisexual & More|newspaper=The Daily Beast|date=2012-09-18|last1=Stern|first1=Marlow}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Ezra Miller at the 2009 Tribeca Film Festival.jpg|thumb|upright|Miller at the 2009 Tribeca Film Festival]]\n\nMiller's start in film began in 2008 with [[Antonio Campos (director)|Antonio Campos]]' ''Afterschool'', in the role of a teenager at a boarding school who accidentally films the drug-related deaths of two classmates, and is then asked to put together a memorial video.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> Miller appeared in ''[[City Island (film)|City Island]]'' (2009), with [[Andy Garc\u00eda]], [[Julianna Margulies]], and [[Steven Strait]], and co-starred in ''[[Beware the Gonzo]]'' and ''[[Every Day (2010 film)|Every Day]]'', both of which premiered at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]]. Miller next appeared in the [[BBC Films]] film ''[[We Need to Talk About Kevin (film)|We Need to Talk About Kevin]]'' (2011), alongside [[Tilda Swinton]] and [[John C. Reilly]], which was adapted and directed by [[Lynne Ramsay]] from American author [[Lionel Shriver]]'s [[We Need to Talk About Kevin|2003 novel of the same name]]. Miller played Damien on the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] hit comedy series ''[[Californication (TV series)|Californication]]''.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/story/ezra-miller-cleared-on-drug-charge_1231177 |title=Ezra Miller &#124; Ezra Miller Cleared On Drug Charge |publisher=Contactmusic |date= 2011-07-05|accessdate=2011-10-25}}</ref> Miller appeared on ''[[Royal Pains]]'' as Tucker Bryant for two seasons. In the 2012 [[The Perks of Being a Wallflower (film)|film adaptation]] of the novel ''[[The Perks of Being a Wallflower]]'' Miller played Patrick, alongside [[Logan Lerman]] and [[Emma Watson]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilkinson|first=Amy|url=http://hollywoodcrush.mtv.com/2011/05/19/ezra-miller-perks-of-being-a-wallflower|title=Ezra Miller To Play Patrick In 'Perks of Being a Wallflower'|work=[[MTV]]|date=2011-05-19|accessdate=2011-05-26}}</ref>\n\nMiller has been credited with singing, drumming and percussion on musical recordings by the band Sons of an Illustrious Father,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sonsofanillustriousfather.bandcamp.com/|title=Sons of an Illustrious Father|website=Sons of an Illustrious Father}}</ref> as early as 2011. The band is a trio that features Lilah Larson (vocals, guitar, bass and drums), Josh Aubin (bass, keyboards, guitar, vocals) and Miller.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://azdailysun.com/flaglive/cover_story/fearless-genre-queer-brooklyn-based-trio-sons-of-an-illustrious/article_2aa7e0b5-6c8f-5178-8dfc-25a7643622be.html|title=Fearless & Genre Queer: Brooklyn-based trio Sons of an Illustrious Father offers sanctuary through music|first=Taylor|last=Haynes|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sonsofanillustriousfather.com/|title=Sons of an Illustrious father|website=Sons of an Illustrious Father}}</ref> In 2019, the band released a cover of \"Don't Cha\" by Pussycat Dolls and Miller was seen in its music video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://etcanada.com/news/453362/ezra-miller-covers-the-pussycat-dolls-dont-cha-in-creepy-new-music-video/|title=Ezra Miller Covers The Pussycat Dolls' 'Don't Cha' In Creepy New Music Video|last=Atad|first=Corey|date=16 May 2019|website=ET Canada|access-date=17 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nMiller played Credence Barebone in the 2016 film ''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]'', a spin-off of the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'' film series]]. Miller reprised the role in the film's sequel, ''[[Fantastic Beasts: The Crimes of Grindelwald]]'', which was released in November 2018.\n\nMiller portrays [[Flash (Barry Allen)|Barry Allen / The Flash]] in [[Warner Bros.]]' [[DC Comics]] adaptations, first appearing in cameos in ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]'' and ''[[Suicide Squad (film)|Suicide Squad]]'', and continuing the role as one of the leads in ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]''. Miller is set to play the character in the standalone film ''[[Flashpoint (DCEU)|The Flash]]''.<ref name=\"auto\">[https://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-flash-movie-ezra-miller-aquaman-jason-momoa-2018-1201330654 \"''The Flash'' Movie to Star Ezra Miller, Out in 2018\"]. Variety.</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/warner-bros-flash-movie-star-741019|title=Warner Bros.' ''The Flash'' Movie to Star Ezra Miller|author=|date=October 15, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> Miller attended [[Middle East Film and Comic Con]] in 2018 representing their character in the DC Comics franchise film ''Justice League''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/life-style/celebrity/hollywood/mefcc-2018-ezra-miller-karl-urban-on-keeping-secrets-1.2200790|title=MEFCC 2018: Ezra Miller, Karl Urban on keeping secrets|last=Reporter|first=Marwa Hamad, Senior|date=2018-04-06|work=GulfNews|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref> In 2020, Miller reprised the role of The Flash for a cameo appearance in the [[Arrowverse]] crossover event, ''[[Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)|Crisis on Infinite Earths]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nMiller [[came out]] as [[queer]] in 2012.<ref name =\"Jackman\">{{cite web|author=Josh Jackman|title=Ezra Miller: I have a polyamorous squad of sexual partners|work=[[Pink News]]|date=November 16, 2018|accessdate=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/11/16/ezra-miller-polyamorous-sexual-partners/}}</ref> Having expressed an interest in \"kissing boys\" at a young age,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_z_BR0ERa9g|title=Ezra Miller talks about realizing as a kid they liked kissing boys|website=YouTube|publisher=Rosa Gamazo|accessdate=November 18, 2016}}</ref> Miller stated, \"The way I would choose to identify myself wouldn't be gay. I've been attracted mostly to 'shes' but I've been with many people and I'm open to love whatever it can be.\"<ref name=dsblse/> Miller also commented on having \"a lot of really wonderful friends who are of very different sexes and genders. I am very much in love with no one in particular.\"<ref name = out/><ref>{{cite web|author=Lawrence Ferber|url=http://www.nextmagazine.com/content/ezra-miller-says-he-has-had-gay-moments|title=Ezra Miller Says He Has Had Gay Moments|publisher=[[Next Magazine (New York City)|Next Magazine]]|date=2012-01-16|accessdate=2012-05-31|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120904172408/http://www.nextmagazine.com/content/ezra-miller-says-he-has-had-gay-moments|archivedate=2012-09-04}}</ref> \n\nMiller uses [[Singular they|they/them pronouns]], which ''[[GQ|GQ Britain]]'' stated is done \"in a pointed refusal to be gendered\".<ref name=\"GQ Britain\">{{cite news|url=https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/fashion/article/ezra-miller-interview |title=We're Obsessed With Ezra Miller's Gender Fluid GQ Photo Shoot|work=[[GQ|GQ Britain]] |location=London, UK |publisher=Conde Nast |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> Miller stated that, for them, ''queer'' means \"I don't identify as a man. I don't identify as a woman. I barely identify as a human.\"<ref name=\"lgbtqnation\">{{cite news |last1=Bollinger |first1=Alex |title=Actor Ezra Miller says they don't identify as a man or a woman |url=https://www.lgbtqnation.com/2018/11/actor-ezra-miller-says-doesnt-identify-man-woman/ |work=LGBTQ Nation |date=November 8, 2018}}</ref> Having used all pronouns interchangeably,<ref>{{cite news |last=Randall |first=Devin |url=http://instinctmagazine.com/post/were-obsessed-ezra-millers-gender-fluid-gq-photo-shoot |title=We're Obsessed With Ezra Miller's Gender Fluid GQ Photo Shoot |work=[[Instinct (magazine)|Instinct]] |location=Burbank, California |publisher=Juki Media |date=November 7, 2018 |accessdate=November 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181114034408/http://instinctmagazine.com/post/were-obsessed-ezra-millers-gender-fluid-gq-photo-shoot |archive-date=November 14, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Miller has also stated that they are \"comfortable with all the pronouns\" and that they \"let he/his/him ride, and that's fine.\"<ref name =\"Jones\">{{cite web|author=Allie Jones|title=Ezra Miller Is the Gender-Bending, Goat-Delivering Hollywood Star of the Future|work=[[GQ]]|date=November 5, 2018|accessdate=March 15, 2020|url=https://www.gq.com/story/ezra-miller-gq-style-cover-story}}</ref> Although Miller has been credited as a [[queer icon]], ''GQ Britain'' stated that they also eschew the term ''queer'', \"as even ''queer'' is a label to them\".<ref name=\"GQ Britain\"/> \n \nMiller revealed having had a personal #[[MeToo]] experience with a Hollywood producer and a director, both unnamed. Miller said, \"They gave me wine and I was underaged. They were like, 'Hey, want to be in our movie about gay revolution?' And I was like, 'No, you guys are monsters.'\" Miller then went on to show support for the #MeToo movement.<ref name=lgbtqnation/>\n\nIn 2010, Miller dated [[Zoe Kravitz]] while they were filming ''[[Beware the Gonzo]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://liverampup.com/entertainment/ezra-miller-gay-girlfriend-boyfriend-dating-ethnicity.html|title=Ezra Miller aka Flash Says 'I'm Queer' Not Gay; Boyfriend & Dating Amid Confusion?|date=May 16, 2019|work=Liverampup.com|access-date=September 8, 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\nOn June 28, 2011, in [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]], while shooting ''The Perks of Being a Wallflower'', Miller was a passenger in a vehicle that was pulled over for a broken brake light, and police discovered 20 grams of [[marijuana]] in their possession.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{cite web|last=Glinow|first=Kiki|url=http://www.popeater.com/2011/06/29/ezra-miller-the-perks-of-being-a-wallflower-marijuana-possession-arrested/|title='Wallflower' Star Ezra Miller Busted for Marijuana Possession|website=|quote=|date=2011-06-29|accessdate=2011-06-29}}</ref> Initially, Miller was charged with drug possession, but the charge was later dropped by a judge. Instead, Miller faced a penalty of $600 for two citations of disorderly conduct.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Miller later commented: \"I don't feel like there's any need to hide the fact that I smoke pot. It's a harmless herbal substance that increases sensory appreciation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/movies/features/ezra-miller-2012-1/index1.html |title=Ezra Miller on Their Roles in ''Another Happy Day'' and ''We Need to Talk About Kevin''|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=2012-01-08 |accessdate=2012-01-11}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2020, in [[Reykjav\u00edk|Reykjavik, Iceland]], Miller was involved in an altercation at a bar which occurred after Miller was confronted by a group of eager fans that caused Miller to lose their temper. According to a video of the incident, which surfaced on April 5, 2020, Miller grabbed a woman by her throat and threw her to the ground, at which point the video cuts out. A source at the establishment confirmed the seriousness of the altercation and that Miller, angry and upset, was escorted off the premises following the incident.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/ezra-miller-throttling-woman-video-1234571800/|title=Ezra Miller Appears to Choke Woman in Video|last=Ravindran|first=Tim Dams,Manori|last2=Dams|first2=Tim|date=2020-04-06|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|last3=Ravindran|first3=Manori}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title \n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Afterschool]]''\n| Robert\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[City Island (film)|City Island]]''\n| Vincent \"Vinnie\" Rizzo Jr.\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2010\n| ''[[Beware the Gonzo]]''\n| Eddie \"Gonzo\" Gilman\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Every Day (2010 film)|Every Day]]''\n| Jonah\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2011\n| ''[[Another Happy Day]]''\n| Elliot Hellman\n|\n|-\n| ''Busted Walk''\n| Jay Turner\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''[[We Need to Talk About Kevin (film)|We Need to Talk About Kevin]]''\n| Kevin Khatchadourian\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[The Perks of Being a Wallflower (film)|The Perks of Being a Wallflower]]''\n| Patrick\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Madame Bovary (2014 film)|Madame Bovary]]''\n| Leon Dupuis\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2015\n| ''[[The Stanford Prison Experiment (film)|The Stanford Prison Experiment]]''\n| Daniel Culp / Prisoner 8612\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Trainwreck (film)|Trainwreck]]''\n| Donald\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2016\n| ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]''\n| rowspan=2|[[Flash (Barry Allen)|Barry Allen / The Flash]]\n|\n|-\n|''[[Suicide Squad (film)|Suicide Squad]]''\n| Cameo \n|-\n| ''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]''\n| Credence Barebone\n| \n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]''\n|Barry Allen / The Flash\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n|''[[Fantastic Beasts: The Crimes of Grindelwald]]''\n|Credence Barebone\n|\n|}\n<!-- Do not add movies not in production per [[WP:CRYSTAL]]. They will be removed -->\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2008\n| ''Cakey! The Cake from Outer Space''\n| Bully\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Californication (TV series)|Californication]]''\n| Damien Patterson\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n| Ethan Morse\n| Episode: \"Crush\"\n|-\n| 2009\u20132010\n| ''[[Royal Pains]]''\n| Tucker Bryant\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Arrow (TV series)|Arrow]]''\n| Barry Allen / The Flash\n| Episode: \"[[Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)|Crisis on Infinite Earths: Part Four]]\" Cameo\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title \n! Voice role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Lego Dimensions]]''\n| Credence Barebone\n|\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2011\n| [[Hamptons International Film Festival|Hamptons International Film Festival for Breakthrough Performer]]\n| ''[[Another Happy Day]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[BIFA Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n| rowspan=2|''[[We Need to Talk About Kevin (film)|We Need to Talk About Kevin]]''\n|rowspan=2 {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=6|[[17th Critics' Choice Awards|2012]]\n| [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Young Performer]]\n|-\n| [[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n| rowspan=8|''[[The Perks of Being a Wallflower (film)|The Perks of Being a Wallflower]]''\n|rowspan=4 {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Hollywood Film Festival|Hollywood Film Festival Spotlight Award]]\n|-\n| [[San Diego Film Critics Society Award for Best Cast]]\n|-\n| [[Santa Barbara International Film Festival|Santa Barbara International Film Festival \u2014 Virtuoso Award]]\n|-\n| [[Detroit Film Critics Society Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n|rowspan=5 {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[2013 MTV Movie Awards|2013]]\n| [[MTV Movie Award for Next Generation|MTV Movie Award for Best Breakthrough Performance]]\n|-\n| [[2013 MTV Movie Awards#Best Musical Moment|MTV Movie Awards for Best Musical Moment]] {{small|(shared with [[Logan Lerman]] and [[Emma Watson]])}}\n|-\n| Phoenix Film Critics Society Award for Best Supporting Actor\n|-\n|2017\n|San Diego Film Critics Society Award for Best Comedic Performance\n|''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q508049|c=Category:Ezra Miller|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|s=no|wikt=no}}\n* {{IMDb name|3009232}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Ezra Miller\n|list =\n{{Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actor}}\n{{Cannes Film Festival Revelation Award}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miller, Ezra}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American drummers]]\n[[Category:American drummers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American child singers]]\n[[Category:American child actors]]\n[[Category:American film actors]]\n[[Category:Models from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:American television actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Jewish American actors]]\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish rock musicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:Actors from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Wyckoff, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Queer actors]]\n[[Category:Queer musicians]]\n[[Category:Singers from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:The Hudson School alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American drummers]]\n[[Category:Non-binary actors]]\n[[Category:Actors of German descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American actor}}\n{{For|the politician|Ezra Miller (politician)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Ezra Miller \n| image        = Ezra Miller by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption      = Miller at the 2016 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birth_name   = Ezra Matthew Miller\n| birth_date   = <!--- September 30, 1992 is correct, check the referenced article, which mentions their 19th birthday in September 2011, http://ezra-miller.com/gallery/albums/userpics/10001/BG_NYLON_JAN12_05.jpg --->{{birth date and age|1992|9|30}}<!--- September 30, 1992 is correct, check the referenced article, which mentions their 19th birthday in September 2011, http://ezra-miller.com/gallery/albums/userpics/10001/BG_NYLON_JAN12_05.jpg --->\n| birth_place  = [[Wyckoff, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| occupation   = Actor\n| years_active = 2007\u2013present\n}}\n<!-- NOTE: Per issues regarding Miller's GENDER IDENTITY (sources referring to Miller as \"he\" while Miller identifies as neither male nor female...but has not made clear preferred gender pronouns, and the confusion \"singular they\" usage causes), we avoid masculine pronouns in the article and use singular they sparingly. Use of the Miller surname where possible is preferred. See the talk page discussion about this. -->\n'''Ezra Matthew Miller'''<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/11176/1156185-58.stm |title=Actor faces charges for marijuana in Peters |publisher=Post-gazette.com |date=2011-06-25 |accessdate=2011-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Tribune |first=Pittsburgh |url=http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/news/regional/s_743898.html |title='Wallflower' actor faces drug chages - Pittsburgh Tribune-Review|publisher=Pittsburghlive.com |date=2011-06-25 |accessdate=2011-10-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120906085801/http://www.pittsburghlive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/news/regional/s_743898.html |archivedate=2012-09-06 }}</ref> (born <!--- September 30, 1992 is correct, check the referenced article, which mentions their 19th birthday in September 2011, http://ezra-miller.com/gallery/albums/userpics/10001/BG_NYLON_JAN12_05.jpg --->September 30, 1992<!--- September 30, 1992 is correct, check the referenced article, which mentions their 19th birthday in September 2011, http://ezra-miller.com/gallery/albums/userpics/10001/BG_NYLON_JAN12_05.jpg --->)<ref name=onyls1>{{Cite news|last=Harvkey|first=Mike|title=Ezra Miller|publisher=Nylon Magazine|year=2012|url=http://ezra-miller.com/gallery/albums/userpics/10001/BG_NYLON_JAN12_05.jpg|accessdate=2012-01-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426044332/http://ezra-miller.com/gallery/albums/userpics/10001/BG_NYLON_JAN12_05.jpg|archivedate=2012-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/11283/1180683-60-0.stm |title=Authentic movie clothing requires lots of shopping |publisher=Post-gazette.com |date=2011-10-10 |accessdate=2011-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Osborn |first=Michael |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-15365179 |title=BBC News - Talk About Kevin: Portrait of a parent's worst nightmare |publisher=bbc.co.uk |date=2011-10-21 |accessdate=2011-11-09|work=BBC News }}</ref> is an American actor. Miller's feature film debut was in ''[[Afterschool]]'' (2008). Miller starred as Kevin in the drama ''[[We Need to Talk About Kevin (film)|We Need to Talk About Kevin]]'' (2011) and co-starred in the film adaptation of ''[[The Perks of Being a Wallflower (film)|The Perks of Being a Wallflower]]'' (2012). In 2015, Miller co-starred in the drama ''[[The Stanford Prison Experiment (film)|The Stanford Prison Experiment]]'' and the comedy ''[[Trainwreck (film)|Trainwreck]]''. Miller played Credence Barebone in the ''[[Wizarding World#Fantastic Beasts films|Fantastic Beasts]]'' films ''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]'' (2016) and ''[[Fantastic Beasts: The Crimes of Grindelwald]]'' (2018).\n\nMiller also portrays [[Flash (Barry Allen)|Barry Allen / The Flash]] in the [[DC Extended Universe]], beginning with a minor role in ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]'' (2016), a cameo in ''[[Suicide Squad (film)|Suicide Squad]]'' (2016) and later as one of the leads in ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]'' (2017). Miller also reprised the role of Barry Allen on television in [[The CW]]'s ''[[Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)|Crisis on Infinite Earths]]'' crossover in 2020.\n\n==Early life==\nMiller was born and raised in [[Wyckoff, New Jersey|Wyckoff]], [[New Jersey]].<ref>Beckerman, Jim; and Rohan, Virginia. [http://www.northjersey.com/arts_entertainment/138023858_Our_picks_for_Oscar_s_top_honors.html \"Our picks for Oscar's top honors\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224100211/http://www.northjersey.com/arts_entertainment/138023858_Our_picks_for_Oscar_s_top_honors.html |date=2013-12-24 }}, ''[[The Record (Bergen County)]]'', January 25, 2012. Accessed June 7, 2012. \"And what happened to Tilda Swinton, Leonardo DiCaprio and Wyckoff's Ezra Miller (a Best Supporting Actor possibility for \"We Need to Talk About Kevin\")?\"</ref><ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|last=Bosworth|first=Kate|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/ezra-miller/|title=Ezra Miller|work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|quote =|date=2011-04-06|accessdate=2011-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lamble |first=David |url=http://www.ebar.com/arts/art_article.php?sec=film&article=976 |title=The Bay Area Reporter Online &#124; We need to talk about Ezra Miller |publisher=Ebar.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-23}}</ref> Miller has two older sisters, Saiya and Caitlin.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> Miller's mother, Marta Miller (n\u00e9e Koch), is a modern dancer.<ref name=autogenerated3/> Miller's father, Robert S. Miller, was senior vice president and managing director of [[Hachette Books#Hyperion Books|Hyperion Books]], and later became a publisher at [[Workman Publishing Company|Workman Publishing]].<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.co.uk/cgi/news/release?id=50644 |title=Walt Disney Company To Reorganise Publishing Business: Disney Publishing, Worldwide And Hyperion |publisher=Prnewswire.co.uk |date=1999-04-12 |accessdate=2011-10-25}} and is now the President of Macmillan's newest imprint, Flatiron Books.</ref><ref name=nymg1>{{Cite news|last=Yuan|first=Jada|title=We Need to Talk About Ezra|pages=|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=2012-01-08|url=https://nymag.com/movies/features/ezra-miller-2012-1/|accessdate=2012-01-11}}</ref> Miller's father is [[Jewish]] and Miller's mother, who has German and Dutch ancestry, is from a Christian background.<ref>{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Moran|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/the-diary/meet-the-latest-jewish-superhero-1.448384|title=Meet The Flash, the latest Jewish superhero|work=The Jewish Chronicle|date=November 20, 2017|accessdate=May 5, 2018}}</ref> Miller self-identifies as Jewish and \"spiritual\".<ref name=hrt1>{{Cite news|last=Saar|first=Yuval|title=Ezra's Way (Weekend)|pages=|publisher=[[Haaretz]]|date=2012-01-19|url=http://www.haaretz.co.il/magazine/1.1620442|accessdate=2012-06-01|quote=\"My father is Jewish, my mother is not, but I consider myself entirely Jewish even though according to Jewish law I am not. I encourage everyone to understand that the rules were written before anyone could do DNA tests... I know that I am a descendant of Abraham through my father.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.interfaithfamily.com/arts_and_entertainment/popular_culture/Interfaith_Celebrities_An_Upcoming_Actor_An_Enduring_Celebrity_Interfaith_Marriage_and_Sheriff_Andys_Jewish_Roots.shtml|title=Interfaith Celebrities: An Upcoming Actor, An Enduring Celebrity \u2013 InterfaithFamily|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=reps1>{{Cite news|last=Lamble|first=David|title=Family estrangement|pages=|publisher=The Bay Area Reporter|date=2011-12-08|url=http://www.cpanel.ebar.com/arts/art_article.php?sec=film&article=946|accessdate=2012-01-11}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of six, Miller started to train as an [[opera]] singer, in order to overcome a speech impediment.<ref name = out>{{cite web|author=Shana Naomi Krochmal|url=http://www.out.com/entertainment/movies/2012/08/15/perks-wallflower-ezra-miller-logan-lerman-johnny-simmons?page=0,2|title=Lost & Found|publisher=[[Out Magazine]]|date=2012-08-15|accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref> Miller has sung with the [[Metropolitan Opera]],<ref>{{cite web|last=VanAirsdale|first=S.T.|url=http://www.movieline.com/2010/04/the-verge-ezra-miller.php?page=all|title=The Verge: Ezra Miller|work=[[Movieline]]|date=2010-04-26|accessdate=2011-05-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100503031028/http://www.movieline.com/2010/04/the-verge-ezra-miller.php?page=all|archive-date=2010-05-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> and performed in the American premiere of [[Philip Glass]]'s opera ''White Raven''.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\" /> Miller attended [[Rockland Country Day School]] and [[The Hudson School]], dropping out at age 16<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2014/10/ezra-miller-the-flash-movie-gay/|title=Ezra Miller: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|last=Barbuti|first=Angela|date=2014-10-15|work=Heavy.com|access-date=2018-01-31|language=en-US}}</ref> after the release of the film ''[[Afterschool]]''.<ref name=\"nymg1\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecinemasource.com/blog/interviews/ezra-miller-interview-for-beware-the-gonzo/ |title=Ezra Miller Interview for Beware the Gonzo |publisher=The Cinema Source |date=2011-09-08 |accessdate=2011-10-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928071241/http://www.thecinemasource.com/blog/interviews/ezra-miller-interview-for-beware-the-gonzo/ |archivedate=2011-09-28 }}</ref><ref name=\"dsblse\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/09/18/ezra-miller-on-perks-of-being-a-wallflower-being-bisexual-more.html|title=Ezra Miller on 'Perks of Being a Wallflower,' Being Bisexual & More|newspaper=The Daily Beast|date=2012-09-18|last1=Stern|first1=Marlow}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Ezra Miller at the 2009 Tribeca Film Festival.jpg|thumb|upright|Miller at the 2009 Tribeca Film Festival]]\n\nMiller's start in film began in 2008 with [[Antonio Campos (director)|Antonio Campos]]' ''Afterschool'', in the role of a teenager at a boarding school who accidentally films the drug-related deaths of two classmates, and is then asked to put together a memorial video.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> Miller appeared in ''[[City Island (film)|City Island]]'' (2009), with [[Andy Garc\u00eda]], [[Julianna Margulies]], and [[Steven Strait]], and co-starred in ''[[Beware the Gonzo]]'' and ''[[Every Day (2010 film)|Every Day]]'', both of which premiered at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]]. Miller next appeared in the [[BBC Films]] film ''[[We Need to Talk About Kevin (film)|We Need to Talk About Kevin]]'' (2011), alongside [[Tilda Swinton]] and [[John C. Reilly]], which was adapted and directed by [[Lynne Ramsay]] from American author [[Lionel Shriver]]'s [[We Need to Talk About Kevin|2003 novel of the same name]]. Miller played Damien on the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] hit comedy series ''[[Californication (TV series)|Californication]]''.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news.nsf/story/ezra-miller-cleared-on-drug-charge_1231177 |title=Ezra Miller &#124; Ezra Miller Cleared On Drug Charge |publisher=Contactmusic |date= 2011-07-05|accessdate=2011-10-25}}</ref> Miller appeared on ''[[Royal Pains]]'' as Tucker Bryant for two seasons. In the 2012 [[The Perks of Being a Wallflower (film)|film adaptation]] of the novel ''[[The Perks of Being a Wallflower]]'' Miller played Patrick, alongside [[Logan Lerman]] and [[Emma Watson]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilkinson|first=Amy|url=http://hollywoodcrush.mtv.com/2011/05/19/ezra-miller-perks-of-being-a-wallflower|title=Ezra Miller To Play Patrick In 'Perks of Being a Wallflower'|work=[[MTV]]|date=2011-05-19|accessdate=2011-05-26}}</ref>\n\nMiller has been credited with singing, drumming and percussion on musical recordings by the band Sons of an Illustrious Father,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sonsofanillustriousfather.bandcamp.com/|title=Sons of an Illustrious Father|website=Sons of an Illustrious Father}}</ref> as early as 2011. The band is a trio that features Lilah Larson (vocals, guitar, bass and drums), Josh Aubin (bass, keyboards, guitar, vocals) and Miller.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://azdailysun.com/flaglive/cover_story/fearless-genre-queer-brooklyn-based-trio-sons-of-an-illustrious/article_2aa7e0b5-6c8f-5178-8dfc-25a7643622be.html|title=Fearless & Genre Queer: Brooklyn-based trio Sons of an Illustrious Father offers sanctuary through music|first=Taylor|last=Haynes|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sonsofanillustriousfather.com/|title=Sons of an Illustrious father|website=Sons of an Illustrious Father}}</ref> In 2019, the band released a cover of \"Don't Cha\" by Pussycat Dolls and Miller was seen in its music video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://etcanada.com/news/453362/ezra-miller-covers-the-pussycat-dolls-dont-cha-in-creepy-new-music-video/|title=Ezra Miller Covers The Pussycat Dolls' 'Don't Cha' In Creepy New Music Video|last=Atad|first=Corey|date=16 May 2019|website=ET Canada|access-date=17 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nMiller played Credence Barebone in the 2016 film ''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]'', a spin-off of the [[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'' film series]]. Miller reprised the role in the film's sequel, ''[[Fantastic Beasts: The Crimes of Grindelwald]]'', which was released in November 2018.\n\nMiller portrays [[Flash (Barry Allen)|Barry Allen / The Flash]] in [[Warner Bros.]]' [[DC Comics]] adaptations, first appearing in cameos in ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]'' and ''[[Suicide Squad (film)|Suicide Squad]]'', and continuing the role as one of the leads in ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]''. Miller is set to play the character in the standalone film ''[[Flashpoint (DCEU)|The Flash]]''.<ref name=\"auto\">[https://variety.com/2014/film/news/the-flash-movie-ezra-miller-aquaman-jason-momoa-2018-1201330654 \"''The Flash'' Movie to Star Ezra Miller, Out in 2018\"]. Variety.</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/warner-bros-flash-movie-star-741019|title=Warner Bros.' ''The Flash'' Movie to Star Ezra Miller|author=|date=October 15, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref> Miller attended [[Middle East Film and Comic Con]] in 2018 representing their character in the DC Comics franchise film ''Justice League''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/life-style/celebrity/hollywood/mefcc-2018-ezra-miller-karl-urban-on-keeping-secrets-1.2200790|title=MEFCC 2018: Ezra Miller, Karl Urban on keeping secrets|last=Reporter|first=Marwa Hamad, Senior|date=2018-04-06|work=GulfNews|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref> In 2020, Miller reprised the role of The Flash for a cameo appearance in the [[Arrowverse]] crossover event, ''[[Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)|Crisis on Infinite Earths]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nMiller [[came out]] as [[queer]] in 2012.<ref name =\"Jackman\">{{cite web|author=Josh Jackman|title=Ezra Miller: I have a polyamorous squad of sexual partners|work=[[Pink News]]|date=November 16, 2018|accessdate=March 16, 2020|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/11/16/ezra-miller-polyamorous-sexual-partners/}}</ref> Having expressed an interest in \"kissing boys\" at a young age,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_z_BR0ERa9g|title=Ezra Miller talks about realizing as a kid they liked kissing boys|website=YouTube|publisher=Rosa Gamazo|accessdate=November 18, 2016}}</ref> Miller stated, \"The way I would choose to identify myself wouldn't be gay. I've been attracted mostly to 'shes' but I've been with many people and I'm open to love whatever it can be.\"<ref name=dsblse/> Miller also commented on having \"a lot of really wonderful friends who are of very different sexes and genders. I am very much in love with no one in particular.\"<ref name = out/><ref>{{cite web|author=Lawrence Ferber|url=http://www.nextmagazine.com/content/ezra-miller-says-he-has-had-gay-moments|title=Ezra Miller Says He Has Had Gay Moments|publisher=[[Next Magazine (New York City)|Next Magazine]]|date=2012-01-16|accessdate=2012-05-31|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120904172408/http://www.nextmagazine.com/content/ezra-miller-says-he-has-had-gay-moments|archivedate=2012-09-04}}</ref> \n\nMiller uses [[Singular they|they/them pronouns]], which ''[[GQ|GQ Britain]]'' stated is done \"in a pointed refusal to be gendered\".<ref name=\"GQ Britain\">{{cite news|url=https://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/fashion/article/ezra-miller-interview |title=We're Obsessed With Ezra Miller's Gender Fluid GQ Photo Shoot|work=[[GQ|GQ Britain]] |location=London, UK |publisher=Conde Nast |date=12 March 2020 |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> Miller stated that, for them, ''queer'' means \"I don't identify as a man. I don't identify as a woman. I barely identify as a human.\"<ref name=\"lgbtqnation\">{{cite news |last1=Bollinger |first1=Alex |title=Actor Ezra Miller says they don't identify as a man or a woman |url=https://www.lgbtqnation.com/2018/11/actor-ezra-miller-says-doesnt-identify-man-woman/ |work=LGBTQ Nation |date=November 8, 2018}}</ref> Having used all pronouns interchangeably,<ref>{{cite news |last=Randall |first=Devin |url=http://instinctmagazine.com/post/were-obsessed-ezra-millers-gender-fluid-gq-photo-shoot |title=We're Obsessed With Ezra Miller's Gender Fluid GQ Photo Shoot |work=[[Instinct (magazine)|Instinct]] |location=Burbank, California |publisher=Juki Media |date=November 7, 2018 |accessdate=November 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181114034408/http://instinctmagazine.com/post/were-obsessed-ezra-millers-gender-fluid-gq-photo-shoot |archive-date=November 14, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Miller has also stated that they are \"comfortable with all the pronouns\" and that they \"let he/his/him ride, and that's fine.\"<ref name =\"Jones\">{{cite web|author=Allie Jones|title=Ezra Miller Is the Gender-Bending, Goat-Delivering Hollywood Star of the Future|work=[[GQ]]|date=November 5, 2018|accessdate=March 15, 2020|url=https://www.gq.com/story/ezra-miller-gq-style-cover-story}}</ref> Although Miller has been credited as a [[queer icon]], ''GQ Britain'' stated that they also eschew the term ''queer'', \"as even ''queer'' is a label to them\".<ref name=\"GQ Britain\"/> \n \nMiller revealed having had a personal #[[MeToo]] experience with a Hollywood producer and a director, both unnamed. Miller said, \"They gave me wine and I was underaged. They were like, 'Hey, want to be in our movie about gay revolution?' And I was like, 'No, you guys are monsters.'\" Miller then went on to show support for the #MeToo movement.<ref name=lgbtqnation/>\n\nIn 2010, Miller dated [[Zoe Kravitz]] while they were filming ''[[Beware the Gonzo]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://liverampup.com/entertainment/ezra-miller-gay-girlfriend-boyfriend-dating-ethnicity.html|title=Ezra Miller aka Flash Says 'I'm Queer' Not Gay; Boyfriend & Dating Amid Confusion?|date=May 16, 2019|work=Liverampup.com|access-date=September 8, 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\nOn June 28, 2011, in [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]], while shooting ''The Perks of Being a Wallflower'', Miller was a passenger in a vehicle that was pulled over for a broken brake light, and police discovered 20 grams of [[marijuana]] in their possession.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{cite web|last=Glinow|first=Kiki|url=http://www.popeater.com/2011/06/29/ezra-miller-the-perks-of-being-a-wallflower-marijuana-possession-arrested/|title='Wallflower' Star Ezra Miller Busted for Marijuana Possession|website=|quote=|date=2011-06-29|accessdate=2011-06-29}}</ref> Initially, Miller was charged with drug possession, but the charge was later dropped by a judge. Instead, Miller faced a penalty of $600 for two citations of disorderly conduct.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Miller later commented: \"I don't feel like there's any need to hide the fact that I smoke pot. It's a harmless herbal substance that increases sensory appreciation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/movies/features/ezra-miller-2012-1/index1.html |title=Ezra Miller on Their Roles in ''Another Happy Day'' and ''We Need to Talk About Kevin''|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=2012-01-08 |accessdate=2012-01-11}}</ref>\n\nOn April 1, 2020, in [[Reykjav\u00edk|Reykjavik, Iceland]], Miller was involved in an altercation at a bar which occurred after Miller was confronted by a group of eager fans that caused him to lose his temper. According to a video of the incident, which surfaced on April 5, 2020, Miller grabbed a woman by her throat and threw her to the ground, at which point the video cuts out. A source at the establishment confirmed the seriousness of the altercation and that Miller, angry and upset, was escorted off the premises following the incident.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/ezra-miller-throttling-woman-video-1234571800/|title=Ezra Miller Appears to Choke Woman in Video|last=Ravindran|first=Tim Dams,Manori|last2=Dams|first2=Tim|date=2020-04-06|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06|last3=Ravindran|first3=Manori}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title \n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Afterschool]]''\n| Robert\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[City Island (film)|City Island]]''\n| Vincent \"Vinnie\" Rizzo Jr.\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2010\n| ''[[Beware the Gonzo]]''\n| Eddie \"Gonzo\" Gilman\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Every Day (2010 film)|Every Day]]''\n| Jonah\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2011\n| ''[[Another Happy Day]]''\n| Elliot Hellman\n|\n|-\n| ''Busted Walk''\n| Jay Turner\n| Short film\n|-\n| ''[[We Need to Talk About Kevin (film)|We Need to Talk About Kevin]]''\n| Kevin Khatchadourian\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[The Perks of Being a Wallflower (film)|The Perks of Being a Wallflower]]''\n| Patrick\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Madame Bovary (2014 film)|Madame Bovary]]''\n| Leon Dupuis\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2015\n| ''[[The Stanford Prison Experiment (film)|The Stanford Prison Experiment]]''\n| Daniel Culp / Prisoner 8612\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Trainwreck (film)|Trainwreck]]''\n| Donald\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2016\n| ''[[Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice]]''\n| rowspan=2|[[Flash (Barry Allen)|Barry Allen / The Flash]]\n|\n|-\n|''[[Suicide Squad (film)|Suicide Squad]]''\n| Cameo \n|-\n| ''[[Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them (film)|Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them]]''\n| Credence Barebone\n| \n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]''\n|Barry Allen / The Flash\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n|''[[Fantastic Beasts: The Crimes of Grindelwald]]''\n|Credence Barebone\n|\n|}\n<!-- Do not add movies not in production per [[WP:CRYSTAL]]. They will be removed -->\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2008\n| ''Cakey! The Cake from Outer Space''\n| Bully\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[Californication (TV series)|Californication]]''\n| Damien Patterson\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n| Ethan Morse\n| Episode: \"Crush\"\n|-\n| 2009\u20132010\n| ''[[Royal Pains]]''\n| Tucker Bryant\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Arrow (TV series)|Arrow]]''\n| Barry Allen / The Flash\n| Episode: \"[[Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)|Crisis on Infinite Earths: Part Four]]\" Cameo\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title \n! Voice role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Lego Dimensions]]''\n| Credence Barebone\n|\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2011\n| [[Hamptons International Film Festival|Hamptons International Film Festival for Breakthrough Performer]]\n| ''[[Another Happy Day]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[BIFA Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n| rowspan=2|''[[We Need to Talk About Kevin (film)|We Need to Talk About Kevin]]''\n|rowspan=2 {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=6|[[17th Critics' Choice Awards|2012]]\n| [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Young Performer]]\n|-\n| [[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n| rowspan=8|''[[The Perks of Being a Wallflower (film)|The Perks of Being a Wallflower]]''\n|rowspan=4 {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Hollywood Film Festival|Hollywood Film Festival Spotlight Award]]\n|-\n| [[San Diego Film Critics Society Award for Best Cast]]\n|-\n| [[Santa Barbara International Film Festival|Santa Barbara International Film Festival \u2014 Virtuoso Award]]\n|-\n| [[Detroit Film Critics Society Award for Best Supporting Actor]]\n|rowspan=5 {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|[[2013 MTV Movie Awards|2013]]\n| [[MTV Movie Award for Next Generation|MTV Movie Award for Best Breakthrough Performance]]\n|-\n| [[2013 MTV Movie Awards#Best Musical Moment|MTV Movie Awards for Best Musical Moment]] {{small|(shared with [[Logan Lerman]] and [[Emma Watson]])}}\n|-\n| Phoenix Film Critics Society Award for Best Supporting Actor\n|-\n|2017\n|San Diego Film Critics Society Award for Best Comedic Performance\n|''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q508049|c=Category:Ezra Miller|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|s=no|wikt=no}}\n* {{IMDb name|3009232}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Ezra Miller\n|list =\n{{Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actor}}\n{{Cannes Film Festival Revelation Award}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miller, Ezra}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American drummers]]\n[[Category:American drummers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American child singers]]\n[[Category:American child actors]]\n[[Category:American film actors]]\n[[Category:Models from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:American television actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Jewish American actors]]\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish rock musicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:Actors from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Wyckoff, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Queer actors]]\n[[Category:Queer musicians]]\n[[Category:Singers from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:The Hudson School alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American drummers]]\n[[Category:Non-binary actors]]\n[[Category:Actors of German descent]]\n", "name_user": "AChakra California", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eControversies:corrected pronoun", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ezra_Miller"}
{"title_page": "Dance-rock", "text_new": "{{Infobox music genre <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Music genres -->\n| name              = Dance-rock\n| bgcolor           = crimson\n| color             = white\n| stylistic_origins = {{hlist|[[Post-disco]]|[[pop rock]]|[[post-punk]]|[[ dance music|dance]]|[[rhythm and blues]]}}\n| cultural_origins  = Late 1970s \u2013 early 1980s, United States and United Kingdom\n| instruments       = {{hlist|[[Keyboard instrument|Keyboard]]|[[bass guitar]]|[[electric guitar]]|[[drum machine]]|[[drums]]|[[synthesizer]]|[[electronic drums]]|[[sampler (musical instrument)|sampler]]|[[Music sequencer|sequencer]]|[[vocals]]|[[vocoder]]|[[Talk box|talkbox]]}}\n| popularity        = Mainstream in the 1980s and 1990s\n| derivatives       = {{hlist|[[Alternative dance]]|[[grebo (music)|grebo]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.avclub.com/article/dudes-ludes-15-bands-named-after-drugs-arent-weed-210345 |title=Dudes on 'ludes: 15 bands named after drugs that aren't weed |last=Modell |first=Josh |publisher=[[The A.V. Club]] |access-date=12 April 2017}}</ref>|[[Minneapolis sound]]}}\n| subgenrelist      = \n| subgenres         =\n| fusiongenres      = \n| regional_scenes   = \n| local_scenes      = \n| other_topics      =\n* [[List of dance-rock artists|List of artists]]\n* [[dance-punk]]\n* [[electronic rock]]\n}}\n'''Dance-rock''' is a [[post-disco]] genre connected with [[pop rock]] and [[post-punk]] with fewer [[rhythm and blues]] influences, originated in the early 1980s, following the decline in popularity of [[punk rock|punk]] and [[disco]].<ref name=Bill/>\n\nExamples of early dance-rock include [[Gina X Performance|Gina X]]'s \"No G.D.M.\",<ref>{{cite journal|year=2002|journal=[[The Fader]]|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=Y2-fAAAAMAAJ&q=No+GDM+gina+X++post-disco+++The+Fader&dq=No+GDM+gina+X++post-disco+++The+Fader |title=The Fader, Issues 14-15|quote=[the] classic post-disco track \"No GDM\" by Gina X|page=38|publisher = Fader, Incorporated}}</ref> [[Russ Ballard]]'s \"On The Rebound\",<ref>{{cite web|last1=Erlewine|first1=Stephen Thomas|title=AllMusic Review by Stephen Thomas Erlewine|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/barnet-dogs-mw0000855726|website=AlMusic.com|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> artists such as [[Arthur Russell (musician)|Dinosaur L]], [[Liquid Liquid]] and [[Polyrock]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Fink|first=Robert|year=2005|title=Repeating Ourselves: American Minimal Music As Cultural Practice|url=https://archive.org/details/repeatingourselv0054fink|url-access=registration|publisher=University of California Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/repeatingourselv0054fink/page/26 26]|isbn=978-0-520-24550-1}}</ref> and the compilation album ''[[Disco Not Disco]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r560174|pure_url=yes}} |title=Disco Not Disco (2000)|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2009-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Battaglia|first=Andy|year=2008|publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/11055-disco-not-disco-post-punk-electro-leftfield-disco-classics-1974-1986|title=Album Reviews: ''VA - Disco Not Disco (Post-Punk, Electro & Leftfield Disco Classics)''|accessdate=2009-08-13}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nMichael Campbell, in his book ''Popular Music in America'', defines the genre as \"post-punk/post-disco fusion\". Campbell also cited [[Robert Christgau]], who described dance-oriented rock (or DOR) as an umbrella term used by various DJs in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite book|last=Campbell|first=Michael|year=2008|title=Popular Music in America: And the Beat Goes On|publisher=Cengage Learning|page=359|isbn=978-0-495-50530-3}}</ref>\n\nHowever, [[AllMusic]] defines \"dance-rock\" as 1980s and 1990s music practiced by rock musicians, influenced by [[Philadelphia soul|Philly soul]], disco and funk, fusing those styles with rock and dance. Artists like [[The Rolling Stones]], [[David Bowie]], [[Duran Duran]], [[Simple Minds]], [[INXS]], [[Eurythmics]], [[Depeche Mode]], [[The Clash]], [[New Order (band)|New Order]] and [[Devo]] belong, according to Allmusic, to this genre. Dance-rock embraces some experimental funk acts like [[A Certain Ratio]], [[Gang of Four (band)|Gang of Four]], and also musicians, for example [[Robert Palmer (singer)|Robert Palmer]], [[Billy Idol]] and [[Hall & Oates]]. This kind of dance-rock influenced acts such as [[Garbage (band)|Garbage]], [[No Doubt]], [[Robbie Williams]], [[Scissor Sisters]],<ref name=DanceRock>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=explore|id=style/d13748|pure_url=yes}}|title=Explore music... Genre: Dance-Rock|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=2009-08-12}}</ref> [[Young Love (band)|Young Love]], [[Franz Ferdinand (band)|Franz Ferdinand]], [[Arctic Monkeys]], [[Kasabian]] and [[The Killers]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Paoletta|first=Michael|date=December 25, 2004|journal=Billboard Magazine|title=Music [Dance]: Mash-Ups, Dance-Rock Lead Breakthroughs|page=38|issn=0006-2510}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDespite predictions that rock music would replace disco in the dance clubs, a mix of post-disco, post-punk, and new wave took its place instead. The first wave of artists arrived with [[New Order (band)|New Order]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[The Human League|Human League]], [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]], [[Tom Tom Club]] and [[Devo]], followed by [[Hall & Oates|Daryl Hall & John Oates]], [[Thompson Twins]], [[Haircut One Hundred|Haircut 100]], [[ABC (band)|ABC]], [[Depeche Mode]] and [[Spandau Ballet]].<ref name=Bill>{{cite journal|date=19 Jun 1982|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|title=The Music Steps Beyond Disco: Where The Beat Meets The Street/Danceable Rock Generates First Bevy of Crossover Stars|issue=94|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> The scene also produced a lot of crossovers, including [[Kraftwerk]] getting [[Urban contemporary|R&B]] audiences with their 1981 influential album ''[[Computer World]]'', which paved the way for [[Afrika Bambaataa]]'s \"[[Planet Rock (song)|Planet Rock]]\" and [[electro (music)|electro]] in general. Reinstated interest in dance-rock and post-disco caused popularity of 12-inch singles and EPs around that era.<ref name=Bill/><ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/computer-world-japan-bonus-track-r11204 ''Computer World ''(1981)] by Krafwerk. Review. Allmusic. Rovi Corporation. Retrieved 22-12-2011.</ref>\n\nKey influences of the genre include [[New Romanticism|New Romantic]] [[synthpop]] acts [[Human League]] and [[Spandau Ballet]] while, according to ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', the pivotal record of the genre is Human League's \"[[Don't You Want Me]]\". [[Arthur Baker (musician)|Arthur Baker]] argued that synthesizers helped to shape the new music: \"I'm into synthesizers right now. The options are limitless. It cuts costs and gives you more ultimate control, but it doesn't sound made up. It still has a human feel\", while the sound, composed of electronic [[Euro disco|Eurodisco]] influences, was generally regarded as \"cold, anti-human and mechanical.\"<ref name=Bill/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of dance-rock artists]]\n*[[Alternative dance]]\n*[[Electronic rock]]\n*[[Dance-punk]]\n*[[Electropunk]]\n*[[New wave music]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Boogierock}}\n{{New wave and post-punk}}\n{{Electronic rock}}\n\n[[Category:Dance-rock| ]]\n[[Category:Fusion music genres]]\n[[Category:American styles of music]]\n[[Category:American rock music genres]]\n[[Category:British styles of music]]\n[[Category:British rock music genres]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox music genre <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Music genres -->\n| name              = Dance-rock\n| bgcolor           = crimson\n| color             = white\n| stylistic_origins = {{hlist|[[Post-disco]]|[[pop rock]]|[[post-punk]]|[[Philadelphia soul]]||[[rhythm and blues]]}}\n| cultural_origins  = Late 1970s \u2013 early 1980s, United States and United Kingdom\n| instruments       = {{hlist|[[Keyboard instrument|Keyboard]]|[[bass guitar]]|[[electric guitar]]|[[drum machine]]|[[drums]]|[[synthesizer]]|[[electronic drums]]|[[sampler (musical instrument)|sampler]]|[[Music sequencer|sequencer]]|[[vocals]]|[[vocoder]]|[[Talk box|talkbox]]}}\n| popularity        = Mainstream in the 1980s and 1990s\n| derivatives       = {{hlist|[[Alternative dance]]|[[grebo (music)|grebo]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.avclub.com/article/dudes-ludes-15-bands-named-after-drugs-arent-weed-210345 |title=Dudes on 'ludes: 15 bands named after drugs that aren't weed |last=Modell |first=Josh |publisher=[[The A.V. Club]] |access-date=12 April 2017}}</ref>|[[Minneapolis sound]]}}\n| subgenrelist      = \n| subgenres         =\n| fusiongenres      = \n| regional_scenes   = \n| local_scenes      = \n| other_topics      =\n* [[List of dance-rock artists|List of artists]]\n* [[dance-punk]]\n* [[electronic rock]]\n}}\n'''Dance-rock''' is a [[post-disco]] genre connected with [[pop rock]] and [[post-punk]] with fewer [[rhythm and blues]] influences, originated in the early 1980s, following the decline in popularity of [[punk rock|punk]] and [[disco]].<ref name=Bill/>\n\nExamples of early dance-rock include [[Gina X Performance|Gina X]]'s \"No G.D.M.\",<ref>{{cite journal|year=2002|journal=[[The Fader]]|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=Y2-fAAAAMAAJ&q=No+GDM+gina+X++post-disco+++The+Fader&dq=No+GDM+gina+X++post-disco+++The+Fader |title=The Fader, Issues 14-15|quote=[the] classic post-disco track \"No GDM\" by Gina X|page=38|publisher = Fader, Incorporated}}</ref> [[Russ Ballard]]'s \"On The Rebound\",<ref>{{cite web|last1=Erlewine|first1=Stephen Thomas|title=AllMusic Review by Stephen Thomas Erlewine|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/barnet-dogs-mw0000855726|website=AlMusic.com|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> artists such as [[Arthur Russell (musician)|Dinosaur L]], [[Liquid Liquid]] and [[Polyrock]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Fink|first=Robert|year=2005|title=Repeating Ourselves: American Minimal Music As Cultural Practice|url=https://archive.org/details/repeatingourselv0054fink|url-access=registration|publisher=University of California Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/repeatingourselv0054fink/page/26 26]|isbn=978-0-520-24550-1}}</ref> and the compilation album ''[[Disco Not Disco]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r560174|pure_url=yes}} |title=Disco Not Disco (2000)|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2009-08-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Battaglia|first=Andy|year=2008|publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/11055-disco-not-disco-post-punk-electro-leftfield-disco-classics-1974-1986|title=Album Reviews: ''VA - Disco Not Disco (Post-Punk, Electro & Leftfield Disco Classics)''|accessdate=2009-08-13}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nMichael Campbell, in his book ''Popular Music in America'', defines the genre as \"post-punk/post-disco fusion\". Campbell also cited [[Robert Christgau]], who described dance-oriented rock (or DOR) as an umbrella term used by various DJs in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite book|last=Campbell|first=Michael|year=2008|title=Popular Music in America: And the Beat Goes On|publisher=Cengage Learning|page=359|isbn=978-0-495-50530-3}}</ref>\n\nHowever, [[AllMusic]] defines \"dance-rock\" as 1980s and 1990s music practiced by rock musicians, influenced by [[Philadelphia soul|Philly soul]], disco and funk, fusing those styles with rock and dance. Artists like [[The Rolling Stones]], [[David Bowie]], [[Duran Duran]], [[Simple Minds]], [[INXS]], [[Eurythmics]], [[Depeche Mode]], [[The Clash]], [[New Order (band)|New Order]] and [[Devo]] belong, according to Allmusic, to this genre. Dance-rock embraces some experimental funk acts like [[A Certain Ratio]], [[Gang of Four (band)|Gang of Four]], and also musicians, for example [[Robert Palmer (singer)|Robert Palmer]], [[Billy Idol]] and [[Hall & Oates]]. This kind of dance-rock influenced acts such as [[Garbage (band)|Garbage]], [[No Doubt]], [[Robbie Williams]], [[Scissor Sisters]],<ref name=DanceRock>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=explore|id=style/d13748|pure_url=yes}}|title=Explore music... Genre: Dance-Rock|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=2009-08-12}}</ref> [[Young Love (band)|Young Love]], [[Franz Ferdinand (band)|Franz Ferdinand]], [[Arctic Monkeys]], [[Kasabian]] and [[The Killers]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Paoletta|first=Michael|date=December 25, 2004|journal=Billboard Magazine|title=Music [Dance]: Mash-Ups, Dance-Rock Lead Breakthroughs|page=38|issn=0006-2510}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDespite predictions that rock music would replace disco in the dance clubs, a mix of post-disco, post-punk, and new wave took its place instead. The first wave of artists arrived with [[New Order (band)|New Order]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[The Human League|Human League]], [[Blondie (band)|Blondie]], [[Tom Tom Club]] and [[Devo]], followed by [[Hall & Oates|Daryl Hall & John Oates]], [[Thompson Twins]], [[Haircut One Hundred|Haircut 100]], [[ABC (band)|ABC]], [[Depeche Mode]] and [[Spandau Ballet]].<ref name=Bill>{{cite journal|date=19 Jun 1982|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|title=The Music Steps Beyond Disco: Where The Beat Meets The Street/Danceable Rock Generates First Bevy of Crossover Stars|issue=94|issn=0006-2510}}</ref> The scene also produced a lot of crossovers, including [[Kraftwerk]] getting [[Urban contemporary|R&B]] audiences with their 1981 influential album ''[[Computer World]]'', which paved the way for [[Afrika Bambaataa]]'s \"[[Planet Rock (song)|Planet Rock]]\" and [[electro (music)|electro]] in general. Reinstated interest in dance-rock and post-disco caused popularity of 12-inch singles and EPs around that era.<ref name=Bill/><ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/computer-world-japan-bonus-track-r11204 ''Computer World ''(1981)] by Krafwerk. Review. Allmusic. Rovi Corporation. Retrieved 22-12-2011.</ref>\n\nKey influences of the genre include [[New Romanticism|New Romantic]] [[synthpop]] acts [[Human League]] and [[Spandau Ballet]] while, according to ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', the pivotal record of the genre is Human League's \"[[Don't You Want Me]]\". [[Arthur Baker (musician)|Arthur Baker]] argued that synthesizers helped to shape the new music: \"I'm into synthesizers right now. The options are limitless. It cuts costs and gives you more ultimate control, but it doesn't sound made up. It still has a human feel\", while the sound, composed of electronic [[Euro disco|Eurodisco]] influences, was generally regarded as \"cold, anti-human and mechanical.\"<ref name=Bill/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of dance-rock artists]]\n*[[Alternative dance]]\n*[[Electronic rock]]\n*[[Dance-punk]]\n*[[Electropunk]]\n*[[New wave music]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Boogierock}}\n{{New wave and post-punk}}\n{{Electronic rock}}\n\n[[Category:Dance-rock| ]]\n[[Category:Fusion music genres]]\n[[Category:American styles of music]]\n[[Category:American rock music genres]]\n[[Category:British styles of music]]\n[[Category:British rock music genres]]\n", "name_user": "2600:8804:8840:1460:10a2:eab8:7839:f09d", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dance-rock"}
